{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly (19th century)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly''' is a list of ships which sank on or near the [[Isles of Scilly]]. The list includes ships that sustained a damaged hull, which were later  refloated and repaired.\n[[File:Scilly-bartholomew02 large.jpg|Scilly Isles: map by John Bartholomew|thumb|300px]]\n*For ships wrecked both before and after the 19th century see [[List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly]].\n*For ships wrecked on the [[Seven Stones Reef]] see [[List of shipwrecks of the Seven Stones Reef]].\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==1801\u20131810==\n\n===1801===\n* January &mdash; '''''Thomas and William''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was wrecked in the islands while on a voyage from [[Neath]], [[Glamorgan]], to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=31 January 1801 |page_number=3 |issue=5018 |column=C }}</ref>\n* January &mdash; '''''Melantho''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was wrecked in the islands while on a voyage from London to [[Tortola]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lloyd's List. |newspaper=Morning Post and Gazetteer |date=15 January 1801 |issue=10094 }}</ref>\n* 5 November &mdash; London brig '''''Esperance''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Nut Rock and was a total loss, after parting her cables during a south-west gale. She was bound for [[Venice]] from Penzance with pilchards.<ref name=larn92>{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=The Shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly|year=1992|publisher=Thomas & Lochar|location=[[Nairn]]|isbn=0-946537-84-4}}</ref>\n\n===1804===\n* 30 May &mdash; '''''Quicksilver''''' wrecked in Crow Sound while carrying salt for Newfoundland.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* July &mdash; while bound for London from Waterford '''''The Exchange''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) foundered west of Scilly.<ref name=Todd>{{cite journal|last=Stevens|first=Todd|title=Wrecks not in any island record|journal=Scillonian|date=Summer 2011|issue=273|page=94}}</ref>\n* 5 November &mdash; London brig '''''Esperance''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Nut Rock, and was a total loss, after parting her cables during a south-west gale. She was bound for Venice from Penzance with pilchards.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1806===\n* 10 January &mdash; the '''''Governor Milne''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) while on passage from Grenada to London went ashore on Tresco in New Grimsby harbour. She was later saved.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 November &mdash; [[Prize (law)|prize vessel]] '''''St Francis Apollo''''' went aground and refloated in New Grimsby harbour.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1807===\n*22 November \u2013 The '''''Anne''''', and '''''Tamer''''', two brigs belonging to Mr. Bayley, merchant of Plymouth, just arrived from Lisbon in ballast, and chartered on account of the Government for Cork, to take in provisions for the Plymouth Victualling Office. Sailed from Cork on Saturday 21 November and wrecked in Tresco, Scilly on Sunday.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Plymouth |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000082/18071124/007/0003 |newspaper=Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=23 November 1807 |access-date=26 September 2015|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription   }}</ref>\n\n===1808===\n* 28 November &mdash; schooner '''''Summer''''' ran ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1809===\n*The '''''Ranter''''', Thomas, from Cork to Falmouth and Plymouth, struck a rock in Scilly and sank in 20 fathoms of water. It was later raised and the cargo landed.\n*23 November. The '''''Nymph''''', of and for Pool, William Turner master, from Newfoundland with codfish, was lost on Samson.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Shipwrecks at Scilly, &c. |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000177/18091202/015/0002\n |newspaper=Royal Cornwall Gazette |location=Falmouth |date=2 December 1809 |access-date=26 September 2015|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription  \n }}</ref>\n\n===1810===\n* 27 January &mdash; '''''Perseus''''' wrecked on Samson while en route from [[Martinique]] to London with a cargo of sugar, which was salvaged and sold on St Mary's.<ref name=\"Larn\">{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=Shipwreck Index of the British Isles|year=1997|publisher=Lloyd's Register of Shipping|location=London|author2=Larn, Bridget }}</ref>\n* 31 August &mdash; '''''Amelia''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on [[Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly#Great Crebawethan|Crebawethan]] while carrying coffee, cotton, rum, sugar and silver dollars from [[Demerara]] to London.<ref name=\"Larn\"/>\n* November &mdash; 69 ton sloop '''''Harriet & John''''' came ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1811\u20131820==\n\n===1812===\n* 26 January &mdash; galliot '''''Maria''''' ({{flag|France}}) went ashore at an unknown location and refloated on 14 March.<ref name=larn92/>\n* November &mdash; ketch '''''Dublin'''''  bound for Londonderry from London holed after hitting a ledge while leaving Scilly. The captain refused the offer of a pilot on board.<ref name=Features>{{cite journal|last=Anon|title=Features|journal=Scillonian|date=Summer 2011|issue=273|pages=201\u20132}}</ref>\n\n===1815===\n* 27 January &mdash; West Indiaman, '''''Queen Charlotte''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the [[Norrard Rocks#Scilly Rock|Scilly Rock]] while bound for [[Jamaica]] from [[Greenock]]. One crew member and three passengers died as did two Bryher pilots. The thirteen remaining crew and passengers survived after being stranded on the rock for two days and nights.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 29 October &mdash; the '''''Thais''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Penzance came ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1818===\n* 5 January &mdash; an unidentified [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] was wrecked offshore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1819===\n* 20 March &mdash; [[Fishguard]] sloop '''''Mary''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on the Western Rocks while carrying oats from [[Youghal]]l to [[Southampton]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 21 November &mdash; '''''Mary''''' wrecked at an unknown location within the Isles of Scilly.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1821\u20131830==\n\n===1821===\n* 2 October &mdash; a brig '''''Providencia''''' ({{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}) wrecked on Hellweathers in thick fog. She was heading for Bristol from [[St Andero]] with wool when caught by a north-west gale.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=Noall>{{cite book|last=Noall|first=Cyril|title=Cornish Lights and Ship-Wrecks|year=1968|publisher=D Bradford Barton|location=Truro}}</ref>\n* 3 October &mdash; Bryher boat '''''Hero''''' with 21 men aboard was smashed to pieces by heavy seas while removing the cargo from the ''Providencia''.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> \n* the St Martin's Preventive Service boat capsized with the loss of the four men on board.<ref name=Cooper>{{cite book|last=Cooper|first=Glynis|title=St Martin's the ancient port of Scilly|year=2002|publisher=Historic Occasions|location=Glossop|isbn=1-900006-00-6|page=32|edition=First}}</ref>\n\n===1822===\n* 4 February &mdash; schooner '''''York''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Chichester carrying oranges from Seville to London was lost, in thick fog, with all hands within half-a-mile (0.8 km) of St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"Noall\" />\n\n===1825===\n* 10 September &mdash; schooner '''''La Sidonia''''' went aground and later refloated in New Grimsby Harbour, Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1826===\n* 29 January &mdash; brig '''''John & Ann''''' wrecked on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 7 September &mdash; '''''Fair Ellen''''' went ashore and was saved.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1827===\n* 9 September &mdash;  galliot '''''Twende Sodskende''''' ({{flagcountry|United Kingdom of the Netherlands}}), [[Bilbao]] to [[Copenhagen]], hit the [[Seven Stones Reef]] and sank two miles (3.2 km) off Bryher.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1829===\n* 4 January &mdash; '''''Ocean''''' on Rosevear Ledges.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"McFarland\" />\n\n===1830===\n* 19 January &mdash; the brig '''''Hope''''' with a cargo of peppers, ivory, gold dust and palm oil, dropped anchor and was driven onto the rocks off the north coast of St Martin's after mistaking the daymark for St Agnes lighthouse. The cargo of gold dust and 300 elephant tusks were saved but four people lost their lives when the boat they were trying to escape in was hit by the mainmast.<ref name=\"Noall\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n==1831\u20131840==\n\n===1831===\n* early January &mdash; two Scillonian gigs wrecked.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 27 March &mdash; the '''''Delf''''' went onto rocks in Old Grimsby Harbour.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 March &mdash; '''''Swift''''' en route from Liverpool to Rotterdam grounded on St Helens but managed to get away on the next tide.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1833===\n* January &mdash; the St Martin's pilot boat sank in heavy seas with the loss of all ten men.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 13 February &mdash; sixth-rate '''{{HMS|Forester|1832|6}}''' ({{navy|UK}}) ran aground at Cruther's Point, St Martin during a \u2033...great gale raged over the UK\u2033. She was later refloated.<ref name=\"Larn\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 13 February &mdash; bound for Bombay, the '''''Providence''''' struck a rock and was scuttled two days later in Crow Sound. She was floated off on 6 May.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n=== 1835 ===\n* 29 December &mdash; the '''''Malta''''' struck the Black Rock off St Helen's whilst on voyage from Cardiff to [[Lynmouth]]. All the crew saved. A [[Scheduled Ancient Monument]].<ref>{{PastScape|mname=Malta|mnumber=878655|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 1836 ===\n* 4 February &mdash; '''''Fame''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Exeter carrying pig iron from Newport for Newcastle sank after the loss of her mainmast, boat and bulwarks {{convert|6|league}} south west of St Agnes. The crew of nine were taken off by twenty men in the St Agnes [[Cornish pilot gig|pilot boats]] ''Champion'' and ''Cyclop'' and landed at St Mary's.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scilly |url= http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/feb.html|accessdate= 27 December 2012 |series= 1836 Articles and Other Items |newspaper= West Briton |date= 12 February 1836}}</ref>\n* 27 March &mdash; cutter '''''Prosperous''''' wrecked at an unknown location.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 7 April &mdash; [[Maryport]] brig '''''Bassenthwaite''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank immediately when she struck a partially submerged wreck in Broad Sound during a north-west gale.<ref name=larn92/>\n* April or May &mdash; parts of the balks, beams, masts, etc. have been washed up on many of the islands. They may be from a timber ship from Quebec that sank recently; whereabouts and time unknown.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/may.html|title= 1836 Articles and Other Items |accessdate= 28 December 2012|newspaper=West Briton |date= 6 May 1836}}</ref>\n* 13 October &mdash; St Ives schooner '''''Minerva''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying wool from Spain to Bristol hit the Western Rocks near Crebawathen and sank. Only one member of the crew survived and was picked up from a rock the next morning.<ref name=larn92/><ref name=gorran>{{cite news|title=The Weather|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/oct.html|accessdate=3 January 2013|newspaper=West Briton|date=14 October 1836}}</ref>\n* 12 October &mdash; brig '''''Experiment''''' on her maiden voyage from Newfoundland to Poole with fish and oil was found on 14 October drifting after losing her mast and taking on water. Three of the nine crew survived.<ref name=gorran/>\n* October &mdash; the stern of '''''John Dunlap''''' washed onto the shore at Porth Hellick.<ref name=gorran/>\n\n===1838===\n* 29 May &mdash; barque '''''Osirus''''' ({{flag|France}}) hit the Crim Rocks in an easterly gale.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 November &mdash; barque '''''Pacquebot de Cayenne''''' ({{flag|France}}) sailed into the Hats during a SSE Gale. The crew were saved and most of her cargo of hides, wool and coffee was lost.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1839===\n* 22 February &mdash; 165 ton brig '''''Louisa Hannah''''' wrecked on the Ranneys, half a mile (0.8 km) west of [[Annet, Isles of Scilly|Annet]]. She was carrying wine and oranges from [[Lisbon]] to her home port of [[Poole]]. None of the crew survived.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 April &mdash; [[Plymouth]] schooner '''''Solace''''' en route from [[Lisbon]] struck a shallow reef within the Western Rocks during thick fog. The crew managed to save their personal belongings and she went to pieces the following day in a ground swell.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 September &mdash; brig '''''Theodorick''''' is probably the earliest recorded wreck on the [[Bishop Rock, Isles of Scilly|Bishop Rock]]. She was carrying a general cargo from [[Essaouira|Mogodore]] to [[London]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 6 December &mdash; the '''''St Vincent''''' hit the Chimney Rocks, at the eastern end of [[St Martin's, Isles of Scilly|St Martin's]] and sank.<ref name=\"Cooper\" /> All her crew and 75% of her cargo of barley was salvaged. She was bound for [[Penzance]] from [[Marans, Charente-Maritime|Marans]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1840===\n* 2 February &mdash; brig '''''Lady Louise''''' carrying coffee, from Rio de Janeiro to Cowes and London, attempted to make anchorage while in distress, and in a gale she was driven onto Guthers Bar.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 17 March &mdash; [[Beaumaris]] brig '''''Jane Ellen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck a rock in St Helen's Gap, lost her rudder and went aground on rocks near St Helen's. She was en route to London from [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] with slate. All the crew were saved.<ref name=\"Jane Ellen\">{{PastScape|mname=Jane Ellen|mnumber=878687|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Jane Ellen\"/>\n* 29 December &mdash; [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] schooner '''''Providence''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit the Bartholomew Ledges and was run ashore on St Agnes.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n==1841\u20131850==\n\n===1841===\n[[File:Figurehead of the SS Thames.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Thames in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 4 January &mdash; a paddle steamer, the Dublin steam packet '''[[SS Thames|SS ''Thames'']]''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}), en route from Dublin to London sank in a strong NE gale near Corregan and Rosevear.  Sixty-two of the sixty-four passengers and crew drowned when her Captain mistook the St Agnes light for the Longships and changed course to head north. Pilot gig ''Whale'', the only boat which managed to reach the wreck, saved three women.<ref name=McFarland>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly 1841 to 1880|journal=Scillonian|year=1927|volume=11}}</ref><ref name=Wreck>{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=Wreck & Rescue round the Cornish Coast|publisher=Tor Mark Press|location=Redruth|isbn= 978-0-85025-406-8|page=48|author2=Larn, Bridget }}</ref> Her figurehead is in the Valhalla Museum at [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]].\n* 2 April &mdash; an unidentified schooner was lost on St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* December &mdash; the pilot boat of St Martin's sank and all six crew escaped with their lives.<ref name=\"Features\" />\n\n===1842===\n* 11 February &mdash; brig '''''William Proben''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of South Shields with a cargo of wheat was lost on Meledgan with the loss of all her crew.<ref name=\"Noall\" />\n* 12 October &mdash; the 600-tonne [[paddle steamer]] '''''Brigand''''', a [[packet boat]], en route from [[Liverpool]] to [[St Petersburg]], struck the Bishop's Rock with such force that it stove in two large bow plates. The rocks then acted as a pivot, and she swung round and heeled into the rock portside, crushing the paddle-wheel and box to such an extent that it penetrated the engine room. She drifted over {{convert|spell=in|7|miles}} in two hours, before sinking in {{cvt|90|m}}. All the crew were saved.<ref name=Maginnis>{{cite web |last=Maginnis |first=Clem |title= Around the Rugged Rock |url= http://www.divernet.com/Travel_Features/157098/around_the_rugged_rock.html| publisher= Divernet |accessdate= 9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1843===\n* 28 January &mdash; The English wooden schooner '''''Douro''''' wrecked on Crebawethan with the loss of all her crew while out from Liverpool for Oporto with a cargo of bailed goods, armoury and brass stops (later determined in the 1970s to be horseshoe shaped [[manillas]] or bracelets used as tokens in the slave trade). All her crew was lost and five seamen including the master are buried in St Mary's churchyard.<ref name=\"Noall\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Slave beads shown|newspaper=The Cornishman|date=3 April 2008}}</ref> Subsequent dives in the 1970s provided the evidence she was involved in the slave trade.<ref>Isles of Scilly Underwater Centre; ''Ships and Boats 1840-1850'', English Heritage September 2012.</ref>\n* 3 March &mdash; schooner '''''Anne & Jane''''' hit a rock north of St Agnes while carrying slates from her home port of Caernarvon to Perth. Local pilots received \u00a330 for helping her to safety.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 21 November &mdash; schooner '''''Challenger''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) from [[Surinam]] (or [[Smyrna]] according to Noall), carrying fruit to her home port of London and wrecked either on the Gunners or the Nundeeps. Her crew of eight managed to row to Bryher with only one oar and the whole island was put under [[quarantine]].<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Noall\" />\n* 21 November &mdash;  barque '''''Nickerie''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) struck a rock, during the night, south-west of [[Rosevear, Isles of Scilly|Rosevear]]. She was heading for her home port of [[Rotterdam]] from [[Semarang|Samarang]], [[Jakarta|Batavia]], with coffee and sugar; her captain thought she was in the [[English Channel]]. She got off and struck again ten minutes later, and started to break up with eight men drowning. The eleven remaining men attempted to make a raft but  only two survived when finally rescued from Rosevear. (According to Noall (1968) this wreck occurred on 22 February 1844).\n\n===1844===\n* 22 February &mdash; 600 ton barque '''''Nickerie''''' (or '''''Nichiril''''') ({{flag|Netherlands}}) wrecked on Rosevean while on a voyage from [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to Rotterdam with coffee and sugar. There were two survivors.<ref name=\"Noall\" /> (According to Larn (1992) this wreck occurred on 21 November 1843). \n* 1 May &mdash; '''''Vespa''''' lost on the Woolpack, Garrison, St Mary's.<ref name=\"Todd\"/> '''''Vesper''''' lost in St Mary's Sound.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1845===\n* 1 December &mdash; the 347 ton barque registered in [[North Shields]] '''''John Esdaile''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Gilstone Ledge in the Western Rocks while out of Green Island for London. She was towed into Smith Sound and a week later went to pieces. Her crew was saved and some of her cargo washed up on Annet and St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1846===\n* 4 January &mdash; brig '''''Leonie''''' hit the Bow, off Gugh and was refloated when her masts were cut off to lighten her. She was carrying brandy for Liverpool and the Clyde.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 3 October &mdash; tender '''''Eddystone''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) driven onto Men-a-Vaur whilst leaving Old Grimsby Harbour; her cargo was saved. A Scheduled Ancient Monument<ref name=larn92/><ref>{{PastScape|mname=Eddystone|mnumber=1124293|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n* 7 October &mdash; brigantine '''''Don''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Sunderland grounded on Tresco and refloated.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1848===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0034 - Figurehead of the Palinurus (1833).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Palinurus in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 18 January &mdash; [[Glasgow]] schooner '''''Eagle''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}), out of her home port for [[Charante]] with coal and iron, hit the Crim, then several other rocks and lastly the Bishop before sinking. The crew had a lucky escaped, with the mainyard narrowly missing the longboat as she was launched.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 25 December &mdash; the brig '''''Charlotte''''' ({{flag|Sweden|1844}}) out of Gothenburg for Montevideo with deals and balk timber foundered on Melledgan where the master, mate, two crew and a passenger lost their lives. Ten survivors erected a rough tent on the rock and were rescued the next day.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 December &mdash; seventeen lives were lost when the '''''Palinurus''''' with a cargo including hogsheads of rum was wrecked off White Island, St Martins.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n===1850===\n* 30 October &mdash; in order to save the brig '''''Calliope''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Greece}}) after she hit the Barthomew Ledges, she was put ashore near the Woolpack Battery, St Mary's. She was heading for Falmouth from [[Odessa]] and was sold for \u00a322 10s.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n==1851\u20131860==\n\n===1851===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0023 - Figurehead of the Alessandro il Grande.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Alessandro Il Grande in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 1 January &mdash; 289 ton Neapolitan brig '''''Alessandro II Grande''''' [[File:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg|25px|1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860 flag]] ([[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]) parted her cables and drifted on to Mare Ledges, to the south of Tresco. There was no loss of life. Her figurehead is in the Tresco Abbey Gardens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valhalla \u2013 Alessandro Il Grande 1851|url=http://www.tresco.co.uk/what-to-do/abbey-garden/valhalla_alessandro.aspx|publisher=Tresco Estate|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 September &mdash; storm damaged brig '''''San Giorgio''''' ([[Naples|Neopolitan]]) drifted onto the Crim Rocks, then cleared and partially sank on her side with her crew rescued by the schooner ''Galway''. ''San Giorgio'' drifted out to sea and was found {{convert|60|mi|km}} offshore. She was towed back to Scilly by a schooner and fifteen pilot-cutters with all her cargo of olive oil and wood salvaged. She was repaired on St Mary's and renamed the ''Lion'' of Scilly.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1852===\n* 13 April &mdash; 225 ton barque '''''Mary Hay''''' hit the Steeple Rock on Bream Ledges while entering Broad Sound despite there being a pilot on board. She was on passage from Jamaica to London with a mixed cargo and sank suddenly with thirty men on deck. There was no loss of life and the wreck was sold for \u00a372 along with salvaged ebony, logwood, coconuts and fustic. The day after the wreck 43 puncheons of rum, two casks of lime-juice, 1,170 bags of pimento, and ship stores, gear and clothing were salvaged Her figurehead is in Valhalla on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* a wooden box from East Indiaman '''''Agnes Ewing''''' [[File:Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg|22px]] [[British East India Company]] was washed ashore on Te\u00e4n. She was on passage from Liverpool to Calcutta and nothing more has been heard of the ship.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1853===\n* 27 January &mdash; Brixham schooner '''''Sarah''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank at anchor in St Martin's Flats; she had sprung a leak two days previous while bound with coal from Cardiff to [[Tenerife]] and [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife|Santa Cruz]]. Her cargo and hull was sold three weeks later for \u00a338.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 3 March &mdash; while carrying slate from her home port of Caernarfon to Perth the schooner '''''Anne & Jane''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit a rock north of St Agnes.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 24 March &mdash; cargo ship '''''Sultana''''' ([[File:Admiralty flag of Hamburg.svg|22px]] [[Hamburg]]) was lost on the Nundeeps and her crew drowned. A nameboard was washed ashore near Padstow nearly a month later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 June &mdash;  brig '''''Ambassador''''' ([[File:19th Century Flag of Malta.svg|border|22px]] [[Malta]]) carrying coal from Cardiff to Malta struck the Seven Stones in fine weather at six in the morning and sank. The crew made it into the ship boats and made for the Trinity House light vessel.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1854===\n* 3 January &mdash; brig '''''Advena''''' driven onto Samson in a south-east gale. She was re-floated at high water after her masts were removed.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 26 June &mdash; the [[Cardiff]] [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] '''''Belinda''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sailing from her home port to [[Cork (city)|Cork]] with [[limestone]], hit the Bishop Rock in thick fog.<ref name=Maginnis/> She got off the rock but took in water and foundered nearby; her crew were saved.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1856===\n* 28 August &mdash; [[Liverpool]] full-rigger '''''Custos''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank within ten minutes after hitting the Crim Rocks. She was carrying brandy, rum, gunpowder and soap, most of which was lost.<ref name=larn92/>\n* '''''Chieftain''''' said to be wrecked on the east side of St Martin's at Hard Lewis.<ref name=Gilmore>{{cite web|title=Gilmore Chieftain|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/1949171|publisher=Geograph|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> The figurehead of a highland chieftain in full dress is in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens#Valhalla collection|Valhalla]] on Tresco, although there is no record of a ship named Chieftain in [[Lloyd's Register]], [[HM Customs and Excise]], [[Board of Trade]] or the RNLI at this time. The wreck in deep water by Hard Lewis is most probably ''Gilmore'', wrecked in [[List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly#1866|1866]].<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1857===\n1 June &mdash; the Padstow brig '''''Voluna''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) while in ballast from Falmouth for Quebec went ashore on the south shore of St Agnes during dense fog. The crew managed to get ashore and ''Voluna'' broke up in the surf.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1860===\n* 14 July &mdash; Austrian sailing ship '''''Osvetitel''''' was wrecked in fog on Maiden Bower while sailing from [[Ibrail]] to Falmouth with barley. Her crew and most of her cargo was recovered.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 19 August &mdash; brig '''''Aurora''''' went ashore, in fog, on the Brow-of-Ponds while carrying wheat from Ibrail to Falmouth. Her crew survived but the cargo was lost and the wreck was sold 23 August.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 26 November &mdash; the '''''Empire''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank during a severe gale in North Sound after hitting Peaked Rock.<ref name=larn92 /><ref name=Allsop>{{cite book|last=Allsop|first=Tim|title=Underwater Scilly|year=2009|publisher=Marshfield Underwater Publications|location=Scilly|isbn=9780956187406|author2=Cawthray, Anna }}</ref>\n\n==1861\u20131870==\n\n===1861===\n* 18 February &mdash; schooner '''''Pauline''''' ({{FRA}}) carrying railway iron from [[Ardrossan]] to Rouen was driven onto Crow Bar<ref name=larn92 />\n* 18 February &mdash; the '''''Mentor''''' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]) parted her cables and collided with the brig ''Arthemise'' ({{FRA}}). The crew managed to get on board the '''''Arthemise''''' which was then ran ashore.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 19 March &mdash; 846 ton sailing ship '''''Award''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) on her second voyage and bound from Liverpool for New Orleans, struck rocks {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} off [[Gweal]]. NNW force 8 to 9 winds drove her on to the northern end of Gweal pushing her bow on to land and forming a temporary bridge to the island. After twelve hours the crew of 24 managed to scramble ashore.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valhalla \u2013 Award 1861|url=http://www.tresco.co.uk/what-to-do/abbey-garden/valhalla_award.aspx|publisher=Tresco Estate|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1862===\n* 24 February &mdash; brig '''''Alexandrina''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Cardiff while carrying coal was abandoned during a gale in the roadstead. Scillonian pilots received \u00a397 from the owner for running her aground.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1863===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0027 - Figurehead of the Friar Tuck (1856).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Friar Tuck in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* December &mdash; sailing ship '''''Friar Tuck''''' with a cargo of tea wrecked in a north-west gale on [[Porthloo|Porth Loo]], St Mary's. The crew were landed by the rocket apparatus.<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n\n===1864===\n* 1 May &mdash; while en route from Malaga to St Petersburg with olive oil the '''''Aegir''''' {{flag|Sweden|1844}} of Gelf was wrecked but re-floated on the same day.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1866===\n* 6 February &mdash; barque '''''Hydra''''' wrecked.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 13 February &mdash; schooner '''''Dauphine''''' ({{FRA}}) caught alight two hours from Scilly and her hulk eventually drifted onto St Agnes.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 12 April &mdash; 535 ton barque '''''[[Gilmore (1824 ship)|Gilmore]]''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Southampton wrecked on Hard Lewis, off the east side of St Martin's.<ref name=Gilmore /> She was in ballast from her home port to Quebec and the crew managed to get away in the ship's boats.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1867===\n*19 January \u2013 Paddle steamer '''Vesper''' of Glasgow, built in 1865, gave way amidships about 50 miles off the Isles of Scilly.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fearful Shipwreck off Scilly. Three lives lost |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000180/18670124/024/0005 |newspaper=Royal Cornwall Gazette |location=England |date=24 January 1867 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \n* December &mdash; brigantine '''''Good Intent''''' with a cargo of coal hit the Crim Rocks and sank.<ref name=larn92 /> \n* coal hulk '''''Eliza''''' wrecked. Her figurehead is in the [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eliza|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/1949176|publisher=Geograph|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1869===\n* 16 February &mdash; Schooner '''''Alida''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) of [[Veendam]] sank off White Island, St Martin's en route from Swansea to Taragonna with patent fuel. her crew were pricked up by the pilot gig ''Linnet''.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 6 December &mdash; Brigantine '''''Otto''''' ({{flag|Sweden|1844}}) stranded on Southward Well, after parting her cables and fouling the barque ''Dorothy Thompson''. She was carrying [[Pine tar|Stockholm tar]] from [[Jakobstad]] to Bristol. There was no loss of life and only 36 barrels were saved before she broke up.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1870===\n* 27 January &mdash; Ship '''''Willem Poolman''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) of Rotterdam went on the rocks at Southward Well while en route from Batavia to her home port. Both the ship and her cargo of tin and coffee were saved.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 20 April &mdash; screw steamer '''''{{SS|Sado||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was lost on the ''Brow of the Ponds'' between Crebawthan and Jackyl Rock while heading to Liverpool from Oporto with a general cargo including wood, wine, oranges, thirty head of cattle and eggs. \u2033''Some of the eggs hatched, the breed of fowl proved unsatisfactory and eventually died''\u2033. Three of the bullocks were found by a Sennen boat and landed on Roseveor and a fourth was landed on St Mary's.<ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 28 May &mdash; schooner '''''Frances Jane''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of [[Carrickfergus]] hit the Bartholomew Ledges (and refloated) while carrying salt from [[Runcorn]] to Plymouth.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 21 July &mdash; while bound for Marseilles from Cardiff, the Liverpool steamer '''''Tyne Queen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Men-a-Vaur in fog, was stranded on rocks in St Helen's Pool for an hour before unloading her cargo in New Grimsby.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 7 October &mdash; despite the good visibility during daylight hours and the lightship within sight, the barque '''''{{SS|Nelson||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Seven Stones reef while carrying [[lead|pig lead]] and [[esparto]] to Tyneside. She sank within two minutes and the master and two of the crew lost their lives.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n==1871\u20131880==\n\n===1871===\n[[File:Figurehead from the Salmon.jpg|thumb|Figurehead from the Salmon in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 11 January &mdash; [[Kinsale]] barque '''''Royal Standard''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying oats from her home port to Southampton was driven ashore on Bryher. She was refloated four days later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 15 January \u2013 barque '''''Salmon''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) drifted onto rocks on Tresco.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wreck at Scilly |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000329/18710118/107/0002 |newspaper=Western Morning News |location=England |date=18 January 1871 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \n* 24 June &mdash; iron barque '''{{SS|Il Primo||2}}''' ({{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}) of Bilbao carrying sugar for [[Greenock]] from [[Havana]] hit the Seven Stones reef and quickly sank with the loss of all the crew bar one.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n* 7 July &mdash; the 387 ton barque '''''Belle of the South''''' hit the Perconger Ledge off St Agnes in a heavy rain squall. With a pilot on board she ran for and beached near St Mary's pier where a piece of rock two foot long was found embedded in her hull. She was repaired and continued her journey to [[Algoa Bay]], South Africa with a general cargo.<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 13 October &mdash; schooner '''''Lelia''''' ({{FRA}}) carrying coal from [[Neath]] to Rochelle went aground on the Spanish Ledges but managed to get clear.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 20 December &mdash; all but two of the crew of the Liverpool steamer '''''{{SS|Delaware||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) drowned when she broke down and was driven ashore on Mincarlo.<ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/> Two of the crew escaped in the ships boat which was washed up on White Island (Sampson) and saved by the crew of Byrher gig ''Albion'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1872===\n* 17 February &mdash; Greek brig '''''Telxinoi''''' ([[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|20px|First National Flag of Greece|border]]) wrecked on Crow Bar.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 16 July &mdash; [[PS Earl of Arran (1860)|'''PS ''Earl of Arran''''']] ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) passenger steamer, which travelled between the islands and [[Penzance]] struck the rock St Martin's Neck and beached on Nornour after a passenger, Stephen Woodcock, a pilot-boat crew member though himself not a pilot, talked the Captain into taking an unusual course \u2033... to give the passengers a better view\u2033. The 92 passengers and crew were saved though the Earl was beyond help.<ref name=\"Cooper\" /><ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite book|last=Carter|first=C.|title=The Port of Penzance: a history|year=1998|publisher=Black Dwarf Publications|location=Lydney|isbn=0-9533028-0-6}}</ref>\n* 6 October  &mdash; '''''[[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company|Little Western]]''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on the Wells Reef. She was the second West Cornwall Steam Ship Company ferry to be wrecked in the islands during 1872.<ref name=\"Carter\" />\n* 22 November  &mdash; Italian barque '''''Rosa Tacchini''''' wrecked on the Paper Ledges, near [[Tresco, Isles of Scilly|Tresco]] after her anchors dragged during a severe south-west gale. No one was hurt. The wreck was towed to Carn Near on Tresco where she was broken up.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1873===\n* 1 February &mdash; while sheltering from hurricane-force winds along with fifty other ships the '''''Outalpha''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of London grounded in St Mary's Roads. She was refloated on the following tide and continued her journey from [[Adelaide]] to London with grain.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 15 March &mdash; all the crew were lost when the '''''Elizabeth''''' was wrecked on St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 10 June &mdash; Mousehole sailing lugger '''''Cornish Girl''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank after striking the Round Rock in the Spanish Ledges in fine weather. No lives lost.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1874===\n* 18 January &mdash; the [[Minnehaha (cargo ship)|'''''Minnehaha''''']], cargo ship, bound for Dublin, wrecked on Peninnis Head, St Mary's with the loss of ten lives including the Pilot.<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 10 March &mdash; schooner '''''Ranneys''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of [[Fowey]] struck the Spanish Ledges and refloated.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 22 March &mdash; the upturned hull of the sailing ship '''''James Armstrong''''', with a cargo of mahogany and coconuts, was found between St Martin's and the Seven Stones and towed to St Mary's beach by the ''Queen of the Bay''. The coconuts were inedible!<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 4 April &mdash; '''SS ''Bordelaise''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Liverpool attempted to enter Crow Sound without a Pilot and hit the Hats. She was bound for Oporto, from Newport, with coal and railway iron. Some of her cargo was salvaged.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 13 April &mdash; schooner '''''Edmund''''' wrecked.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 16 April &mdash; '''SS ''Zelda''''', on her maiden voyage, stranded on the Maiden Bower Rock in fog. Her crew and passengers were saved, and some cargo was salvaged by divers. When the wreck was inspected in 1966, it was found that not only had the SS ''Brinkburn'' sunk on top of the ''Zelda'' in 1898, but that evidence of an unknown wooden warship was found beneath it.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stevens|first=Todd|author2=Cummings Ed |title=The Search for the Nancy Wreck|journal=Scillonian|year=2011|issue=272|pages=160\u201362}}</ref><ref>{{PastScape|mname=Zelda|mnumber=858309|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> \n* 20 April &mdash; St Agnes pilot cutter '''''Gem''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) smashed on Perconger after she slipped her moorings.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1875===\n* 7 May &mdash; ocean liner '''''{{SS|Schiller||2}}''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) on a journey from [[New York City]] to [[Hamburg]], wrecked on the Retarrier Ledges with the loss of 335 people.<ref>{{cite book |author=Austin, Keith |date=2001 |title=The Victorian Titanic: The Loss of the SS Schiller in 1875 |publisher=Halsgrove |isbn=1-84114-133-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Museum News|url=http://www.scillyonline.co.uk/sutd/120/pages/museum.html|accessdate=2 November 2011|newspaper=Scilly Up To Date|date=April 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008071820/http://www.scillyonline.co.uk/sutd/120/pages/museum.html|archive-date=8 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 11 August &mdash; barque '''''Cactus''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) on passage from [[Tripoli]] to Cardiff with [[Esparto|esparto grass]] struck the Northern Rocks. With pilots on board, she was deliberately run onto Samson the next day and taken to Hugh Town on the 13th.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 26 August &mdash; ([[Genoa]]) barque '''''Gloria''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) hit the Crim Rocks. Assisted to St Mary's by the ''Lady of the Isles'', her cargo of ore and grass from Pomeron was saved.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 1 November &mdash; on her [[maiden voyage]] to Rio de Janeiro with coal, the three\u2013masted brigantine '''''Catherine Griffiths''''' sank in thick fog with the loss of eight of her nine crew. Giovanni Carstulovich managed to reach the shore at Troy Town.<ref name=Noall />\n* 2 November &mdash; steamer '''''Aksai''''' ({{flagcountry|Russian Empire}}) sailed into [[White Island, Isles of Scilly|White Island]], St Martin's in thick fog while bound for [[Odessa]] from Cardiff with coal. The captain and crew of thirty-nine were saved by the [[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company#Lady of the Isles|''Lady of the Isles'']].<ref name=larn92 />\n* 23 November &mdash; 452 ton '''''Foscolo''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) of [[Naples]] struck the Seven Stone Reef while bound from [[Montevideo]] for [[Dundee]] with scrap iron and bones. She managed to reach Crow Bar and sank in the shallows. She was later salvaged and raised.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1876===\n* 17 February &mdash; the '''''Linn Fern''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Glasgow wrecked in Crow Sound<ref name=larn92/>\n* British barque '''''Bordelaise''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) with a cargo of \u2033railway iron\u2033 lost on The Hats; see 1874 above.<ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref name=McFarland3>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F M|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly (Conclusion)|journal=[[Scillonian (magazine)|Scillonian]]|date=March 1928|volume=4|issue=13|pages=18\u201322}}</ref>\n\n===1877===\n* schooner '''{{SS|Ethel||2}}''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Seven Stones reef but sustained little damage and headed for Plymouth. Her captain and mate had their certificates withdrawn.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1878===\n* 23 July &mdash; Out of [[Seville]], '''''Ranneys''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) ran aground off St Mary's while awaiting orders. After 24 hours she refloated with the loss of her [[Anchor#Kedging|kedge anchor]] and [[hawser]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Our Ships and our Sailors|work=The Cornishman|issue=4|date=8 August 1878|page=8}}</ref>\n* 10 October &mdash; [[Aberystwyth]] schooner '''''Integrity''''' (or '''''Integrite''''') ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) lost her foremast and longboat in heavy seas off the Bishop Rock. Carrying lime phosphates from Lisbon to Wicklow she found it impossible to manoeuvre in Smith Sound and drifted around Annet before being beached in Perconger, St Agnes. One of the four crew was swept overboard and drowned. Two days later she was refloated and taken to St Mary's.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 23 October &mdash; '''''{{SS|Ely Rise||2}}''''' ({{flag|France}}) carrying \u2033patent fuel\u2033 struck rocks near The Hats in Crow Sound. She was refloated and repaired and was subject to a [[Marine salvage|salvage]] claim by the [[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company]].<ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Salvage Action by the West Cornwall Steamship Company|work=The Cornishman|issue=28|date=30 January 1879|page=6}}</ref>\n* 31 December &mdash; brigantine '''''Minerve''''' ({{flag|France}}) driven onto rocks between Wrass and Morning Point. All the crew, bar one who swam to safety, were saved by the rocket apparatus.<ref name=\"McFarland\" />\n\n===1879===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0009 - Figurehead of the River Lune.jpg|thumb|FIgurehead of the '''River Lune''' in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* January &mdash; Liverpool barque '''''Bertha''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was abandoned, off the islands, after a collision with ''J Brown'' which headed for Queenstown with the crew of the abandoned ship. ''Bertha'' foundered shortly after.<ref>{{cite news|title=Collision off Scilly|work=The Cornishman|issue=28|date=30 January 1879|page=6}}</ref>\n* 6 January &mdash; the brigantine '''''Gerhardine''''' was abandoned by her crew approximately {{convert|30|miles}} south of St Agnes. She was towed into St Mary's by ''Gladiator''. The crew were landed at [[Le Havre]] on 16 January.<ref>{{cite news |title= Rescue of an Abandoned Vessel |work= The Cornishman |issue=28 |date= 23 January 1879 |page=5}}</ref>\n* 24 March &mdash; on her maiden voyage, the 215 ton barquentine '''''Tabasco''''', carrying bottled beer and coal from Greenock struck White Island, St Martin's. Her master mistook the Seven Stones lightship for Trevose Head.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 27 July &mdash; Liverpool barque '''''Maipu''''' was wrecked in Hell Bay on Bryher. She was bound for Hamburg from [[Iquique]] with a cargo of [[Sodium nitrate|saltpetre]].<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 27 July &mdash; barque '''''River Lune''''' in ballast from [[Lorient]] to [[Ardrossan]] was lost on Brothers Rock in Muncoy Neck, the channel between Annet and Melledgan, after a faulty chronometer put her off course. She sank in ten minutes, but the crew escaped.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> The wreck was sold on 13 August 1879 for \u00a310 to Messrs Banfield and Son.<ref>{{cite news |title= Isles of Scilly |work=The Cornishman |issue=58 |date= 21 August 1879 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n===1880===\n* the St Martin's cutter '''''Queen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) grounded on Par Beach, St Martin's and wrecked.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 23 October \u2013 the coal schooner '''''Argo''''' wrecked on [[Te\u00e4n]] while on passage from Newport to [[Polruan]]. All the crew of eight managed to get ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 28 October \u2013 the 194 tons gross wooden brig '''''Messenger''''' of Salcombe dragged onto Skirt Island while carrying coal from Cardiff to Portsmouth. She refloated after St. Mary's lifeboat (''Henry Dundas'') had saved five of her crew but was later scrapped.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1881\u20131890==\n\n===1881===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum FHD0003 - Figurehead of the Independenzia (1875).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Independenzia in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* January &mdash; the barque '''''Saint Jean''''' ({{flag|France}}) sank, with the loss of three men, after colliding with the barque ''Privateer''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The French barque|work=The Cornishman|issue=131|date=13 January 1881|page=3}}</ref>\n* 18 January &mdash; the wooden hulled brigantine '''''Charlotte Dunbar''''' was found ashore and abandoned on Burnt Island, St Agnes. She was sailing from Newport to [[Audierne]] with coal and nothing was heard of her crew of six.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 8 February &mdash; the brigantine '''''Kron Prinz von Preussen''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) was driven ashore in [[New Grimsby|New Grimsby harbour]], Tresco.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Stranding Of A Ship|work=The Cornishman|issue=137|date=24 February 1881|page=7}}</ref>\n* 7 May &mdash; the '''''SS Culmore''''' with a cargo of onions, peppers and oranges hit the Crim.<ref name=McFarland2>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly 1881 to 1900|journal=Scillonian|date=December 1927|volume=4|issue=12|pages=402\u20135}}</ref> The captain and three of the crew lost their lives.<ref>{{cite news|title=Loss Of The Steamer Culmore, Near The Bishop Rock Lighthouse, And Of Her Captain And Three Others.|work=The Cornishman|issue=148|date=12 May 1881|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Loss Of A Fine Barque And Her Cargo Of Guano Among The Islands Of Scilly In A Fog|work=The Cornishman|issue=168|date=29 September 1881|page=6}}</ref>\n* 24 September \u2013 the barque '''''Independenzia''''' was carrying a cargo of guano and horn from [[Valpara\u00edso|Valparaiso]], Chile, when she struck the [[Crim Rocks]] and later sank on the Barrel of Butter rock on [[St Mary's, Isles of Scilly#The Garrison and Star Castle|The Garrison]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fearful Shipwreck off Scilly. Three lives lost |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000289/18810927/012/0003 |newspaper=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette |location=England |date=27 September 1881 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n* 21 November &mdash; the small steamer '''''Gem''''' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) broke from her moorings in St Mary's Pool, and went ashore at William's Bay, becoming a total wreck. ''Gem''  taking on coal and was bound for South Africa for employment as a river boat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wreck of a steamer at Scilly=The Cornishman|issue=176|date=24 November 1881|page=5}}</ref>\n* 27 November &mdash; the '''''Excelsior''''' ({{Flag|German Empire}}) of Hamburg grounded on Crow Bar and consequently beached on the south-west corner of Higher Town Bay, St Martin's. She had left Rangoon on 7 June and was carrying 915 tons of rice, rattan and teak. Two months later on 22 January she was towed towards St Mary's by the ''Queen of the Bay'' and ''Lady of the Isles'' and after 30 minutes sank (see also 1882).<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n===1882===\n* 22 January &mdash; the '''''Excelsior''''' sank off St Martin's after repairs on a St Martin's beach (see 1881).<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 24 April &mdash; London barge '''''St Vincent''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank on Toll Island, near Pelistry, St Mary's after striking the Spanish Ledges. She was en route from [[Saint Vincent (island)|St Vincent]] for London with sugar. The crew escaped, but there was much embarrassment as she was carrying a St Agnes pilot.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 December &mdash; the steamer '''''Raglan''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank, after being hit by a Greek steamer and her boiler exploding. The crew were picked up by the Greek steamer.<ref>{{cite news |title=The steamer ''Raglan'' |work=The Cornishman |issue=231 |date=14 December 1882 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n===1883===\n* 9 February &mdash; '''''Criccieth Castle''''' lost on Porthcress Beach.<ref name=\"McFarland3\" />\n\n===1885===\n* 8 June &mdash; '''''Earl of Lonsdale''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Newcastle, carrying cotton seed from Alexandria to [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], was wrecked in Smith Sound, off the Troy Town maze, St Agnes in thick fog.<ref name=Noall/><ref>{{cite book|last=Ratcliffe|first=J|title=The Archaeology of Scilly|year=1989|publisher=Cornwall Archaeological Unit|location=Truro}}</ref> The master had thought his ship was to the west of, and {{cvt|10|miles}} south of, the Bishop Rock.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 17 December &mdash; cargo ship SS '''''Sussex''''' struck Seal Rock, near the Maiden Bower after being caught in heavy fog, while travelling at normal cruising speed. The crew escaped and she broke up during the night of 4\u20135 January in heavy seas.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 30 December &mdash; a local cutter capsized off Yellow Ledges with the loss of one life, while on its way to the steamer ''Sussex'', which struck Seal Rock on 17 December.\n\n===1886===\n* 26 March &mdash; Brigantine '''''Nellie'''''({{flag|Denmark}}) of [[Elsinore]] had been in collision to the west of Scilly and was driven before a south-westerly gale onto the Western Rocks where she first struck Jackys Rock. Part of the vessel drifted onto Annet and the remainder into St Warna's Cove on St Agnes. She was on passage from Bordeaux to Cardiff with pit props under the command of Capt M L Svendsen who lost his life along his chief officer. Two of the crew were saved after clinging to the wreck for sixteen hours and four were picked up from Melledgan where they quenched their thirst with [[puffin|puffins']] blood.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1887===\n* 12 January &mdash; Caernarvon schooner '''''Bolina''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying slate from [[Portmadoc]] to London sank off the south coast of Gugh during an easterly gale.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 8 June &mdash; the SS '''''Castleford''''' struck the [[Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly|Crebawethans]] and led to some of her cargo of 250 to 450 cattle being landed on [[Annet, Isles of Scilly|Annet]] and staying there for up to ten days.<ref>Gurney (1889) \"Notes on the Isles of Scilly and the Manx Shearwater (''Puffinus anglorum'')\"; ''Transactions of the Norfolk and Norwich Naturalists' Society''. In: Parslow, R. (2007) ''The Isles of Scilly''. London: HarperCollins</ref>\n\n===1888===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0053 - Figurehead of the Bernardo.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Bernardo in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 15 January &mdash; the 332 ton barque '''''Gauloise''''' ({{Flag|France}}) of Bordeaux sailed onto Great Arthur Island on the northern edge of Crow Sound. She was carrying pitprops for Porthcawl and heading NNE when fog came down {{convert|14|miles}} south of St Agnes light.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 11 March &mdash; while in ballast, the barque '''''Bernardo''''' ({{Flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) of Genoa lost her sails in a west-north-west gale and was blown ashore on the back of Annet. The captain was rescued from Old Woman Rock by St Agnes fisherman after the ship broke up around him. Eleven of the crew were drowned in the ship's boat when it capsized.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> Her figurehead, apparently [[Bernard of Clairvaux|St Bernard of Clairvaux]], is in Valhalla on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 7 May &mdash; London steamer '''''Egyptian Monarch''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) on passage from New York to her home port with a general cargo including cattle, and passengers, stranded near Bryher. She managed to refloat and made Falmouth the same day with one compartment full of water.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 9 August &mdash; no one on the islands knew that the steamer '''''Gomes V''''' ({{Flag|Portugal|1830}}) had foundered until a St Martin's pilot boat picked up nineteen crew and one passenger drifting eastwards past Hanjaque in two of the ships boats. She was carrying coal to Oporto from Cardiff and struck the Shag Rock in dense fog.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1889===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0045 - Figurehead from the Jane Owen.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Jane Owen in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 3 March &mdash; '''''Jane Owen''''' wrecked on Crow Bar.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n==1891\u20131900==\n\n===1891===\n* 19 February &mdash; steamer '''''Trignac''''' ({{Flag|France}}) sprang a leak, blew up and sank within five minutes, between the Islands and the Seven Stones Reef. She was carrying coal from Newport to [[Saint-Nazaire|St Nazaire]].<ref name=larn92/>\n* 10 March &mdash; 34 ton smack '''''Porth''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Padstow ran ashore on the Minmanueth Rocks on the western coast of Annet. She was heading for [[St Columb Minor]] with [[Culm (coal)|culm]] from Swansea when she was caught in the \u2033[[Great Blizzard of 1891]]\u2033. St Agnes lifeboat ''James & Caroline'' rescued the master and his son, but the third crew member was found frozen.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 March &mdash; barque '''''Megellan''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) foundered in the approaches to the English Channel at lat 47.48 N long 6.53 W. The crew were picked up and taken to Falmouth.<ref name=1891blizard>{{cite book|last=Anon|title=The Blizzard in the West|year=1891|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall, Hamilton, Kent and Co., Limited|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/blizzardinwestbe00londiala#page/n0/mode/2up}}</ref>\n* 11 November &mdash; Padstow schooner '''''J K A''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on Shag Rocks near the Mouls; she broke free and foundered. Her crew abandoned ship and landed on [[Eastern Isles#Great Innisvouls and Little Innisvouls|Great Innisvouls]] where they were rescued by a gig from St Martin's.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1892===\n* 6 February &mdash; '''''Embiricos''''' of [[Andros]] hit either John Thomas or Deep Ledge, St Martin's in heavy rain. She was bound for Malta and Odessa with coal from Cardiff. The captain and five others lost their lives when attempting to launch a boat. Twenty-eight hours four of her crew in a second boat were picked up off the Lizard by steamer ''Rutland'' and landed at Le Havre.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1893===\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 144983 Horsa (ship).jpg|thumb|''Horsa'' shipwreck]]\n* February &mdash; a Truro schooner, '''''John and Mary''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was found ashore on Samson after she collided with a Greek  brig in St Mary's Roads. She was later towed to New Grimsby.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 April &mdash; full\u2013rigger '''''Horsa''''' with a cargo of oats and wool from New Zealand grounded in Bread and Cheese Cove on St Martin's. She later capsized {{convert|spell=in |21|miles}} south-west of the Bishop Rock, while being towed; there were no deaths.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref>Noall, C. (1969?) ''Cornish Shipwrecks Illustrated''. Truro: Tor Mark Press; p. 20</ref>\n* 24 November &mdash; the SS '''''Serica''''' nearly foundered and took shelter in St Mary's Roads on the 19th. As she left she struck an uncharted rock (later named Serica Rock) and sank.<ref>''The Cornishman''. 18 January 1894. p. 8.</ref>\n\n===1896===\n[[File:Anchor from the Sophie.jpg|thumb|Anchor from the Sophie in the Flying Boat Club, Tresco]]\n* 14 December &mdash; '''''Sophie''''' ({{Flag|Norway|1844}}) of Fredrikstadt started to disintegrate and was abandoned along with her cargo of anthracite from Cardiff. She was towed into New Grimsby by the ''Lady of the Isles'' and sold to [[Thomas Algernon Smith-Dorrien-Smith|Algernon Dorrien Smith]] who used her timbers around the Tresco estate and her cargo to heat his greenhouses.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1898===\n* 26 May &mdash; Newlyn fishing lugger '''''Nyanza''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was run ashore on Great Crebawethan after hitting the Crims and springing a leak. St Agnes lifeboat, ''James and Caroline'' took off four of the crew and the fifth was saved by an island boat.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 20 August &mdash; 2,843 ton Sunderland steamer '''''Toledo''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit Steeple Rock and ripped open her hull. Her crew managed to lower the ship's boats and escape before she sank in twenty-five fathoms.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 15 December &mdash; 3,229 ton steamship '''''Brinkburn''''' struck the Maiden Bower in fog and sank, while bound for Le Havre from Galveston with cotton and cotton seed. Her crew of mainly [[lascar]]s survived. An inspection of the wreck in 1966, found beneath her two other ships, one the ''Sussex'' which sank in 1885 and an unknown warship.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1899===\n* 12 February &mdash; 76-ton wooden brigantine '''''Bohallard''''' ({{flag|France}}) of Nantes broke her cables during a WNW hurricane-force gale and drifted onto Pendrathen. She later floated clear and was wrecked in Higher Town Bay, where she broke up two days later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 7 June &mdash; [[Liverpool & Glasgow Salvage Association#Liverpool Salvage Association|Liverpool Salvage Association's]] steamer '''''Ranger''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) grounded on Crow Bar and was refloated the same day.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 25 October &mdash; while carrying rice from Bangkok to [[Bremen]], the [[Rickmers Group|Rickmer Line, full-rigged ship]], '''''Erik Rickmers''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) of [[Bremerhaven]] went ashore on Scilly Rock. She later sank in deep water.<ref name=larn92/> Her crew of twenty-six took to the boats and landed on Bryher.<ref name=\"living memories\">{{cite magazine|title=Living Memories|work=The Islander|date=Spring 2009|pages=18\u201321}}</ref>\n* 26 October &mdash; barque '''''Parame''''' ({{flag|France}}) hit Scilly Rock, her crew of ten landed on Bryher. Her cargo of coconuts was salvaged.<ref name=\"living memories\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [[List of shipwrecks]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of Cornwall]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of the Seven Stones Reef]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* See further literature and details: [http://www.shipwrecks.uk.com Shipwrecks UK]\n\n{{Isles of Scilly}}\n{{Sailing Vessels and Rigs}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks of the United Kingdom|Scilly]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly| List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly]]\n[[Category:Isles of Scilly-related lists|Shipwrecks]]\n[[Category:19th century in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:19th-century maritime incidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly''' is a list of ships which sank on or near the [[Isles of Scilly]]. The list includes ships that sustained a damaged hull, which were later  refloated and repaired.\n[[File:Scilly-bartholomew02 large.jpg|Scilly Isles: map by John Bartholomew|thumb|300px]]\n*For ships wrecked both before and after the 19th century see [[List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly]].\n*For ships wrecked on the [[Seven Stones Reef]] see [[List of shipwrecks of the Seven Stones Reef]].\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==1801\u20131810==\n\n===1801===\n* January &mdash; '''''Thomas and William''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was wrecked in the islands while on a voyage from [[Neath]], [[Glamorgan]], to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=31 January 1801 |page_number=3 |issue=5018 |column=C }}</ref>\n* January &mdash; '''''Melantho''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was wrecked in the islands while on a voyage from London to [[Tortola]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lloyd's List. |newspaper=Morning Post and Gazetteer |date=15 January 1801 |issue=10094 }}</ref>\n* 5 November &mdash; London brig '''''Esperance''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Nut Rock and was a total loss, after parting her cables during a south-west gale. She was bound for [[Venice]] from Penzance with pilchards.<ref name=larn92>{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=The Shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly|year=1992|publisher=Thomas & Lochar|location=[[Nairn]]|isbn=0-946537-84-4}}</ref>\n\n===1804===\n* 30 May &mdash; '''''Quicksilver''''' wrecked in Crow Sound while carrying salt for Newfoundland.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* July &mdash; while bound for London from Waterford '''''The Exchange''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) foundered west of Scilly.<ref name=Todd>{{cite journal|last=Stevens|first=Todd|title=Wrecks not in any island record|journal=Scillonian|date=Summer 2011|issue=273|page=94}}</ref>\n* 5 November &mdash; London brig '''''Esperance''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Nut Rock, and was a total loss, after parting her cables during a south-west gale. She was bound for Venice from Penzance with pilchards.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1806===\n* 10 January &mdash; the '''''Governor Milne''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) while on passage from Grenada to London went ashore on Tresco in New Grimsby harbour. She was later saved.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 November &mdash; [[Prize (law)|prize vessel]] '''''St Francis Apollo''''' went aground and refloated in New Grimsby harbour.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1807===\n*22 November \u2013 The '''''Anne''''', and '''''Tamer''''', two brigs belonging to Mr. Bayley, merchant of Plymouth, just arrived from Lisbon in ballast, and chartered on account of the Government for Cork, to take in provisions for the Plymouth Victualling Office. Sailed from Cork on Saturday 21 November and wrecked in Tresco, Scilly on Sunday.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Plymouth |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000082/18071124/007/0003 |newspaper=Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=23 November 1807 |access-date=26 September 2015|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription   }}</ref>\n\n===1808===\n* 28 November &mdash; schooner '''''Summer''''' ran ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1809===\n*The '''''Ranter''''', Thomas, from Cork to Falmouth and Plymouth, struck a rock in Scilly and sank in 20 fathoms of water. It was later raised and the cargo landed.\n*23 November. The '''''Nymph''''', of and for Pool, William Turner master, from Newfoundland with codfish, was lost on Samson.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Shipwrecks at Scilly, &c. |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000177/18091202/015/0002\n |newspaper=Royal Cornwall Gazette |location=Falmouth |date=2 December 1809 |access-date=26 September 2015|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription  \n }}</ref>\n\n===1810===\n* 27 January &mdash; '''''Perseus''''' wrecked on Samson while en route from [[Martinique]] to London with a cargo of sugar, which was salvaged and sold on St Mary's.<ref name=\"Larn\">{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=Shipwreck Index of the British Isles|year=1997|publisher=Lloyd's Register of Shipping|location=London|author2=Larn, Bridget }}</ref>\n* 31 August &mdash; '''''Amelia''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on [[Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly#Great Crebawethan|Crebawethan]] while carrying coffee, cotton, rum, sugar and silver dollars from [[Demerara]] to London.<ref name=\"Larn\"/>\n* November &mdash; 69 ton sloop '''''Harriet & John''''' came ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1811\u20131820==\n\n===1812===\n* 26 January &mdash; galliot '''''Maria''''' ({{flag|France}}) went ashore at an unknown location and refloated on 14 March.<ref name=larn92/>\n* November &mdash; ketch '''''Dublin'''''  bound for Londonderry from London holed after hitting a ledge while leaving Scilly. The captain refused the offer of a pilot on board.<ref name=Features>{{cite journal|last=Anon|title=Features|journal=Scillonian|date=Summer 2011|issue=273|pages=201\u20132}}</ref>\n\n===1815===\n* 27 January &mdash; West Indiaman, '''''Queen Charlotte''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the [[Norrard Rocks#Scilly Rock|Scilly Rock]] while bound for [[Jamaica]] from [[Greenock]]. One crew member and three passengers died as did two Bryher pilots. The thirteen remaining crew and passengers survived after being stranded on the rock for two days and nights.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 29 October &mdash; the '''''Thais''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Penzance came ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1818===\n* 5 January &mdash; an unidentified [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] was wrecked offshore.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1819===\n* 20 March &mdash; [[Fishguard]] sloop '''''Mary''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on the Western Rocks while carrying oats from [[Youghal]]l to [[Southampton]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 21 November &mdash; '''''Mary''''' wrecked at an unknown location within the Isles of Scilly.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1821\u20131830==\n\n===1821===\n* 2 October &mdash; a brig '''''Providencia''''' ({{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}) wrecked on Hellweathers in thick fog. She was heading for Bristol from [[St Andero]] with wool when caught by a north-west gale.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=Noall>{{cite book|last=Noall|first=Cyril|title=Cornish Lights and Ship-Wrecks|year=1968|publisher=D Bradford Barton|location=Truro}}</ref>\n* 3 October &mdash; Bryher boat '''''Hero''''' with 21 men aboard was smashed to pieces by heavy seas while removing the cargo from the ''Providencia''.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> \n* the St Martin's Preventive Service boat capsized with the loss of the four men on board.<ref name=Cooper>{{cite book|last=Cooper|first=Glynis|title=St Martin's the ancient port of Scilly|year=2002|publisher=Historic Occasions|location=Glossop|isbn=1-900006-00-6|page=32|edition=First}}</ref>\n\n===1822===\n* 4 February &mdash; schooner '''''York''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Chichester carrying oranges from Seville to London was lost, in thick fog, with all hands within half-a-mile (0.8 km) of St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"Noall\" />\n\n===1825===\n* 10 September &mdash; schooner '''''La Sidonia''''' went aground and later refloated in New Grimsby Harbour, Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1826===\n* 29 January &mdash; brig '''''John & Ann''''' wrecked on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 7 September &mdash; '''''Fair Ellen''''' went ashore and was saved.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1827===\n* 9 September &mdash;  galliot '''''Twende Sodskende''''' ({{flagcountry|United Kingdom of the Netherlands}}), [[Bilbao]] to [[Copenhagen]], hit the [[Seven Stones Reef]] and sank two miles (3.2 km) off Bryher.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1829===\n* 4 January &mdash; '''''Ocean''''' on Rosevear Ledges.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"McFarland\" />\n\n===1830===\n* 19 January &mdash; the brig '''''Hope''''' with a cargo of peppers, ivory, gold dust and palm oil, dropped anchor and was driven onto the rocks off the north coast of St Martin's after mistaking the daymark for St Agnes lighthouse. The cargo of gold dust and 300 elephant tusks were saved but four people lost their lives when the boat they were trying to escape in was hit by the mainmast.<ref name=\"Noall\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n==1831\u20131840==\n\n===1831===\n* early January &mdash; two Scillonian gigs wrecked.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 27 March &mdash; the '''''Delf''''' went onto rocks in Old Grimsby Harbour.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 March &mdash; '''''Swift''''' en route from Liverpool to Rotterdam grounded on St Helens but managed to get away on the next tide.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1833===\n* January &mdash; the St Martin's pilot boat sank in heavy seas with the loss of all ten men.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 13 February &mdash; sixth-rate '''{{HMS|Forester|1832|6}}''' ({{navy|UK}}) ran aground at Cruther's Point, St Martin during a \u2033...great gale raged over the UK\u2033. She was later refloated.<ref name=\"Larn\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 13 February &mdash; bound for Bombay, the '''''Providence''''' struck a rock and was scuttled two days later in Crow Sound. She was floated off on 6 May.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n=== 1835 ===\n* 29 December &mdash; the '''''Malta''''' struck the Black Rock off St Helen's whilst on voyage from Cardiff to [[Lynmouth]]. All the crew saved. A [[Scheduled Ancient Monument]].<ref>{{PastScape|mname=Malta|mnumber=878655|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 1836 ===\n* 4 February &mdash; '''''Fame''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Exeter carrying pig iron from Newport for Newcastle sank after the loss of her mainmast, boat and bulwarks {{convert|6|league}} south west of St Agnes. The crew of nine were taken off by twenty men in the St Agnes [[Cornish pilot gig|pilot boats]] ''Champion'' and ''Cyclop'' and landed at St Mary's.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scilly |url= http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/feb.html|accessdate= 27 December 2012 |series= 1836 Articles and Other Items |newspaper= West Briton |date= 12 February 1836}}</ref>\n* 27 March &mdash; cutter '''''Prosperous''''' wrecked at an unknown location.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 7 April &mdash; [[Maryport]] brig '''''Bassenthwaite''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank immediately when she struck a partially submerged wreck in Broad Sound during a north-west gale.<ref name=larn92/>\n* April or May &mdash; parts of the balks, beams, masts, etc. have been washed up on many of the islands. They may be from a timber ship from Quebec that sank recently; whereabouts and time unknown.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/may.html|title= 1836 Articles and Other Items |accessdate= 28 December 2012|newspaper=West Briton |date= 6 May 1836}}</ref>\n* 13 October &mdash; St Ives schooner '''''Minerva''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying wool from Spain to Bristol hit the Western Rocks near Crebawathen and sank. Only one member of the crew survived and was picked up from a rock the next morning.<ref name=larn92/><ref name=gorran>{{cite news|title=The Weather|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~wbritonad/cornwall/1836/misc/oct.html|accessdate=3 January 2013|newspaper=West Briton|date=14 October 1836}}</ref>\n* 12 October &mdash; brig '''''Experiment''''' on her maiden voyage from Newfoundland to Poole with fish and oil was found on 14 October drifting after losing her mast and taking on water. Three of the nine crew survived.<ref name=gorran/>\n* October &mdash; the stern of '''''John Dunlap''''' washed onto the shore at Porth Hellick.<ref name=gorran/>\n\n===1838===\n* 29 May &mdash; barque '''''Osirus''''' ({{flag|France}}) hit the Crim Rocks in an easterly gale.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 November &mdash; barque '''''Pacquebot de Cayenne''''' ({{flag|France}}) sailed into the Hats during a SSE Gale. The crew were saved and most of her cargo of hides, wool and coffee was lost.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1839===\n* 22 February &mdash; 165 ton brig '''''Louisa Hannah''''' wrecked on the Ranneys, half a mile (0.8 km) west of [[Annet, Isles of Scilly|Annet]]. She was carrying wine and oranges from [[Lisbon]] to her home port of [[Poole]]. None of the crew survived.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 April &mdash; [[Plymouth]] schooner '''''Solace''''' en route from [[Lisbon]] struck a shallow reef within the Western Rocks during thick fog. The crew managed to save their personal belongings and she went to pieces the following day in a ground swell.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 September &mdash; brig '''''Theodorick''''' is probably the earliest recorded wreck on the [[Bishop Rock, Isles of Scilly|Bishop Rock]]. She was carrying a general cargo from [[Essaouira|Mogodore]] to [[London]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 6 December &mdash; the '''''St Vincent''''' hit the Chimney Rocks, at the eastern end of [[St Martin's, Isles of Scilly|St Martin's]] and sank.<ref name=\"Cooper\" /> All her crew and 75% of her cargo of barley was salvaged. She was bound for [[Penzance]] from [[Marans, Charente-Maritime|Marans]].<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1840===\n* 2 February &mdash; brig '''''Lady Louise''''' carrying coffee, from Rio de Janeiro to Cowes and London, attempted to make anchorage while in distress, and in a gale she was driven onto Guthers Bar.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 17 March &mdash; [[Beaumaris]] brig '''''Jane Ellen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck a rock in St Helen's Gap, lost her rudder and went aground on rocks near St Helen's. She was en route to London from [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] with slate. All the crew were saved.<ref name=\"Jane Ellen\">{{PastScape|mname=Jane Ellen|mnumber=878687|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Jane Ellen\"/>\n* 29 December &mdash; [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] schooner '''''Providence''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit the Bartholomew Ledges and was run ashore on St Agnes.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n==1841\u20131850==\n\n===1841===\n[[File:Figurehead of the SS Thames.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Thames in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 4 January &mdash; a paddle steamer, the Dublin steam packet '''[[SS Thames|SS ''Thames'']]''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}), en route from Dublin to London sank in a strong NE gale near Corregan and Rosevear.  Sixty-two of the sixty-four passengers and crew drowned when her Captain mistook the St Agnes light for the Longships and changed course to head north. Pilot gig ''Whale'', the only boat which managed to reach the wreck, saved three women.<ref name=McFarland>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly 1841 to 1880|journal=Scillonian|year=1927|volume=11}}</ref><ref name=Wreck>{{cite book|last=Larn|first=Richard|title=Wreck & Rescue round the Cornish Coast|publisher=Tor Mark Press|location=Redruth|isbn= 978-0-85025-406-8|page=48|author2=Larn, Bridget }}</ref> Her figurehead is in the Valhalla Museum at [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]].\n* 2 April &mdash; an unidentified schooner was lost on St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* December &mdash; the pilot boat of St Martin's sank and all six crew escaped with their lives.<ref name=\"Features\" />\n\n===1842===\n* 11 February &mdash; brig '''''William Proben''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of South Shields with a cargo of wheat was lost on Meledgan with the loss of all her crew.<ref name=\"Noall\" />\n* 12 October &mdash; the 600-tonne [[paddle steamer]] '''''Brigand''''', a [[packet boat]], en route from [[Liverpool]] to [[St Petersburg]], struck the Bishop's Rock with such force that it stove in two large bow plates. The rocks then acted as a pivot, and she swung round and heeled into the rock portside, crushing the paddle-wheel and box to such an extent that it penetrated the engine room. She drifted over {{convert|spell=in|7|miles}} in two hours, before sinking in {{cvt|90|m}}. All the crew were saved.<ref name=Maginnis>{{cite web |last=Maginnis |first=Clem |title= Around the Rugged Rock |url= http://www.divernet.com/Travel_Features/157098/around_the_rugged_rock.html| publisher= Divernet |accessdate= 9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1843===\n* 28 January &mdash; The English wooden schooner '''''Douro''''' wrecked on Crebawethan with the loss of all her crew while out from Liverpool for Oporto with a cargo of bailed goods, armoury and brass stops (later determined in the 1970s to be horseshoe shaped [[manillas]] or bracelets used as tokens in the slave trade). All her crew was lost and five seamen including the master are buried in St Mary's churchyard.<ref name=\"Noall\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Slave beads shown|newspaper=The Cornishman|date=3 April 2008}}</ref> Subsequent dives in the 1970s provided the evidence she was involved in the slave trade.<ref>Isles of Scilly Underwater Centre; ''Ships and Boats 1840-1850'', English Heritage September 2012.</ref>\n* 3 March &mdash; schooner '''''Anne & Jane''''' hit a rock north of St Agnes while carrying slates from her home port of Caernarvon to Perth. Local pilots received \u00a330 for helping her to safety.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 21 November &mdash; schooner '''''Challenger''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) from [[Surinam]] (or [[Smyrna]] according to Noall), carrying fruit to her home port of London and wrecked either on the Gunners or the Nundeeps. Her crew of eight managed to row to Bryher with only one oar and the whole island was put under [[quarantine]].<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Noall\" />\n* 21 November &mdash;  barque '''''Nickerie''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) struck a rock, during the night, south-west of [[Rosevear, Isles of Scilly|Rosevear]]. She was heading for her home port of [[Rotterdam]] from [[Semarang|Samarang]], [[Jakarta|Batavia]], with coffee and sugar; her captain thought she was in the [[English Channel]]. She got off and struck again ten minutes later, and started to break up with eight men drowning. The eleven remaining men attempted to make a raft but  only two survived when finally rescued from Rosevear. (According to Noall (1968) this wreck occurred on 22 February 1844).\n\n===1844===\n* 22 February &mdash; 600 ton barque '''''Nickerie''''' (or '''''Nichiril''''') ({{flag|Netherlands}}) wrecked on Rosevean while on a voyage from [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to Rotterdam with coffee and sugar. There were two survivors.<ref name=\"Noall\" /> (According to Larn (1992) this wreck occurred on 21 November 1843). \n* 1 May &mdash; '''''Vespa''''' lost on the Woolpack, Garrison, St Mary's.<ref name=\"Todd\"/> '''''Vesper''''' lost in St Mary's Sound.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1845===\n* 1 December &mdash; the 347 ton barque registered in [[North Shields]] '''''John Esdaile''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Gilstone Ledge in the Western Rocks while out of Green Island for London. She was towed into Smith Sound and a week later went to pieces. Her crew was saved and some of her cargo washed up on Annet and St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1846===\n* 4 January &mdash; brig '''''Leonie''''' hit the Bow, off Gugh and was refloated when her masts were cut off to lighten her. She was carrying brandy for Liverpool and the Clyde.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 3 October &mdash; tender '''''Eddystone''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) driven onto Men-a-Vaur whilst leaving Old Grimsby Harbour; her cargo was saved. A Scheduled Ancient Monument<ref name=larn92/><ref>{{PastScape|mname=Eddystone|mnumber=1124293|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n* 7 October &mdash; brigantine '''''Don''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Sunderland grounded on Tresco and refloated.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1848===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0034 - Figurehead of the Palinurus (1833).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Palinurus in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 18 January &mdash; [[Glasgow]] schooner '''''Eagle''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}), out of her home port for [[Charante]] with coal and iron, hit the Crim, then several other rocks and lastly the Bishop before sinking. The crew had a lucky escaped, with the mainyard narrowly missing the longboat as she was launched.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 25 December &mdash; the brig '''''Charlotte''''' ({{flag|Sweden|1844}}) out of Gothenburg for Montevideo with deals and balk timber foundered on Melledgan where the master, mate, two crew and a passenger lost their lives. Ten survivors erected a rough tent on the rock and were rescued the next day.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 27 December &mdash; seventeen lives were lost when the '''''Palinurus''''' with a cargo including hogsheads of rum was wrecked off White Island, St Martins.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n===1850===\n* 30 October &mdash; in order to save the brig '''''Calliope''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Greece}}) after she hit the Barthomew Ledges, she was put ashore near the Woolpack Battery, St Mary's. She was heading for Falmouth from [[Odessa]] and was sold for \u00a322 10s.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n==1851\u20131860==\n\n===1851===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0023 - Figurehead of the Alessandro il Grande.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Alessandro Il Grande in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 1 January &mdash; 289 ton Neapolitan brig '''''Alessandro II Grande''''' [[File:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg|25px|1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860 flag]] ([[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]) parted her cables and drifted on to Mare Ledges, to the south of Tresco. There was no loss of life. Her figurehead is in the Tresco Abbey Gardens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valhalla \u2013 Alessandro Il Grande 1851|url=http://www.tresco.co.uk/what-to-do/abbey-garden/valhalla_alessandro.aspx|publisher=Tresco Estate|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 September &mdash; storm damaged brig '''''San Giorgio''''' ([[Naples|Neopolitan]]) drifted onto the Crim Rocks, then cleared and partially sank on her side with her crew rescued by the schooner ''Galway''. ''San Giorgio'' drifted out to sea and was found {{convert|60|mi|km}} offshore. She was towed back to Scilly by a schooner and fifteen pilot-cutters with all her cargo of olive oil and wood salvaged. She was repaired on St Mary's and renamed the ''Lion'' of Scilly.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1852===\n* 13 April &mdash; 225 ton barque '''''Mary Hay''''' hit the Steeple Rock on Bream Ledges while entering Broad Sound despite there being a pilot on board. She was on passage from Jamaica to London with a mixed cargo and sank suddenly with thirty men on deck. There was no loss of life and the wreck was sold for \u00a372 along with salvaged ebony, logwood, coconuts and fustic. The day after the wreck 43 puncheons of rum, two casks of lime-juice, 1,170 bags of pimento, and ship stores, gear and clothing were salvaged Her figurehead is in Valhalla on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* a wooden box from East Indiaman '''''Agnes Ewing''''' [[File:Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg|22px]] [[British East India Company]] was washed ashore on Te\u00e4n. She was on passage from Liverpool to Calcutta and nothing more has been heard of the ship.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1853===\n* 27 January &mdash; Brixham schooner '''''Sarah''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank at anchor in St Martin's Flats; she had sprung a leak two days previous while bound with coal from Cardiff to [[Tenerife]] and [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife|Santa Cruz]]. Her cargo and hull was sold three weeks later for \u00a338.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 3 March &mdash; while carrying slate from her home port of Caernarfon to Perth the schooner '''''Anne & Jane''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit a rock north of St Agnes.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 24 March &mdash; cargo ship '''''Sultana''''' ([[File:Admiralty flag of Hamburg.svg|22px]] [[Hamburg]]) was lost on the Nundeeps and her crew drowned. A nameboard was washed ashore near Padstow nearly a month later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 June &mdash;  brig '''''Ambassador''''' ([[File:19th Century Flag of Malta.svg|border|22px]] [[Malta]]) carrying coal from Cardiff to Malta struck the Seven Stones in fine weather at six in the morning and sank. The crew made it into the ship boats and made for the Trinity House light vessel.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1854===\n* 3 January &mdash; brig '''''Advena''''' driven onto Samson in a south-east gale. She was re-floated at high water after her masts were removed.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 26 June &mdash; the [[Cardiff]] [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] '''''Belinda''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sailing from her home port to [[Cork (city)|Cork]] with [[limestone]], hit the Bishop Rock in thick fog.<ref name=Maginnis/> She got off the rock but took in water and foundered nearby; her crew were saved.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1856===\n* 28 August &mdash; [[Liverpool]] full-rigger '''''Custos''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank within ten minutes after hitting the Crim Rocks. She was carrying brandy, rum, gunpowder and soap, most of which was lost.<ref name=larn92/>\n* '''''Chieftain''''' said to be wrecked on the east side of St Martin's at Hard Lewis.<ref name=Gilmore>{{cite web|title=Gilmore Chieftain|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/1949171|publisher=Geograph|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> The figurehead of a highland chieftain in full dress is in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens#Valhalla collection|Valhalla]] on Tresco, although there is no record of a ship named Chieftain in [[Lloyd's Register]], [[HM Customs and Excise]], [[Board of Trade]] or the RNLI at this time. The wreck in deep water by Hard Lewis is most probably ''Gilmore'', wrecked in [[List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly#1866|1866]].<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1857===\n1 June &mdash; the Padstow brig '''''Voluna''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) while in ballast from Falmouth for Quebec went ashore on the south shore of St Agnes during dense fog. The crew managed to get ashore and ''Voluna'' broke up in the surf.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1860===\n* 14 July &mdash; Austrian sailing ship '''''Osvetitel''''' was wrecked in fog on Maiden Bower while sailing from [[Ibrail]] to Falmouth with barley. Her crew and most of her cargo was recovered.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 19 August &mdash; brig '''''Aurora''''' went ashore, in fog, on the Brow-of-Ponds while carrying wheat from Ibrail to Falmouth. Her crew survived but the cargo was lost and the wreck was sold 23 August.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 26 November &mdash; the '''''Empire''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank during a severe gale in North Sound after hitting Peaked Rock.<ref name=larn92 /><ref name=Allsop>{{cite book|last=Allsop|first=Tim|title=Underwater Scilly|year=2009|publisher=Marshfield Underwater Publications|location=Scilly|isbn=9780956187406|author2=Cawthray, Anna }}</ref>\n\n==1861\u20131870==\n\n===1861===\n* 18 February &mdash; schooner '''''Pauline''''' ({{FRA}}) carrying railway iron from [[Ardrossan]] to Rouen was driven onto Crow Bar<ref name=larn92 />\n* 18 February &mdash; the '''''Mentor''''' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]) parted her cables and collided with the brig ''Arthemise'' ({{FRA}}). The crew managed to get on board the '''''Arthemise''''' which was then ran ashore.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 19 March &mdash; 846 ton sailing ship '''''Award''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) on her second voyage and bound from Liverpool for New Orleans, struck rocks {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} off [[Gweal]]. NNW force 8 to 9 winds drove her on to the northern end of Gweal pushing her bow on to land and forming a temporary bridge to the island. After twelve hours the crew of 24 managed to scramble ashore.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valhalla \u2013 Award 1861|url=http://www.tresco.co.uk/what-to-do/abbey-garden/valhalla_award.aspx|publisher=Tresco Estate|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1862===\n* 24 February &mdash; brig '''''Alexandrina''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Cardiff while carrying coal was abandoned during a gale in the roadstead. Scillonian pilots received \u00a397 from the owner for running her aground.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1863===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0027 - Figurehead of the Friar Tuck (1856).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Friar Tuck in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* December &mdash; sailing ship '''''Friar Tuck''''' with a cargo of tea wrecked in a north-west gale on [[Porthloo|Porth Loo]], St Mary's. The crew were landed by the rocket apparatus.<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n\n===1864===\n* 1 May &mdash; while en route from Malaga to St Petersburg with olive oil the '''''Aegir''''' {{flag|Sweden|1844}} of Gelf was wrecked but re-floated on the same day.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1866===\n* 6 February &mdash; barque '''''Hydra''''' wrecked.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 13 February &mdash; schooner '''''Dauphine''''' ({{FRA}}) caught alight two hours from Scilly and her hulk eventually drifted onto St Agnes.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 12 April &mdash; 535 ton barque '''''[[Gilmore (1824 ship)|Gilmore]]''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Southampton wrecked on Hard Lewis, off the east side of St Martin's.<ref name=Gilmore /> She was in ballast from her home port to Quebec and the crew managed to get away in the ship's boats.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1867===\n*19 January \u2013 Paddle steamer '''Vesper''' of Glasgow, built in 1865, gave way amidships about 50 miles off the Isles of Scilly.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fearful Shipwreck off Scilly. Three lives lost |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000180/18670124/024/0005 |newspaper=Royal Cornwall Gazette |location=England |date=24 January 1867 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \n* December &mdash; brigantine '''''Good Intent''''' with a cargo of coal hit the Crim Rocks and sank.<ref name=larn92 /> \n* coal hulk '''''Eliza''''' wrecked. Her figurehead is in the [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eliza|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/1949176|publisher=Geograph|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1869===\n* 16 February &mdash; Schooner '''''Alida''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) of [[Veendam]] sank off White Island, St Martin's en route from Swansea to Taragonna with patent fuel. her crew were pricked up by the pilot gig ''Linnet''.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 6 December &mdash; Brigantine '''''Otto''''' ({{flag|Sweden|1844}}) stranded on Southward Well, after parting her cables and fouling the barque ''Dorothy Thompson''. She was carrying [[Pine tar|Stockholm tar]] from [[Jakobstad]] to Bristol. There was no loss of life and only 36 barrels were saved before she broke up.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1870===\n* 27 January &mdash; Ship '''''Willem Poolman''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) of Rotterdam went on the rocks at Southward Well while en route from Batavia to her home port. Both the ship and her cargo of tin and coffee were saved.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 20 April &mdash; screw steamer '''''{{SS|Sado||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was lost on the ''Brow of the Ponds'' between Crebawthan and Jackyl Rock while heading to Liverpool from Oporto with a general cargo including wood, wine, oranges, thirty head of cattle and eggs. \u2033''Some of the eggs hatched, the breed of fowl proved unsatisfactory and eventually died''\u2033. Three of the bullocks were found by a Sennen boat and landed on Roseveor and a fourth was landed on St Mary's.<ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 28 May &mdash; schooner '''''Frances Jane''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of [[Carrickfergus]] hit the Bartholomew Ledges (and refloated) while carrying salt from [[Runcorn]] to Plymouth.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 21 July &mdash; while bound for Marseilles from Cardiff, the Liverpool steamer '''''Tyne Queen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck Men-a-Vaur in fog, was stranded on rocks in St Helen's Pool for an hour before unloading her cargo in New Grimsby.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 7 October &mdash; despite the good visibility during daylight hours and the lightship within sight, the barque '''''{{SS|Nelson||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Seven Stones reef while carrying [[lead|pig lead]] and [[esparto]] to Tyneside. She sank within two minutes and the master and two of the crew lost their lives.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n==1871\u20131880==\n\n===1871===\n[[File:Figurehead from the Salmon.jpg|thumb|Figurehead from the Salmon in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 11 January &mdash; [[Kinsale]] barque '''''Royal Standard''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying oats from her home port to Southampton was driven ashore on Bryher. She was refloated four days later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 15 January \u2013 barque '''''Salmon''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) drifted onto rocks on Tresco.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wreck at Scilly |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000329/18710118/107/0002 |newspaper=Western Morning News |location=England |date=18 January 1871 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \n* 24 June &mdash; iron barque '''{{SS|Il Primo||2}}''' ({{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}) of Bilbao carrying sugar for [[Greenock]] from [[Havana]] hit the Seven Stones reef and quickly sank with the loss of all the crew bar one.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n* 7 July &mdash; the 387 ton barque '''''Belle of the South''''' hit the Perconger Ledge off St Agnes in a heavy rain squall. With a pilot on board she ran for and beached near St Mary's pier where a piece of rock two foot long was found embedded in her hull. She was repaired and continued her journey to [[Algoa Bay]], South Africa with a general cargo.<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 13 October &mdash; schooner '''''Lelia''''' ({{FRA}}) carrying coal from [[Neath]] to Rochelle went aground on the Spanish Ledges but managed to get clear.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 20 December &mdash; all but two of the crew of the Liverpool steamer '''''{{SS|Delaware||2}}''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) drowned when she broke down and was driven ashore on Mincarlo.<ref name=\"Noall\"/><ref name=\"McFarland\"/> Two of the crew escaped in the ships boat which was washed up on White Island (Sampson) and saved by the crew of Byrher gig ''Albion'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1872===\n* 17 February &mdash; Greek brig '''''Telxinoi''''' ([[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|20px|First National Flag of Greece|border]]) wrecked on Crow Bar.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 16 July &mdash; [[PS Earl of Arran (1860)|'''PS ''Earl of Arran''''']] ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) passenger steamer, which travelled between the islands and [[Penzance]] struck the rock St Martin's Neck and beached on Nornour after a passenger, Stephen Woodcock, a pilot-boat crew member though himself not a pilot, talked the Captain into taking an unusual course \u2033... to give the passengers a better view\u2033. The 92 passengers and crew were saved though the Earl was beyond help.<ref name=\"Cooper\" /><ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite book|last=Carter|first=C.|title=The Port of Penzance: a history|year=1998|publisher=Black Dwarf Publications|location=Lydney|isbn=0-9533028-0-6}}</ref>\n* 6 October  &mdash; '''''[[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company|Little Western]]''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on the Wells Reef. She was the second West Cornwall Steam Ship Company ferry to be wrecked in the islands during 1872.<ref name=\"Carter\" />\n* 22 November  &mdash; Italian barque '''''Rosa Tacchini''''' wrecked on the Paper Ledges, near [[Tresco, Isles of Scilly|Tresco]] after her anchors dragged during a severe south-west gale. No one was hurt. The wreck was towed to Carn Near on Tresco where she was broken up.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1873===\n* 1 February &mdash; while sheltering from hurricane-force winds along with fifty other ships the '''''Outalpha''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of London grounded in St Mary's Roads. She was refloated on the following tide and continued her journey from [[Adelaide]] to London with grain.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 15 March &mdash; all the crew were lost when the '''''Elizabeth''''' was wrecked on St Agnes.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 10 June &mdash; Mousehole sailing lugger '''''Cornish Girl''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank after striking the Round Rock in the Spanish Ledges in fine weather. No lives lost.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1874===\n* 18 January &mdash; the [[Minnehaha (cargo ship)|'''''Minnehaha''''']], cargo ship, bound for Dublin, wrecked on Peninnis Head, St Mary's with the loss of ten lives including the Pilot.<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 10 March &mdash; schooner '''''Ranneys''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of [[Fowey]] struck the Spanish Ledges and refloated.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 22 March &mdash; the upturned hull of the sailing ship '''''James Armstrong''''', with a cargo of mahogany and coconuts, was found between St Martin's and the Seven Stones and towed to St Mary's beach by the ''Queen of the Bay''. The coconuts were inedible!<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n* 4 April &mdash; '''SS ''Bordelaise''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Liverpool attempted to enter Crow Sound without a Pilot and hit the Hats. She was bound for Oporto, from Newport, with coal and railway iron. Some of her cargo was salvaged.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 13 April &mdash; schooner '''''Edmund''''' wrecked.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 16 April &mdash; '''SS ''Zelda''''', on her maiden voyage, stranded on the Maiden Bower Rock in fog. Her crew and passengers were saved, and some cargo was salvaged by divers. When the wreck was inspected in 1966, it was found that not only had the SS ''Brinkburn'' sunk on top of the ''Zelda'' in 1898, but that evidence of an unknown wooden warship was found beneath it.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stevens|first=Todd|author2=Cummings Ed |title=The Search for the Nancy Wreck|journal=Scillonian|year=2011|issue=272|pages=160\u201362}}</ref><ref>{{PastScape|mname=Zelda|mnumber=858309|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> \n* 20 April &mdash; St Agnes pilot cutter '''''Gem''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) smashed on Perconger after she slipped her moorings.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1875===\n* 7 May &mdash; ocean liner '''''{{SS|Schiller||2}}''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) on a journey from [[New York City]] to [[Hamburg]], wrecked on the Retarrier Ledges with the loss of 335 people.<ref>{{cite book |author=Austin, Keith |date=2001 |title=The Victorian Titanic: The Loss of the SS Schiller in 1875 |publisher=Halsgrove |isbn=1-84114-133-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Museum News|url=http://www.scillyonline.co.uk/sutd/120/pages/museum.html|accessdate=2 November 2011|newspaper=Scilly Up To Date|date=April 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008071820/http://www.scillyonline.co.uk/sutd/120/pages/museum.html|archive-date=8 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 11 August &mdash; barque '''''Cactus''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) on passage from [[Tripoli]] to Cardiff with [[Esparto|esparto grass]] struck the Northern Rocks. With pilots on board, she was deliberately run onto Samson the next day and taken to Hugh Town on the 13th.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 26 August &mdash; ([[Genoa]]) barque '''''Gloria''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) hit the Crim Rocks. Assisted to St Mary's by the ''Lady of the Isles'', her cargo of ore and grass from Pomeron was saved.<ref name=larn92 />\n* 1 November &mdash; on her [[maiden voyage]] to Rio de Janeiro with coal, the three\u2013masted brigantine '''''Catherine Griffiths''''' sank in thick fog with the loss of eight of her nine crew. Giovanni Carstulovich managed to reach the shore at Troy Town.<ref name=Noall />\n* 2 November &mdash; steamer '''''Aksai''''' ({{flagcountry|Russian Empire}}) sailed into [[White Island, Isles of Scilly|White Island]], St Martin's in thick fog while bound for [[Odessa]] from Cardiff with coal. The captain and crew of thirty-nine were saved by the [[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company#Lady of the Isles|''Lady of the Isles'']].<ref name=larn92 />\n* 23 November &mdash; 452 ton '''''Foscolo''''' ({{flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) of [[Naples]] struck the Seven Stone Reef while bound from [[Montevideo]] for [[Dundee]] with scrap iron and bones. She managed to reach Crow Bar and sank in the shallows. She was later salvaged and raised.<ref name=larn92 />\n\n===1876===\n* 17 February &mdash; the '''''Linn Fern''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Glasgow wrecked in Crow Sound<ref name=larn92/>\n* British barque '''''Bordelaise''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) with a cargo of \u2033railway iron\u2033 lost on The Hats; see 1874 above.<ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref name=McFarland3>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F M|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly (Conclusion)|journal=[[Scillonian (magazine)|Scillonian]]|date=March 1928|volume=4|issue=13|pages=18\u201322}}</ref>\n\n===1877===\n* schooner '''{{SS|Ethel||2}}''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) struck the Seven Stones reef but sustained little damage and headed for Plymouth. Her captain and mate had their certificates withdrawn.<ref name=\"Noall\"/>\n\n===1878===\n* 23 July &mdash; Out of [[Seville]], '''''Ranneys''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) ran aground off St Mary's while awaiting orders. After 24 hours she refloated with the loss of her [[Anchor#Kedging|kedge anchor]] and [[hawser]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Our Ships and our Sailors|work=The Cornishman|issue=4|date=8 August 1878|page=8}}</ref>\n* 10 October &mdash; [[Aberystwyth]] schooner '''''Integrity''''' (or '''''Integrite''''') ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) lost her foremast and longboat in heavy seas off the Bishop Rock. Carrying lime phosphates from Lisbon to Wicklow she found it impossible to manoeuvre in Smith Sound and drifted around Annet before being beached in Perconger, St Agnes. One of the four crew was swept overboard and drowned. Two days later she was refloated and taken to St Mary's.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 23 October &mdash; '''''{{SS|Ely Rise||2}}''''' ({{flag|France}}) carrying \u2033patent fuel\u2033 struck rocks near The Hats in Crow Sound. She was refloated and repaired and was subject to a [[Marine salvage|salvage]] claim by the [[West Cornwall Steam Ship Company]].<ref name=\"McFarland\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Salvage Action by the West Cornwall Steamship Company|work=The Cornishman|issue=28|date=30 January 1879|page=6}}</ref>\n* 31 December &mdash; brigantine '''''Minerve''''' ({{flag|France}}) driven onto rocks between Wrass and Morning Point. All the crew, bar one who swam to safety, were saved by the rocket apparatus.<ref name=\"McFarland\" />\n\n===1879===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0009 - Figurehead of the River Lune.jpg|thumb|FIgurehead of the '''River Lune''' in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* January &mdash; Liverpool barque '''''Bertha''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was abandoned, off the islands, after a collision with ''J Brown'' which headed for Queenstown with the crew of the abandoned ship. ''Bertha'' foundered shortly after.<ref>{{cite news|title=Collision off Scilly|work=The Cornishman|issue=28|date=30 January 1879|page=6}}</ref>\n* 6 January &mdash; the brigantine '''''Gerhardine''''' was abandoned by her crew approximately {{convert|30|miles}} south of St Agnes. She was towed into St Mary's by ''Gladiator''. The crew were landed at [[Le Havre]] on 16 January.<ref>{{cite news |title= Rescue of an Abandoned Vessel |work= The Cornishman |issue=28 |date= 23 January 1879 |page=5}}</ref>\n* 24 March &mdash; on her maiden voyage, the 215 ton barquentine '''''Tabasco''''', carrying bottled beer and coal from Greenock struck White Island, St Martin's. Her master mistook the Seven Stones lightship for Trevose Head.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 27 July &mdash; Liverpool barque '''''Maipu''''' was wrecked in Hell Bay on Bryher. She was bound for Hamburg from [[Iquique]] with a cargo of [[Sodium nitrate|saltpetre]].<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 27 July &mdash; barque '''''River Lune''''' in ballast from [[Lorient]] to [[Ardrossan]] was lost on Brothers Rock in Muncoy Neck, the channel between Annet and Melledgan, after a faulty chronometer put her off course. She sank in ten minutes, but the crew escaped.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> The wreck was sold on 13 August 1879 for \u00a310 to Messrs Banfield and Son.<ref>{{cite news |title= Isles of Scilly |work=The Cornishman |issue=58 |date= 21 August 1879 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n===1880===\n* the St Martin's cutter '''''Queen''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) grounded on Par Beach, St Martin's and wrecked.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 23 October \u2013 the coal schooner '''''Argo''''' wrecked on [[Te\u00e4n]] while on passage from Newport to [[Polruan]]. All the crew of eight managed to get ashore.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 28 October \u2013 the 194 tons gross wooden brig '''''Messenger''''' of Salcombe dragged onto Skirt Island while carrying coal from Cardiff to Portsmouth. She refloated after St. Mary's lifeboat (''Henry Dundas'') had saved five of her crew but was later scrapped.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n==1881\u20131890==\n\n===1881===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum FHD0003 - Figurehead of the Independenzia (1875).jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Independenzia in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* January &mdash; the barque '''''Saint Jean''''' ({{flag|France}}) sank, with the loss of three men, after colliding with the barque ''Privateer''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The French barque|work=The Cornishman|issue=131|date=13 January 1881|page=3}}</ref>\n* 18 January &mdash; the wooden hulled brigantine '''''Charlotte Dunbar''''' was found ashore and abandoned on Burnt Island, St Agnes. She was sailing from Newport to [[Audierne]] with coal and nothing was heard of her crew of six.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 8 February &mdash; the brigantine '''''Kron Prinz von Preussen''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) was driven ashore in [[New Grimsby|New Grimsby harbour]], Tresco.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Stranding Of A Ship|work=The Cornishman|issue=137|date=24 February 1881|page=7}}</ref>\n* 7 May &mdash; the '''''SS Culmore''''' with a cargo of onions, peppers and oranges hit the Crim.<ref name=McFarland2>{{cite journal|last=McFarland|first=F|title=Shipwrecks of Scilly 1881 to 1900|journal=Scillonian|date=December 1927|volume=4|issue=12|pages=402\u20135}}</ref> The captain and three of the crew lost their lives.<ref>{{cite news|title=Loss Of The Steamer Culmore, Near The Bishop Rock Lighthouse, And Of Her Captain And Three Others.|work=The Cornishman|issue=148|date=12 May 1881|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Loss Of A Fine Barque And Her Cargo Of Guano Among The Islands Of Scilly In A Fog|work=The Cornishman|issue=168|date=29 September 1881|page=6}}</ref>\n* 24 September \u2013 the barque '''''Independenzia''''' was carrying a cargo of guano and horn from [[Valpara\u00edso|Valparaiso]], Chile, when she struck the [[Crim Rocks]] and later sank on the Barrel of Butter rock on [[St Mary's, Isles of Scilly#The Garrison and Star Castle|The Garrison]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fearful Shipwreck off Scilly. Three lives lost |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000289/18810927/012/0003 |newspaper=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette |location=England |date=27 September 1881 |access-date=13 May 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n* 21 November &mdash; the small steamer '''''Gem''''' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) broke from her moorings in St Mary's Pool, and went ashore at William's Bay, becoming a total wreck. ''Gem''  taking on coal and was bound for South Africa for employment as a river boat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wreck of a steamer at Scilly=The Cornishman|issue=176|date=24 November 1881|page=5}}</ref>\n* 27 November &mdash; the '''''Excelsior''''' ({{Flag|German Empire}}) of Hamburg grounded on Crow Bar and consequently beached on the south-west corner of Higher Town Bay, St Martin's. She had left Rangoon on 7 June and was carrying 915 tons of rice, rattan and teak. Two months later on 22 January she was towed towards St Mary's by the ''Queen of the Bay'' and ''Lady of the Isles'' and after 30 minutes sank (see also 1882).<ref name=larn92/><ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n===1882===\n* 22 January &mdash; the '''''Excelsior''''' sank off St Martin's after repairs on a St Martin's beach (see 1881).<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n* 24 April &mdash; London barge '''''St Vincent''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank on Toll Island, near Pelistry, St Mary's after striking the Spanish Ledges. She was en route from [[Saint Vincent (island)|St Vincent]] for London with sugar. The crew escaped, but there was much embarrassment as she was carrying a St Agnes pilot.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 December &mdash; the steamer '''''Raglan''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) sank, after being hit by a Greek steamer and her boiler exploding. The crew were picked up by the Greek steamer.<ref>{{cite news |title=The steamer ''Raglan'' |work=The Cornishman |issue=231 |date=14 December 1882 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n===1883===\n* 9 February &mdash; '''''Criccieth Castle''''' lost on Porthcress Beach.<ref name=\"McFarland3\" />\n\n===1885===\n* 8 June &mdash; '''''Earl of Lonsdale''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Newcastle, carrying cotton seed from Alexandria to [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], was wrecked in Smith Sound, off the Troy Town maze, St Agnes in thick fog.<ref name=Noall/><ref>{{cite book|last=Ratcliffe|first=J|title=The Archaeology of Scilly|year=1989|publisher=Cornwall Archaeological Unit|location=Truro}}</ref> The master had thought his ship was to the west of, and {{cvt|10|miles}} south of, the Bishop Rock.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 17 December &mdash; cargo ship SS '''''Sussex''''' struck Seal Rock, near the Maiden Bower after being caught in heavy fog, while travelling at normal cruising speed. The crew escaped and she broke up during the night of 4\u20135 January in heavy seas.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 30 December &mdash; a local cutter capsized off Yellow Ledges with the loss of one life, while on its way to the steamer ''Sussex'', which struck Seal Rock on 17 December.\n\n===1886===\n* 26 March &mdash; Brigantine '''''Nellie'''''({{flag|Denmark}}) of [[Elsinore]] had been in collision to the west of Scilly and was driven before a south-westerly gale onto the Western Rocks where she first struck Jackys Rock. Part of the vessel drifted onto Annet and the remainder into St Warna's Cove on St Agnes. She was on passage from Bordeaux to Cardiff with pit props under the command of Capt M L Svendsen who lost his life along his chief officer. Two of the crew were saved after clinging to the wreck for sixteen hours and four were picked up from Melledgan where they quenched their thirst with [[puffin|puffins']] blood.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1887===\n* 12 January &mdash; Caernarvon schooner '''''Bolina''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) carrying slate from [[Portmadoc]] to London sank off the south coast of Gugh during an easterly gale.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 8 June &mdash; the SS '''''Castleford''''' struck the [[Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly|Crebawethans]] and led to some of her cargo of 250 to 450 cattle being landed on [[Annet, Isles of Scilly|Annet]] and staying there for up to ten days.<ref>Gurney (1889) \"Notes on the Isles of Scilly and the Manx Shearwater (''Puffinus anglorum'')\"; ''Transactions of the Norfolk and Norwich Naturalists' Society''. In: Parslow, R. (2007) ''The Isles of Scilly''. London: HarperCollins</ref>\n\n===1888===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0053 - Figurehead of the Bernardo.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Bernardo in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 15 January &mdash; the 332 ton barque '''''Gauloise''''' ({{Flag|France}}) of Bordeaux sailed onto Great Arthur Island on the northern edge of Crow Sound. She was carrying pitprops for Porthcawl and heading NNE when fog came down {{convert|14|miles}} south of St Agnes light.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 11 March &mdash; while in ballast, the barque '''''Bernardo''''' ({{Flag|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}) of Genoa lost her sails in a west-north-west gale and was blown ashore on the back of Annet. The captain was rescued from Old Woman Rock by St Agnes fisherman after the ship broke up around him. Eleven of the crew were drowned in the ship's boat when it capsized.<ref name=\"larn92\"/> Her figurehead, apparently [[Bernard of Clairvaux|St Bernard of Clairvaux]], is in Valhalla on Tresco.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 7 May &mdash; London steamer '''''Egyptian Monarch''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) on passage from New York to her home port with a general cargo including cattle, and passengers, stranded near Bryher. She managed to refloat and made Falmouth the same day with one compartment full of water.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n* 9 August &mdash; no one on the islands knew that the steamer '''''Gomes V''''' ({{Flag|Portugal|1830}}) had foundered until a St Martin's pilot boat picked up nineteen crew and one passenger drifting eastwards past Hanjaque in two of the ships boats. She was carrying coal to Oporto from Cardiff and struck the Shag Rock in dense fog.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n===1889===\n[[File:National Maritime Museum, FHD0045 - Figurehead from the Jane Owen.jpg|thumb|Figurehead of the Jane Owen in [[Tresco Abbey Gardens]]]]\n* 3 March &mdash; '''''Jane Owen''''' wrecked on Crow Bar.<ref name=\"larn92\"/>\n\n==1891\u20131900==\n\n===1891===\n* 19 February &mdash; steamer '''''Trignac''''' ({{Flag|France}}) sprang a leak, blew up and sank within five minutes, between the Islands and the Seven Stones Reef. She was carrying coal from Newport to [[Saint-Nazaire|St Nazaire]].<ref name=larn92/>\n* 10 March &mdash; 34 ton smack '''''Porth''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) of Padstow ran ashore on the Minmanueth Rocks on the western coast of Annet. She was heading for [[St Columb Minor]] with [[Culm (coal)|culm]] from Swansea when she was caught in the \u2033[[Great Blizzard of 1891]]\u2033. St Agnes lifeboat ''James & Caroline'' rescued the master and his son, but the third crew member was found frozen.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 12 March &mdash; barque '''''Megellan''''' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) foundered in the approaches to the English Channel at lat 47.48 N long 6.53 W. The crew were picked up and taken to Falmouth.<ref name=1891blizard>{{cite book|last=Anon|title=The Blizzard in the West|year=1891|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall, Hamilton, Kent and Co., Limited|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/blizzardinwestbe00londiala#page/n0/mode/2up}}</ref>\n* 11 November &mdash; Padstow schooner '''''J K A''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) wrecked on Shag Rocks near the Mouls; she broke free and foundered. Her crew abandoned ship and landed on [[Eastern Isles#Great Innisvouls and Little Innisvouls|Great Innisvouls]] where they were rescued by a gig from St Martin's.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1892===\n* 6 February &mdash; '''''Embiricos''''' of [[Andros]] hit either John Thomas or Deep Ledge, St Martin's in heavy rain. She was bound for Malta and Odessa with coal from Cardiff. The captain and five others lost their lives when attempting to launch a boat. Twenty-eight hours four of her crew in a second boat were picked up off the Lizard by steamer ''Rutland'' and landed at Le Havre.<ref name=larn92/>\n\n===1893===\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 144983 Horsa (ship).jpg|thumb|''Horsa'' shipwreck]]\n* February &mdash; a Truro schooner, '''''John and Mary''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was found ashore on Samson after she collided with a Greek  brig in St Mary's Roads. She was later towed to New Grimsby.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 4 April &mdash; full\u2013rigger '''''Horsa''''' with a cargo of oats and wool from New Zealand grounded in Bread and Cheese Cove on St Martin's. She later capsized {{convert|spell=in |21|miles}} south-west of the Bishop Rock, while being towed; there were no deaths.<ref name=\"larn92\" /><ref>Noall, C. (1969?) ''Cornish Shipwrecks Illustrated''. Truro: Tor Mark Press; p. 20</ref>\n* 24 November &mdash; the SS '''''Serica''''' nearly foundered and took shelter in St Mary's Roads on the 19th. As she left she struck an uncharted rock (later named Serica Rock) and sank.<ref>''The Cornishman''. 18 January 1894. p. 8.</ref>\n\n===1896===\n[[File:Anchor from the Sophie.jpg|thumb|Anchor from the Sophie in the Flying Boat Club, Tresco]]\n* 14 December &mdash; '''''Sophie''''' ({{Flag|Norway|1844}}) of Fredrikstadt started to disintegrate and was abandoned along with her cargo of anthracite from Cardiff. She was towed into New Grimsby by the ''Lady of the Isles'' and sold to [[Thomas Algernon Smith-Dorrien-Smith|Algernon Dorrien Smith]] who used her timbers around the Tresco estate and her cargo to heat his greenhouses.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1898===\n* 26 May &mdash; Newlyn fishing lugger '''''Nyanza''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was run ashore on Great Crebawethan after hitting the Crims and springing a leak. St Agnes lifeboat, ''James and Caroline'' took off four of the crew and the fifth was saved by an island boat.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 20 August &mdash; 2,843 ton Sunderland steamer '''''Toledo''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) hit Steeple Rock and ripped open her hull. Her crew managed to lower the ship's boats and escape before she sank in twenty-five fathoms.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n* 15 December &mdash; 3,229 ton steamship '''''Brinkburn''''' struck the Maiden Bower in fog and sank, while bound for Le Havre from Galveston with cotton and cotton seed. Her crew of mainly [[lascar]]s survived. An inspection of the wreck in 1966, found beneath her two other ships, one the ''Sussex'' which sank in 1885 and an unknown warship.<ref name=\"larn92\" />\n\n===1899===\n* 12 February &mdash; 76-ton wooden brigantine '''''Bohallard''''' ({{flag|France}}) of Nantes broke her cables during a WNW hurricane-force gale and drifted onto Pendrathen. She later floated clear and was wrecked in Higher Town Bay, where she broke up two days later.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 7 June &mdash; [[Liverpool & Glasgow Salvage Association#Liverpool Salvage Association|Liverpool Salvage Association's]] steamer '''''Ranger''''' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) grounded on Crow Bar and was refloated the same day.<ref name=larn92/>\n* 25 October &mdash; while carrying rice from Bangkok to [[Bremen]], the [[Rickmers Group|Rickmer Line, full-rigged ship]], '''''Erik Rickmers''''' ({{flag|German Empire}}) of [[Bremerhaven]] went ashore on Scilly Rock. She later sank in deep water.<ref name=larn92/> Her crew of twenty-six took to the boats and landed on Bryher.<ref name=\"living memories\">{{cite magazine|title=Living Memories|work=The Islander|date=Spring 2009|pages=18\u201321}}</ref>\n* 26 October &mdash; barque '''''Parame''''' ({{flag|France}}) hit Scilly Rock, her crew of ten landed on Bryher. Her cargo of coconuts was salvaged.<ref name=\"living memories\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of shipwrecks]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of Cornwall]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of the Seven Stones Reef]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* See further literature and details: [http://www.shipwrecks.uk.com Shipwrecks UK]\n\n{{Isles of Scilly}}\n{{Sailing Vessels and Rigs}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks of the United Kingdom|Scilly]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly| List of shipwrecks of the Isles of Scilly]]\n[[Category:Isles of Scilly-related lists|Shipwrecks]]\n[[Category:19th century in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:19th-century maritime incidents]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_shipwrecks_of_the_Isles_of_Scilly_(19th_century)"}
{"title_page": "Fistral Bay Hotel", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=Needs detailed copy-edit for grammar and prose. }}\n\n{{Infobox hotel\n| name = Fistral Bay Hotel\n| former_names = The Fistral Bay Hotel\n| image = Fistral Bay Hotel.jpg\n| status = Closed\n| address = 1 Pentire Ave, Newquay TR7 1NZ\n| location = Newquay, Cornwall,UK\n| caption = \n| opened_date = March 1931\n| floor_count = 4\n| architectural_style = Art-Deco\n| renovation_date = TBD\n| rooms = 60\n| website = www.fistralbayhotel.co.uk\n| map_caption = \n| ren_cost = 10 Million (Approximately)\n| architect = John Sansom\n}}\n\n[[File:North-Northwest from the Fistral Bay Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 170164.jpg|thumb|234x234px|View From room 205.]]\n'''Fistral Bay Hotel''' is an abandoned hotel located in [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. It was opened in 1931 and is built in a prominent position overlooking [[Fistral Beach]] and The Golf Links. \n\nAlthough local residents at the time considered the hotel \"risky and unwelcome\", the hotel eventually reduced the negative impact on the harbour economy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cornwalllive.com/news/inside-eerie-derelict-newquay-hotel-955407 |title=Inside the eerie hotel that has stood derelict for more than a decade|last=Smallcombe|first=Mike|date=2017-12-30|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> The hotel has 60 rooms.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel thrived during the 1950s and 1960s, as Newquay became a beneficiary of the diversion of domestic holiday demand to Cornwall and Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cornwalllive.com/news/cornwall-news/popular-cornwall-hotels-closed-2000s-2590671|title=The popular hotels of Cornwall lost over the past two decades|last=Becquart|first=Charlotte|date=2019-03-03|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> The hotel closed in 2006 after 75 years of business. It fell into disrepair and is widely regarded as \"the town\u2019s biggest eyesore.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> As of December 2019, a businessman plans to purchase the former Fistral Bay Hotel as part of proposal to renovate and reopen the building as a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newquayvoice.co.uk |title=A bid to Restore Hotel to former Glory|last=Wilkins|first=Warren|date=December 2019|work=The Newquay Voice}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel officially opened on Easter weekend, 1931.\n\nDuring the early 1930's, accommodation for visitors in Newquay increased as the town's popularity grew among tourists. Many existing hotels expanded during this time such as the [[Great Western Hotel (Newquay)|Great Western Hotel]] and the now-demolished St. Brannock's Hotel.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|title=Newquay Hotels|date=9 April 1931|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1931}}</ref> However, the art-decor themed Fistral Bay Hotel and The Pentire Hotel became the first purpose-built hotels in [[Pentire, Cornwall|Pentire]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe hotel appears in computer dating pioneer [[Joan Ball|Joan Ball's]] autobiography \"Just Me,\" where the author describes having stayed in [[Newquay]] for a short while during [[World War II|World War 2]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSqdBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=%22Fistral+Bay+Hotel%22+-wikipedia#v=onepage&q=%22Fistral%20Bay%20Hotel%22%20-wikipedia&f=false|title=Just Me by Joan Ball|last=Joan|first=Ball|date=2012|website=Google Ebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|isbn=9781312560147}}</ref>\n\n=== Hotel Fire ===\nOn the fifth of May, 1957, normal plans to open the hotel during the summer were delayed when a fire broke out. Someone from the neighboring Phelima hotel reported flames coming from the foyer, followed by cracking windows and visible smoke plumes. The local fire department successfully extinguished the fire. Workmen were on site the next day to repair damage.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hotel Fire At Newquay|date=May 1957|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Newquay]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in England]]\n__INDEX__\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=Needs detailed copy-edit for grammar and prose. }}\n\n{{Infobox hotel\n| name = Fistral Bay Hotel\n| former_names = The Fistral Bay Hotel\n| image = Fistral Bay Hotel.jpg\n| status = Closed\n| address = 1 Pentire Ave, Newquay TR7 1NZ\n| location = Newquay, Cornwall,UK\n| caption = \n| opened_date = March 1931\n| floor_count = 4\n| architectural_style = Art-Deco\n| renovation_date = TBD\n| rooms = 60\n| website = www.fistralbayhotel.co.uk\n| map_caption = \n| ren_cost = 10 Million (Approximately)\n| architect = John Sansom\n}}\n\n[[File:North-Northwest from the Fistral Bay Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 170164.jpg|thumb|234x234px|View From room 205.]]\n'''Fistral Bay Hotel''' is an abandoned hotel located in [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. It was opened in 1931 and is built in a prominent position overlooking [[Fistral Beach]] and The Golf Links. \n\nAlthough local residents at the time considered the hotel \"risky and unwelcome\", the hotels eventually reduced the negative impact on the harbour economy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cornwalllive.com/news/inside-eerie-derelict-newquay-hotel-955407 |title=Inside the eerie hotel that has stood derelict for more than a decade|last=Smallcombe|first=Mike|date=2017-12-30|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> The hotel has 60 guest rooms.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel thrived during the 1950s and 1960s, as Newquay became a beneficiary of the diversion of domestic holiday demand to Cornwall and Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cornwalllive.com/news/cornwall-news/popular-cornwall-hotels-closed-2000s-2590671|title=The popular hotels of Cornwall lost over the past two decades|last=Becquart|first=Charlotte|date=2019-03-03|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> The hotel closed in 2006 after 75 years of business. It fell into disrepair and is widely regarded as \"the town\u2019s biggest eyesore.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> As of December 2019, a businessman plans to purchase the former Fistral Bay Hotel as part of proposal to renovate and reopen the building as a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newquayvoice.co.uk |title=A bid to Restore Hotel to former Glory|last=Wilkins|first=Warren|date=December 2019|work=The Newquay Voice}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel officially opened on Easter weekend, 1931.\n\nDuring the early 1930's, accommodation for visitors in Newquay increased as the town's popularity grew among tourists. Many existing hotels expanded during this time such as the [[Great Western Hotel (Newquay)|Great Western Hotel]] and the now-demolished St. Brannock's Hotel.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|title=Newquay Hotels|date=9 April 1931|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1931}}</ref> However, the art-deco themed Fistral Bay Hotel and The Pentire Hotel became the first purpose-built hotels in [[Pentire, Cornwall|Pentire]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe hotel appears in computer dating pioneer [[Joan Ball|Joan Ball's]] autobiography \"Just Me,\" where the author describes having to stay in [[Newquay]] for a short while during [[World War II|World War 2]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSqdBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=%22Fistral+Bay+Hotel%22+-wikipedia#v=onepage&q=%22Fistral%20Bay%20Hotel%22%20-wikipedia&f=false|title=Just Me by Joan Ball|last=Joan|first=Ball|date=2012|website=Google Ebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|isbn=9781312560147}}</ref>\n\n=== Hotel Fire ===\nOn the fifth of May, 1957, normal plans to open the hotel during the summer were delayed when a fire broke out. Someone from the neighboring Phelima hotel reported flames coming from the foyer, followed by cracking windows and visible smoke plumes. The local fire department successfully extinguished the fire. Workmen were on site the next day to repair damage.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hotel Fire At Newquay|date=May 1957|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Newquay]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in England]]\n__INDEX__\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "Shoumyab", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fistral_Bay_Hotel"}
{"title_page": "1993 Los Angeles Raiders season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL team season\n| team            = Los Angeles Raiders\n| year            = 1993\n| record          = 10\u20136\n| division_place  = 2nd [[AFC West]]\n| coach           = [[Art Shell]]\n| general manager = [[Al Davis]]\n| owner           = Al Davis\n| stadium         = [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum|L.A. Memorial Coliseum]]\n| radio           = [[KLAC]]\n| playoffs        =  '''Won''' [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs|Wild Card playoffs]] ([[1993 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]]) 42\u201324<br>Lost [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs|Divisional playoffs]] (at [[1993 Buffalo Bills season|Bills]]) 23\u201329\n| shortnavlink    = Raiders seasons\n}}\n\nThe '''1993 Los Angeles Raiders season''' was the franchise's 34th season overall, and the franchise's 24th season in the [[National Football League]]. The team improved upon its 7\u20139 record in the previous season and returned to the NFL playoffs after a one-year absence, but lost in the AFC Divisional game to the [[1993 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].\n\nThis was the Raiders\u2019 final playoff appearance in Los Angeles, and would not return to the playoffs until [[2000 Oakland Raiders season|2000]], when the franchise returned to Oakland.\n\n==Offseason==\n\nDuring the offseason the Raiders signed quarterback [[Jeff Hostetler]] from the New York Giants to lead the offense.  [[Joe Kelly (American football)|Joe Kelly]] a former first round pick of the Bengals was signed to fill the middle lineback slot.  Left tackle [[Gerald Perry (American football)|Gerald Perry]] was signed from the Rams to solidify the left tackle position which the Raiders had struggled to fill since the retirement of former Raider left tackles [[Bruce Davis (offensive tackle)|Bruce Davis]] and [[Art Shell]].  [[Marcus Allen]] the team's all-time leading rusher was allowed to leave as a free agent and later signed with the Kansas City Chiefs.  To fill his spot the Raiders signed running back [[Gaston Green]] formally of the Denver Broncos.  Green did not make the team and was cut prior to the 1993 season.  The Los Angeles Raiders also brought back [[James Lofton]] from the Buffalo Bills.  Lofton played for the Raiders during the 1987\u20131988 seasons.  Like Green he was cut prior to the 1993 season.<ref>The 1993 Los Angeles Raidersr Media Guide</ref>\n\n===NFL draft===\n\nThe 1993 draft for the Los Angeles Raiders eventually produced several starters.  With the 12th pick in the first round the Raiders drafted safety [[Patrick Bates]] from Texas A&M.  The Raiders did not have a second round pick.  In the third round with the 58th pick the team drafted quarterback [[Billy Joe Hobert]] from Washington.  Also in the third round with the 72nd pick the Raiders took defensive back [[James Trapp]] from Clemson.  In the fifth round the team drafted wide receiver [[Olanda Truitt]] from Mississippi State. The Raiders next pick occurred in the seventh round and with the 181st pick the team took linebacker [[Greg Biekert]] from Colorado.  The Raiders final pick of the 1993 draft occurred in the 8th round.  The Raiders drafted running back [[Greg Robinson (running back)|Greg Robinson]] from La-Monroe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakland/Los Angeles Raiders All-Time Draft Listing \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/draft/rai.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdYMtsR?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/draft/rai.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> Greg Biekert was the best of the group.  He went on to become a primary starter in 1994 and was a starter for the Raiders until 2001.  He started 123 out of a possible 144 games with the Raiders with 15 sacks, 5 fumble recoveries and 3 interceptions.  As the Raiders middle linebacker he also recorded 704 tackles and 212 assists with the Raiders.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greg Biekert Statistics \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BiekGr20.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdYoMDA?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BiekGr20.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> As a rookie running back Greg Robinson started 12 games and led the 1993 Los Angeles Raiders in rushing with 591 yards and a touchdown.  He also added 15 receptions for 142 yards.<ref name=\"Ref-1\">{{cite web|title=1993 Los Angeles Raiders Statistics &amp; Players \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZAc9I?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> James Trapp was the third best of the bunch and he stayed on the Raiders roster as a sometime starter and as a reserve until the end of the 1996 season.  He then spent four years with the Ravens and helped Baltimore achieve their first Super Bowl victory.  With the Raiders he started 26 out of 88 games that he appeared in which included 4 interceptions and 3 fumble recoveries.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/TrapJa20.htm</ref> Olanda Truitt ended up leaving Los Angeles prior to the 1993 season and spent one year with the Vikings before spending two straight seasons with Washington.  During that time he caught just 15 passes for 283 yards.  In 1996, he returned to the Raiders and played two more years for them.  He ended his career with just 22 catches.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/TruiOl00.htm</ref> Hobert appeared in just 12 games for the Raiders between 1993\u20131996 which included 5 starts.  Hobert went 0\u20135 as the Raiders starter in 1995\u20131996 and eventually left the team.  He passed for 3,371 yards with the Raiders, Saints and Bills.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HobeBi00.htm</ref> Safety Patrick Bates was the Raiders first round choice in the 1993 draft.  He played for the Raiders for only two years (93\u201394) recording just 69 tackles in 29 game appearances with the Raiders.  In 1996, he played one season with Atlanta.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BatePa20.htm</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n{{NFL final staff\n| year = 1993\n| team = Los Angeles Raiders\n\n| front_office =\n* President of the General Partner \u2013 [[Al Davis]]\n* Director of Football Operations \u2013 [[Steve Ortmayer]]\n* Senior Executive \u2013 [[John Herrera (gridiron football)|John Herrera]]\n\n| head_coach =\n* Head Coach \u2013 [[Art Shell]]\n\n| offensive =\n* Offense \u2013 [[Tom Walsh (American football)|Tom Walsh]]\n* Offensive Backs \u2013 [[Joe Scannella]]\n* Wide Receivers \u2013 [[Fred Biletnikoff]]\n* Tight Ends \u2013 [[Terry Robiskie]]\n* Offensive Line \u2013 [[Bill Meyers]]\n* Offensive Line \u2013 [[Mike White (American football coach)|Mike White]]\n\n| defensive =\n* Defense/Linebackers \u2013 [[Gunther Cunningham]]\n* Defensive Line \u2013 [[Ray Hamilton]]\n* Linebackers \u2013 [[Jim Haslett]]\n* Defensive Backs \u2013 [[Odis McKinney]]\n* Defensive Backs \u2013 [[Jack Stanton]]\n\n| special_teams =\n* Special Teams \u2013 [[Steve Ortmayer]]\n\n| strength =\n* Strength and Conditioning \u2013 [[Todd Sperber]]\n* Strength and Conditioning \u2013 [[Doug Wilkerson]]\n}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{NFL season roster\n| year = 1993\n| team = Los Angeles Raiders\n\n| quarterbacks =\n{{NFLplayer|11|Vince Evans}}\n{{NFLplayer|12|Billy Joe Hobert|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|15|Jeff Hostetler}}\n\n| running_backs =\n{{NFLplayer|38|Nick Bell|d=American football}}\n{{NFLplayer|23|Randy Jordan|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|41|Napoleon McCallum}}\n{{NFLplayer|21|Tyrone Montgomery|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Greg Robinson|d=running back|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|35|Steve Smith|d=running back|FB}}\n\n| wide_receivers =\n{{NFLplayer|81|Tim Brown|d=American football|PR}}\n{{NFLplayer|83|Willie Gault}}\n{{NFLplayer|86|Rocket Ismail|rookie=y|KR}}\n{{NFLplayer|82|James Jett|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|89|Alexander Wright|d=American football}}\n\n| tight_ends =\n{{NFLplayer|87|Andrew Glover|d=American football}}\n{{NFLplayer|88|Ethan Horton}}\n\n| offensive_linemen =\n{{NFLplayer|65|Max Montoya|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|72|Don Mosebar|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|64|Todd Peat|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|71|Gerald Perry|d=American football|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|78|Greg Skrepenak|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|67|Dan Turk|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|68|Bruce Wilkerson|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|76|Steve Wisniewski|G}}\n\n| defensive_linemen =\n{{NFLplayer|97|Willie Broughton|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|74|Nolan Harrison|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|75|Howie Long|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|91|Chester McGlockton|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|94|Anthony Smith|d=defensive end|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|93|Greg Townsend|DE}}\n\n| linebackers =\n{{NFLplayer|54|Greg Biekert|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|56|Aundray Bruce|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|52|Mike Jones|d=linebacker|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|57|Joe Kelly|d=American football|MLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|99|Winston Moss|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|51|Aaron Wallace|OLB}}\n\n| defensive_backs =\n{{NFLplayer|33|Eddie Anderson|d=safety|FS}}\n{{NFLplayer|46|Torin Dorn|CB}}\n{{NFLplayer|20|Derrick Hoskins|SS}}\n{{NFLplayer|25|Dan Land|S}}\n{{NFLplayer|36|Terry McDaniel|CB}}\n{{NFLplayer|43|Elvis Patterson|DB}}\n{{NFLplayer|37|James Trapp|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|48|Lionel Washington|CB}}\n\n| special_teams =\n{{NFLplayer|&nbsp;7|Jeff Gossett|P}}\n{{NFLplayer|18|Jeff Jaeger|K}}\n\n| reserve_lists =\n\n| practice_squad =\n}}\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Schedule===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Week\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! Result\n! Attendance\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 1\n| September 5, 1993\n| [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n| W 24\u20137\n| <center>44,120</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 2\n| September 12, 1993\n| at [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n| W 17\u201313\n| <center>58,836</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 3\n| September 19, 1993\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n| L 19\u201316\n| <center>48,617</center>\n|-\n| 4\n| colspan=4 align=\"center\" | ''Bye''\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 5\n| October 3, 1993\n| at [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n| L 24\u20139\n| <center>77,395</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 6\n| October 10, 1993\n| [[New York Jets]]\n| W 24\u201320\n| <center>41,627</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 7\n| October 18, 1993\n| at [[Denver Broncos]]\n| W 23\u201320\n| <center>75,712</center>\n|-\n| 8\n| colspan=4 align=\"center\" | ''Bye''\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 9\n| October 31, 1993\n| [[San Diego Chargers]]\n| L 30\u201323\n| <center>45,122</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 10\n| November 7, 1993\n| at [[Chicago Bears]]\n| W 16\u201314\n| <center>59,750</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 11\n| November 14, 1993\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n| L 31\u201320\n| <center>66,553</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 12\n| November 21, 1993\n| at [[San Diego Chargers]]\n| W 12\u20137\n| <center>60,615</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 13\n| November 28, 1993\n| at [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n| L 16\u201310\n| <center>43,272</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 14\n| December 5, 1993\n| at [[Buffalo Bills]]\n| W 25\u201324\n| <center>79,478</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 15\n| December 12, 1993\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n| W 27\u201323\n| <center>38,161</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 16\n| December 19, 1993\n| [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n| W 27\u201320\n| <center>40,532</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 17\n| December 26, 1993\n| at [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| L 28\u20130\n| <center>54,482</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 18\n| January 2, 1994\n| [[Denver Broncos]]\n| W 33\u201330\n| <center>66,904</center>\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n{{1993 AFC West standings}}\n\n===Game details===\n*Week 1 \u2013 September 5 W 24\u20137 vs Minnesota Vikings\nJeff Hostetler completed 15 straight passes during the game which included a touchdown pass to Tim Brown.  Cornerback Terry McDaniel intercepted a Jim McMahon pass and returned it 36 yards for a touchdown. Rookie running back Greg Robinson scored his only regular season touchdown as a Raider. Hostetler also rushed for 34 yards and defensive end Anthony Smith recorded 2 sacks.\n*Week 2 \u2013 September 12 W 17\u201313 at Seattle Seahawks\nDefensive End Anthony Smith sacked Seahawks quarterback Rick Mirer four times. Rookie Patrick Bates and Terry McDaniel each intercepted a pass and Jeff Hostetler rushed for a touchdown and tossed a touchdown pass to Tim Brown.  Wide receivers Alexander Wright and Tim Brown totalled 13 receptions combined to pace the win.\n* Week 3 \u2013 Sep 19 L 19\u201316 vs Cleveland Browns\nThe Raiders dominated the Browns early and led 13\u20130.  Defensive tackle Chester McGlockton intercepted a Bernie Kosar pass which set up one of the Raiders two field goals.  After that the Browns defense pressured Hostetler by sacking him six times and holding him to just 94 yards passing. The Raiders gained one first down in the second half and committed eight penalties. Browns running back Eric Metcalf scored the game-winning touchdown with just seconds remaining.\n*Week 4 \u2013 Bye week\n*Week 5 \u2013 Oct 3 L 24\u20139 at Kansas City Chiefs\nFormer Raider Marcus Allen scored his 100th career rushing touchdown against his former team.  Hostetler missed the game due to a knee injury and with veteran [[Vince Evans]] serving in his place the Raiders were unable to beat their chief rivals.  The Raiders aided the Kansas City cause by committing 16 penalties for 173 yards.\n*Week 6  Oct 10 W 24\u201320 vs New York Jets\nRaiders overcame a 17\u20130 Jet lead to win. Head coach Art Shell pulled a struggling Hostetler and Evans replaced him and the aging quarterback completed 14 passes for 247 yards and two touchdowns.  During the third period and trailing 17\u20137 Evans hit Alexander Wright for a 68-yard touchdown pass.  The Jets scored on a field goal to retake the lead 20\u201317.  During a two-minute drill Evans drove the Raiders downfield.  A third down was converted into a first down on a pass to James Jett.  With four seconds remaining and with the ball inside the Jets one-yard line the Raiders ran a risky run play and running back Nick Bell scored a touchdown to defeat the New York Jets.\n*Week 7  Oct 18 W 23\u201320 at Denver Broncos\nOn Monday Night Football quarterback Jeff Hostetler went 15 of 24 for 2 touchdowns.  The Raiders dominated the first half and led 13\u20130 off two Jaeger field goals and a Hostetler touchdown pass to Alexander Wright.  Denver fought their way back and scored 17 unanswered points to take a 17\u201313 lead.  Raider James Jett scored on a 74-yard pass from Hostetler and the Raiders took the lead back from the Broncos.  John Elway drove Denver downfield and rookie kicker Jason Elam kicked a field goal to tie the game 20\u201320.  The Raiders responded with just seconds remaining with a Jeff Jaeger field goal from 53 yards away to beat the Broncos.\n*Week 8  Bye Week\n*Week 9  Oct 31 L 30\u201323 vs San Diego Chargers\nHalloween was all tricks for the Raiders and all treats for the Chargers as San Diego beat Los Angeles in a key game.  This didn't stop Jeff Hostetler from passing for a Raider record 424 yards.  The Raiders started the scoring on their first play from scrimmage with Tim Brown hauling in a Hostetler pass and racing 71 yards for a touchdown.  Later and with the score tied 10\u201310 both Hostetler and Brown hooked up again for a 38-yard touchdown.  San Diego retied the score 17\u201317 on a touchdown run by running back Marion Butts.  The Raiders drove down the field and with the ball inside the San Diego 10-yard line, defensive back Donald Frank intercepted a Hostetler pass and ran back the interception 102 yards for a touchdown and a 24\u201317 San Diego lead. The Raiders could not get back into the game and despite 156 receiving yards by Brown the Raiders were defeated by the Chargers.\n* Week 10 \u2013 November 7 W 16\u201314 at Chicago Bears\nFor the third time in five games the Raiders led early but saw their lead evaporate.  Greg Robinson rushed for 70 yards and Napoleon McCallum added 50 more and one touchdown to overcome 11 penalties and 3 sacks of Hostetler.  Los Angeles led 13\u20130 at halftime and just like the Cleveland game the Bears got themselves back in the game. The Raiders lead was cut to 13\u20137 on a Neal Anderson touchdown run but Jeff Jaeger saved the day by adding a field goal later in the fourth quarter. Bears quarterback [[Jim Harbaugh]] tossed a touchdown pass with just minutes remaining in the game to pull Chicago within two points.  The Bears recovered their onside kick and drove within field goal range.  Bears kicker Kevin Butler missed the field goal that would have won the game for Chicago.\n* Week 11 \u2013 November 14 L 31\u201320 vs Kansas City Chiefs\nOnce again the Raiders led early on a Hostetler touchdown pass to Ethan Horton and a touchdown run by Napoleon McCallum.  Leading 14\u20130, the Raiders allowed Kansas City to go on a 31\u20136 run to beat the Raiders for the second straight time.  Horton caught 6 passes for 69 yards and a touchdown against his old team.\n* Week 12 \u2013 November 21 W 12\u20137 at San Diego Chargers\nFor the second time in four games the Raiders faced the San Diego Chargers.  Jeff Jaeger kicked four field goals for the win but the Raiders had another nail biting game when San Diego scored a touchdown in the fourth quarter.  Rookies Greg Robinson and James Jett had stellar games.  Robinson accounted for 89 yards rushing and 13 yards receiving.  Jett caught 7 passes for 138 yards.  Also, future hall of famer Howie Long record two sacks.\n*Week 13 \u2013 November 28 L 16\u201310 at Cincinnati Bengals\nThe Bengals were 0\u201310 entering the game and led the Raiders 13\u20130 as the fourth quarter began.  The Raiders offense was unable to get anything going all day and two turnovers by Los Angeles granted them their fifth loss of the 1993 season. Chester McGlockton had three sacks.\n*Week 14 \u2013 Dec 5 W 25\u201324 at Buffalo Bills\nNeeding a win to keep their playoff hopes alive the Raiders overcame the three time AFC Champion Buffalo Bills.  Jeff Hostetler rushed for a touchdown and threw for another.  Jeff Jaeger added four field goals and Tim Brown caught 10 passes for 183 yards and a TD.  During the fourth quarter the Bills led the Raiders 24\u201319.  The Raiders defense forced Buffalo to punt.  The Raiders ran just three plays, the first coming on a short completion to running back Nick Bell and a second to wide receiver James Jett.  Then Hostetler knifed the football between three Buffalo defenders to receiver Tim Brown for a touchdown.  Buffalo was driving for a game-winning field goal when Nolan Harrison forced Buffalo running back Thurman Thomas to fumble and the Raiders defense recovered to seal a 25\u201324 win.\n*Week 15  Dec 12 W 27\u201323 vs Seattle Seahawks\nTying to maintain their playoff dreams the Raiders defeated Seattle with the help of Cornerback Terry McDaniel who had a key interception.  Hostetler, Jett and Brown all scored touchdowns after Seattle established a 9\u20133 lead.  Leading 27\u20139 the Raiders allowed Seattle to reenter the game and the Seahawks scored the final 14 points of the game to cut the Raider lead 27\u201323. After their second touchdown the Seahawks were unable to recover their onside kick which preserved a Raider win.\n*Week 16  Dec 19 W 27\u201320 vs Tampa Bay Buccaneers\nThe Raiders established a 14\u20130 lead before Tampa Bay forced their way back into the game.  Alexander Wright recorded his first 100+ yard game as a Raider and Jeff Hostetler rushed for his fifth touchdown of the season.  The Raiders defense recorded five sacks and forced 2 turnovers to preserve the victory.  Tampa Bay's final ditch effort to win ended on a botched onside kick attempt and the Raiders prevailed.\n*Week 17  Dec 26 L 28\u20130 at Green Bay Packers\nBrett Favre beat the Raiders for the first of what would be four wins versus the Silver and Black.  Sterling Sharpe torched the Raiders defense for 119 yards and a touchdown and the Packers running game burned the Raiders for 148 yards.  Trailing 14\u20130 quarterback Jeff Hostetler suffered a concussion during a sack and was forced to leave the game.  Vince Evans replaced him but fared no better than Hostetler as both men completed just 18 of 38 passes. This is the game that gave birth to the \"Lambeau Leap\" when LeRoy Butler received a lateral from Reggie White, whom recovered a fumble.  Tim Brown did add 80 yards receiving but a 25-yard fumble return and a long touchdown run gave the Packers an important 28\u20130 victory.\n*Week 18  Jan 2 W 33\u201330 vs Denver Broncos (OT)\nNeeding a win to make the playoffs the Los Angeles Raiders came back from a 17-point deficit twice in the game.  Late in the fourth quarter the Raiders trailed Denver 30\u201323 but Jeff Hostetler and his offense drove Los Angeles down the field.  On the final play of regulation Hostetler completed a third down pass to Alexander Wright for a 4-yard touchdown to force overtime.  Denver won the overtime coin toss and John Elway drove Denver to a field goal opportunity.  Rookie kicker Jason Elam missed his kick and the Raiders were granted new life.  Hostetler drove Los Angeles down field again and Jeff Jaeger kicked a 47-yard field goal to send the Raiders to the 1993 playoffs.  One week later the Raiders would host Denver again in the 1993 WildCard Playoffs.<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\n==Classic comebacks==\n\nThe 1993 season saw an enormous amount of Raider comebacks.  These comebacks included:\n<br />\n<br />1) In week six versus the New York Jets.  The Raiders trailed 17\u20130 before coming back to win 24\u201320<ref>{{cite web|title=New York Jets  at  Los Angeles Raiders \u2013 October 10th, 1993 \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199310100rai.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5h6q6ihT1?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199310100rai.htm |archivedate=May 28, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<br />2) In week fifteen versus the Seattle Seahawks the Raiders trailed 9\u20133 before coming back to win 27\u201323.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199312120rai.htm</ref>\n<br />\n<br />3) In week seventeen the Raiders trailed Denver 17\u20130 and came back twice to tie and later win the game 33\u201330.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199401020rai.htm</ref>\n\n==Playoffs==\n\n===AFC Wild Card===\n{{Americanfootballbox | title=Los Angeles Raiders 42, Denver Broncos 24\n|Road=Broncos\n|R1=7\n|R2=14\n|R3=0\n|R4=3\n|RT=24\n|Home='''Raiders'''\n|H1=14\n|H2=7\n|H3=14\n|H4=7\n|HT=42\n|stadium= [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]], [[Los Angeles, California]]\n|time= 4:00 p.m. [[North American Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]/1:00 p.m. [[Pacific Standard Time Zone|PST]]\n|weather= {{convert|70|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}, clear\n|TV=[[NFL on NBC|NBC]]\n|TVAnnouncers= [[Charlie Jones (sportscaster)|Charlie Jones]] and [[Todd Christensen]]\n|referee= [[Bob McElwee]]\n|attendance= 65,314\n}}\nBoth teams entered the game with poor running games and backfield injuries.  This made the passing attacks of both squads very important.  During the first half both John Elway and Jeff Hostetler dominated with each man throwing three touchdown passes.  After a 21\u201321 tie at halftime, Raiders running back [[Napoleon McCallum]] scored three rushing touchdowns in the second half to lead his team to the victory.  Quarterback Jeff Hostetler completed 13 of 19 passes for 294 yards and 3 touchdowns.  James Jett caught 3 passes for 111 yards and a touchdown.  Tim Brown caught 3 passes for 86 yards and a touchdown.  The game was tied 21\u201321 at halftime but the Raiders pulled away with McCallum's three touchdowns in the second half.\n\n===AFC Divisional Playoff===\n{{Americanfootballbox | title=Buffalo Bills 29, Los Angeles Raiders 23\n|Road=Raiders\n|R1=0\n|R2=17\n|R3=6\n|R4=0\n|RT=23\n|Home='''Bills'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=13\n|H3=9\n|H4=7\n|HT=29\n|stadium= [[Rich Stadium]], [[Orchard Park (town), New York|Orchard Park, New York]]\n|time= 12:30 p.m. [[North American Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= {{convert|0|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}, cloudy\n|TV=[[NFL on NBC|NBC]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Marv Albert]] and [[Paul Maguire]]\n|referee= [[Red Cashion]]\n|attendance= 61,923\n}}\nIn one of the coldest games in NFL history, the Bills overcame a 17\u20136 Raiders lead by scoring three times in a span of 6:18 in the second half.  During the second half the Bills defense dominated the Raiders offense by allowing the Raiders to earn just one first down.  Tim Brown caught 5 passes for 127 yards which included an 86-yard pass for his lone touchdown of the game.  The play is the Raiders longest postseason play ever.  Running back Napoleon McCallum scored twice which brought his 1993 postseason touchdown total to five.\n\n==Awards, records, and milestones==\n\n* [[Jeff Hostetler]], Single Game Record, 424 passing yards, achieved on October 31 against the Chargers.  That record was broken when Derek Carr passed for 513 yards against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in 2016.\n* [[Jeff Jaeger]], Single Season Record, Most Field Goals in One Season, 35 and most field goals attempted in a season, 44.\n* [[Jeff Jaeger]], Single Season Record, Most Points in One Season, 132.  This record would remain a Raider record until the 2010 season.\n* [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] recorded his first 1,000 yard receiving season\n* [[Jeff Hostetler]] became the first Raider since 1979 to pass for over 3,000 yards.  He also became just the third Raider at that time to accomplish that feat.<ref>Los Angeles Raiders: Official 1993 Yearbook. Prod. Steve Sabol. VHS. NFL Films, 1994.</ref>\n*Defensive end [[Howie Long]] retired following the season.  In 2000, he entered the Pro Football Hall of Fame.\n*Pro Bowl: Cornerback [[Terry McDaniel]], Wide Receiver Tim Brown, Guard [[Steve Wisniewski]], Guard [[Max Montoya]] and Defensive End/Tackle [[Howie Long]].\n*This season was so memorable that Raiders.com has devoted three 3 of 27 of its \"Fantastic Finishes\" stories to the 1993 season.  The games that appear are the 12/5 game at Buffalo, the 10/10 game against the Jets and the 1/2/94 game against Denver.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakland Raiders \u2013 Greatest Moments |url=http://www.raiders.com/History/Default.aspx?id=874 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZZTdu?url=http://www.raiders.com/History/Default.aspx?id=874 |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n*Tim Browns 74-yard punt return for a touchdown was the second time that he returned a punt for a touchdown during his career.  He would only score one more time on a punt return and that would not occur again until 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Every Touchdown Scored by Tim Brown \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/score.cgi?id=BrowTi00 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdaPLAC?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/score.cgi?id=BrowTi00 |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> During the season, Brown became the Raiders all-time leader in punt return yardage by surpassing Neal Colize. Brown would eventually run his career punt return total to 3,272 yards and 3 touchdowns and a 10.2 average.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/career-returns.htm</ref>\n*[[Jeff Hostetler]] became just the third Raider ever to pass for 3,000 yards in one season.  At that time the others were [[Daryle Lamonica]] and [[Ken Stabler]].  Only five Raider quarterbacks have passed for 3,000 yards or more as a Raider since Hostetler.  This includes [[Rich Gannon]] (four times), [[Kerry Collins]] (twice), [[Carson Palmer]] (once), [[Derek Carr (American football)|Derek Carr]] (each of his four seasons thus far) and [[Jeff George]] (once).  The 1993 playoffs also marked Hostetler's first and only loss as a playoff starter.  Hostetler led the Giants to the Super Bowl championship in 1990 going 4\u20130 and the Raiders in 1993 with a 1\u20131 record.  In five playoff games, he completed 72 of 115 passes (62.6 percent) for 1,034 yards, seven touchdowns, no interceptions, and a 112.0 passer rating while going 4\u20131.\n\n==Team leaders==\n\n* Leading Passer [[Jeff Hostetler]], with 3,242 yards & 14 touchdowns\n* Leading rusher: [[Greg Robinson (running back)|Greg Robinson]] with 591 yards\n* Leading receiver: [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] with 80 receptions for 1,180 yards\n* Leading scorer: [[Jeff Jaeger]] with 132 points\n* Sack leader: [[Anthony Smith (defensive end)|Anthony Smith]] with 12.5 sacks\n* Leading Tackler: [[Winston Moss]] with 102 tackles\n* Interception leader: [[Terry McDaniel]] with 5 interceptions<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm Raiders on Pro Football Reference] ([https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZAc9I?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm Archived] 2009-05-11)\n* [http://www.jt-sw.com/football/pro/results.nsf/Teams/1993-lai Raiders on jt-sw.com]\n* [http://www.jt-sw.com/football/pro/stats.nsf/Annual/1993-lai Raiders stats on jt-sw.com]\n* Rinehart, Michael., [https://www.amazon.com/Complete-History-Angeles-Raiders-ebook/dp/B00E9DXEU2/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1381158899&sr=8-2&keywords=1993+los+angeles+raiders The Complete History of the 1993 Los Angeles Raiders. published on Amazon Kindle July 30, 2013]\n\n{{Las Vegas Raiders}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders seasons}}\n{{1993 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1993 Los Angeles Raiders season}}\n[[Category:1993 National Football League season by team|Los Angeles Raiders]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Raiders seasons]]\n[[Category:1993 in sports in California|Los]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL season\n| team            = Los Angeles Raiders\n| year            = 1993\n| record          = 10\u20136\n| division_place  = 2nd [[AFC West]]\n| coach           = [[Art Shell]]\n| general manager = [[Al Davis]]\n| owner           = Al Davis\n| stadium         = [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum|L.A. Memorial Coliseum]]\n| radio           = [[KLAC]]\n| playoffs        =  '''Won''' [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs|Wild Card playoffs]] ([[1993 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]]) 42\u201324<br>Lost [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs|Divisional playoffs]] (at [[1993 Buffalo Bills season|Bills]]) 23\u201329\n| shortnavlink    = Raiders seasons\n}}\n\nThe '''1993 Los Angeles Raiders season''' was the franchise's 34th season overall, and the franchise's 24th season in the [[National Football League]]. The team improved upon its 7\u20139 record in the previous season and returned to the NFL playoffs after a one-year absence, but lost in the AFC Divisional game to the [[1993 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].\n\nThis was the Raiders\u2019 final playoff appearance in Los Angeles, and would not return to the playoffs until [[2000 Oakland Raiders season|2000]], when the franchise returned to Oakland.\n\n==Offseason==\n\nDuring the offseason the Raiders signed quarterback [[Jeff Hostetler]] from the New York Giants to lead the offense.  [[Joe Kelly (American football)|Joe Kelly]] a former first round pick of the Bengals was signed to fill the middle lineback slot.  Left tackle [[Gerald Perry (American football)|Gerald Perry]] was signed from the Rams to solidify the left tackle position which the Raiders had struggled to fill since the retirement of former Raider left tackles [[Bruce Davis (offensive tackle)|Bruce Davis]] and [[Art Shell]].  [[Marcus Allen]] the teams all-time leading rusher was allowed to leave as a free agent and later signed with the Kansas City Chiefs.  To fill his spot the Raiders signed running back [[Gaston Green]] formally of the Denver Broncos.  Green did not make the team and was cut prior to the 1993 season.  The Los Angeles Raiders also brought back [[James Lofton]] from the Buffalo Bills.  Lofton played for the Raiders during the 1987\u20131988 seasons.  Like Green he was cut prior to the 1993 season.<ref>The 1993 Los Angeles Raidersr Media Guide</ref>\n\n===NFL draft===\n\nThe 1993 draft for the Los Angeles Raiders eventually produced several starters.  With the 12th pick in the first round the Raiders drafted safety [[Patrick Bates]] from Texas A&M.  The Raiders did not have a second round pick.  In the third round with the 58th pick the team drafted quarterback [[Billy Joe Hobert]] from Washington.  Also in the third round with the 72nd pick the Raiders took defensive back [[James Trapp]] from Clemson.  In the fifth round the team drafted wide receiver [[Olanda Truitt]] from Mississippi State. The Raiders next pick occurred in the seventh round and with the 181st pick the team took linebacker [[Greg Biekert]] from Colorado.  The Raiders final pick of the 1993 draft occurred in the 8th round.  The Raiders drafted running back [[Greg Robinson (running back)|Greg Robinson]] from La-Monroe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakland/Los Angeles Raiders All-Time Draft Listing \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/draft/rai.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdYMtsR?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/draft/rai.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> Greg Biekert was the best of the group.  He went on to become a primary starter in 1994 and was a starter for the Raiders until 2001.  He started 123 out of a possible 144 games with the Raiders with 15 sacks, 5 fumble recoveries and 3 interceptions.  As the Raiders middle linebacker he also recorded 704 tackles and 212 assists with the Raiders.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greg Biekert Statistics \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BiekGr20.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdYoMDA?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BiekGr20.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> As a rookie running back Greg Robinson started 12 games and led the 1993 Los Angeles Raiders in rushing with 591 yards and a touchdown.  He also added 15 receptions for 142 yards.<ref name=\"Ref-1\">{{cite web|title=1993 Los Angeles Raiders Statistics &amp; Players \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZAc9I?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> James Trapp was the third best of the bunch and he stayed on the Raiders roster as a sometime starter and as a reserve until the end of the 1996 season.  He then spent four years with the Ravens and helped Baltimore achieve their first Super Bowl victory.  With the Raiders he started 26 out of 88 games that he appeared in which included 4 interceptions and 3 fumble recoveries.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/TrapJa20.htm</ref> Olanda Truitt ended up leaving Los Angeles prior to the 1993 season and spent one year with the Vikings before spending two straight seasons with Washington.  During that time he caught just 15 passes for 283 yards.  In 1996, he returned to the Raiders and played two more years for them.  He ended his career with just 22 catches.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/TruiOl00.htm</ref> Hobert appeared in just 12 games for the Raiders between 1993\u20131996 which included 5 starts.  Hobert went 0\u20135 as the Raiders starter in 1995\u20131996 and eventually left the team.  He passed for 3,371 yards with the Raiders, Saints and Bills.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HobeBi00.htm</ref> Safety Patrick Bates was the Raiders first round choice in the 1993 draft.  He played for the Raiders for only two years (93\u201394) recording just 69 tackles in 29 game appearances with the Raiders.  In 1996, he played one season with Atlanta.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BatePa20.htm</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n{{NFL final staff\n| year = 1993\n| team = Los Angeles Raiders\n\n| front_office =\n* President of the General Partner \u2013 [[Al Davis]]\n* Director of Football Operations \u2013 [[Steve Ortmayer]]\n* Senior Executive \u2013 [[John Herrera (gridiron football)|John Herrera]]\n\n| head_coach =\n* Head Coach \u2013 [[Art Shell]]\n\n| offensive =\n* Offense \u2013 [[Tom Walsh (American football)|Tom Walsh]]\n* Offensive Backs \u2013 [[Joe Scannella]]\n* Wide Receivers \u2013 [[Fred Biletnikoff]]\n* Tight Ends \u2013 [[Terry Robiskie]]\n* Offensive Line \u2013 [[Bill Meyers]]\n* Offensive Line \u2013 [[Mike White (American football coach)|Mike White]]\n\n| defensive =\n* Defense/Linebackers \u2013 [[Gunther Cunningham]]\n* Defensive Line \u2013 [[Ray Hamilton]]\n* Linebackers \u2013 [[Jim Haslett]]\n* Defensive Backs \u2013 [[Odis McKinney]]\n* Defensive Backs \u2013 [[Jack Stanton]]\n\n| special_teams =\n* Special Teams \u2013 [[Steve Ortmayer]]\n\n| strength =\n* Strength and Conditioning \u2013 [[Todd Sperber]]\n* Strength and Conditioning \u2013 [[Doug Wilkerson]]\n}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{NFL season roster\n| year = 1993\n| team = Los Angeles Raiders\n\n| quarterbacks =\n{{NFLplayer|11|Vince Evans}}\n{{NFLplayer|12|Billy Joe Hobert|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|15|Jeff Hostetler}}\n\n| running_backs =\n{{NFLplayer|38|Nick Bell|d=American football}}\n{{NFLplayer|23|Randy Jordan|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|41|Napoleon McCallum}}\n{{NFLplayer|21|Tyrone Montgomery|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Greg Robinson|d=running back|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|35|Steve Smith|d=running back|FB}}\n\n| wide_receivers =\n{{NFLplayer|81|Tim Brown|d=American football|PR}}\n{{NFLplayer|83|Willie Gault}}\n{{NFLplayer|86|Rocket Ismail|rookie=y|KR}}\n{{NFLplayer|82|James Jett|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|89|Alexander Wright|d=American football}}\n\n| tight_ends =\n{{NFLplayer|87|Andrew Glover|d=American football}}\n{{NFLplayer|88|Ethan Horton}}\n\n| offensive_linemen =\n{{NFLplayer|65|Max Montoya|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|72|Don Mosebar|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|64|Todd Peat|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|71|Gerald Perry|d=American football|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|78|Greg Skrepenak|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|67|Dan Turk|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|68|Bruce Wilkerson|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|76|Steve Wisniewski|G}}\n\n| defensive_linemen =\n{{NFLplayer|97|Willie Broughton|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|74|Nolan Harrison|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|75|Howie Long|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|91|Chester McGlockton|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|94|Anthony Smith|d=defensive end|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|93|Greg Townsend|DE}}\n\n| linebackers =\n{{NFLplayer|54|Greg Biekert|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|56|Aundray Bruce|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|52|Mike Jones|d=linebacker|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|57|Joe Kelly|d=American football|MLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|99|Winston Moss|OLB}}\n{{NFLplayer|51|Aaron Wallace|OLB}}\n\n| defensive_backs =\n{{NFLplayer|33|Eddie Anderson|d=safety|FS}}\n{{NFLplayer|46|Torin Dorn|CB}}\n{{NFLplayer|20|Derrick Hoskins|SS}}\n{{NFLplayer|25|Dan Land|S}}\n{{NFLplayer|36|Terry McDaniel|CB}}\n{{NFLplayer|43|Elvis Patterson|DB}}\n{{NFLplayer|37|James Trapp|rookie=y}}\n{{NFLplayer|48|Lionel Washington|CB}}\n\n| special_teams =\n{{NFLplayer|&nbsp;7|Jeff Gossett|P}}\n{{NFLplayer|18|Jeff Jaeger|K}}\n\n| reserve_lists =\n\n| practice_squad =\n}}\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Schedule===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Week\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! Result\n! Attendance\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 1\n| September 5, 1993\n| [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n| W 24\u20137\n| <center>44,120</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 2\n| September 12, 1993\n| at [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n| W 17\u201313\n| <center>58,836</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 3\n| September 19, 1993\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n| L 19\u201316\n| <center>48,617</center>\n|-\n| 4\n| colspan=4 align=\"center\" | ''Bye''\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 5\n| October 3, 1993\n| at [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n| L 24\u20139\n| <center>77,395</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 6\n| October 10, 1993\n| [[New York Jets]]\n| W 24\u201320\n| <center>41,627</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 7\n| October 18, 1993\n| at [[Denver Broncos]]\n| W 23\u201320\n| <center>75,712</center>\n|-\n| 8\n| colspan=4 align=\"center\" | ''Bye''\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 9\n| October 31, 1993\n| [[San Diego Chargers]]\n| L 30\u201323\n| <center>45,122</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 10\n| November 7, 1993\n| at [[Chicago Bears]]\n| W 16\u201314\n| <center>59,750</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 11\n| November 14, 1993\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n| L 31\u201320\n| <center>66,553</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 12\n| November 21, 1993\n| at [[San Diego Chargers]]\n| W 12\u20137\n| <center>60,615</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 13\n| November 28, 1993\n| at [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n| L 16\u201310\n| <center>43,272</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 14\n| December 5, 1993\n| at [[Buffalo Bills]]\n| W 25\u201324\n| <center>79,478</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 15\n| December 12, 1993\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n| W 27\u201323\n| <center>38,161</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 16\n| December 19, 1993\n| [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n| W 27\u201320\n| <center>40,532</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 17\n| December 26, 1993\n| at [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| L 28\u20130\n| <center>54,482</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 18\n| January 2, 1994\n| [[Denver Broncos]]\n| W 33\u201330\n| <center>66,904</center>\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n{{1993 AFC West standings}}\n\n===Game details===\n*Week 1 \u2013 September 5 W 24\u20137 vs Minnesota Vikings\nJeff Hostetler completed 15 straight passes during the game which included a touchdown pass to Tim Brown.  Cornerback Terry McDaniel intercepted a Jim McMahon pass and returned it 36 yards for a touchdown. Rookie running back Greg Robinson scored his only regular season touchdown as a Raider. Hostetler also rushed for 34 yards and defensive end Anthony Smith recorded 2 sacks.\n*Week 2 \u2013 September 12 W 17\u201313 at Seattle Seahawks\nDefensive End Anthony Smith sacked Seahawks quarterback Rick Mirer four times. Rookie Patrick Bates and Terry McDaniel each intercepted a pass and Jeff Hostetler rushed for a touchdown and tossed a touchdown pass to Tim Brown.  Wide receivers Alexander Wright and Tim Brown totalled 13 receptions combined to pace the win.\n* Week 3 \u2013 Sep 19 L 19\u201316 vs Cleveland Browns\nThe Raiders dominated the Browns early and led 13\u20130.  Defensive tackle Chester McGlockton intercepted a Bernie Kosar pass which set up one of the Raiders two field goals.  After that the Browns defense pressured Hostetler by sacking him six times and holding him to just 94 yards passing. The Raiders gained one first down in the second half and committed eight penalties. Browns running back Eric Metcalf scored the game-winning touchdown with just seconds remaining.\n*Week 4 \u2013 Bye week\n*Week 5 \u2013 Oct 3 L 24\u20139 at Kansas City Chiefs\nFormer Raider Marcus Allen scored his 100th career rushing touchdown against his former team.  Hostetler missed the game due to a knee injury and with veteran [[Vince Evans]] serving in his place the Raiders were unable to beat their chief rivals.  The Raiders aided the Kansas City cause by committing 16 penalties for 173 yards.\n*Week 6  Oct 10 W 24\u201320 vs New York Jets\nRaiders overcame a 17\u20130 Jet lead to win. Head coach Art Shell pulled a struggling Hostetler and Evans replaced him and the aging quarterback completed 14 passes for 247 yards and two touchdowns.  During the third period and trailing 17\u20137 Evans hit Alexander Wright for a 68-yard touchdown pass.  The Jets scored on a field goal to retake the lead 20\u201317.  During a two-minute drill Evans drove the Raiders downfield.  A third down was converted into a first down on a pass to James Jett.  With four seconds remaining and with the ball inside the Jets one-yard line the Raiders ran a risky run play and running back Nick Bell scored a touchdown to defeat the New York Jets.\n*Week 7  Oct 18 W 23\u201320 at Denver Broncos\nOn Monday Night Football quarterback Jeff Hostetler went 15 of 24 for 2 touchdowns.  The Raiders dominated the first half and led 13\u20130 off two Jaeger field goals and a Hostetler touchdown pass to Alexander Wright.  Denver fought their way back and scored 17 unanswered points to take a 17\u201313 lead.  Raider James Jett scored on a 74-yard pass from Hostetler and the Raiders took the lead back from the Broncos.  John Elway drove Denver downfield and rookie kicker Jason Elam kicked a field goal to tie the game 20\u201320.  The Raiders responded with just seconds remaining with a Jeff Jaeger field goal from 53 yards away to beat the Broncos.\n*Week 8  Bye Week\n*Week 9  Oct 31 L 30\u201323 vs San Diego Chargers\nHalloween was all tricks for the Raiders and all treats for the Chargers as San Diego beat Los Angeles in a key game.  This didn't stop Jeff Hostetler from passing for a Raider record 424 yards.  The Raiders started the scoring on their first play from scrimmage with Tim Brown hauling in a Hostetler pass and racing 71 yards for a touchdown.  Later and with the score tied 10\u201310 both Hostetler and Brown hooked up again for a 38-yard touchdown.  San Diego retied the score 17\u201317 on a touchdown run by running back Marion Butts.  The Raiders drove down the field and with the ball inside the San Diego 10-yard line, defensive back Donald Frank intercepted a Hostetler pass and ran back the interception 102 yards for a touchdown and a 24\u201317 San Diego lead. The Raiders could not get back into the game and despite 156 receiving yards by Brown the Raiders were defeated by the Chargers.\n* Week 10 \u2013 November 7 W 16\u201314 at Chicago Bears\nFor the third time in five games the Raiders led early but saw their lead evaporate.  Greg Robinson rushed for 70 yards and Napoleon McCallum added 50 more and one touchdown to overcome 11 penalties and 3 sacks of Hostetler.  Los Angeles led 13\u20130 at halftime and just like the Cleveland game the Bears got themselves back in the game. The Raiders lead was cut to 13\u20137 on a Neal Anderson touchdown run but Jeff Jaeger saved the day by adding a field goal later in the fourth quarter. Bears quarterback [[Jim Harbaugh]] tossed a touchdown pass with just minutes remaining in the game to pull Chicago within two points.  The Bears recovered their onside kick and drove within field goal range.  Bears kicker Kevin Butler missed the field goal that would have won the game for Chicago.\n* Week 11 \u2013 November 14 L 31\u201320 vs Kansas City Chiefs\nOnce again the Raiders led early on a Hostetler touchdown pass to Ethan Horton and a touchdown run by Napoleon McCallum.  Leading 14\u20130, the Raiders allowed Kansas City to go on a 31\u20136 run to beat the Raiders for the second straight time.  Horton caught 6 passes for 69 yards and a touchdown against his old team.\n* Week 12 \u2013 November 21 W 12\u20137 at San Diego Chargers\nFor the second time in four games the Raiders faced the San Diego Chargers.  Jeff Jaeger kicked four field goals for the win but the Raiders had another nail biting game when San Diego scored a touchdown in the fourth quarter.  Rookies Greg Robinson and James Jett had stellar games.  Robinson accounted for 89 yards rushing and 13 yards receiving.  Jett caught 7 passes for 138 yards.  Also, future hall of famer Howie Long record two sacks.\n*Week 13 \u2013 November 28 L 16\u201310 at Cincinnati Bengals\nThe Bengals were 0\u201310 entering the game and led the Raiders 13\u20130 as the fourth quarter began.  The Raiders offense was unable to get anything going all day and two turnovers by Los Angeles granted them their fifth loss of the 1993 season. Chester McGlockton had three sacks.\n*Week 14 \u2013 Dec 5 W 25\u201324 at Buffalo Bills\nNeeding a win to keep their playoff hopes alive the Raiders overcame the three time AFC Champion Buffalo Bills.  Jeff Hostetler rushed for a touchdown and threw for another.  Jeff Jaeger added four field goals and Tim Brown caught 10 passes for 183 yards and a TD.  During the fourth quarter the Bills led the Raiders 24\u201319.  The Raiders defense forced Buffalo to punt.  The Raiders ran just three plays, the first coming on a short completion to running back Nick Bell and a second to wide receiver James Jett.  Then Hostetler knifed the football between three Buffalo defenders to receiver Tim Brown for a touchdown.  Buffalo was driving for a game-winning field goal when Nolan Harrison forced Buffalo running back Thurman Thomas to fumble and the Raiders defense recovered to seal a 25\u201324 win.\n*Week 15  Dec 12 W 27\u201323 vs Seattle Seahawks\nTying to maintain their playoff dreams the Raiders defeated Seattle with the help of Cornerback Terry McDaniel who had a key interception.  Hostetler, Jett and Brown all scored touchdowns after Seattle established a 9\u20133 lead.  Leading 27\u20139 the Raiders allowed Seattle to reenter the game and the Seahawks scored the final 14 points of the game to cut the Raider lead 27\u201323. After their second touchdown the Seahawks were unable to recover their onside kick which preserved a Raider win.\n*Week 16  Dec 19 W 27\u201320 vs Tampa Bay Buccaneers\nThe Raiders established a 14\u20130 lead before Tampa Bay forced their way back into the game.  Alexander Wright recorded his first 100+ yard game as a Raider and Jeff Hostetler rushed for his fifth touchdown of the season.  The Raiders defense recorded five sacks and forced 2 turnovers to preserve the victory.  Tampa Bay's final ditch effort to win ended on a botched onside kick attempt and the Raiders prevailed.\n*Week 17  Dec 26 L 28\u20130 at Green Bay Packers\nBrett Favre beat the Raiders for the first of what would be four wins versus the Silver and Black.  Sterling Sharpe torched the Raiders defense for 119 yards and a touchdown and the Packers running game burned the Raiders for 148 yards.  Trailing 14\u20130 quarterback Jeff Hostetler suffered a concussion during a sack and was forced to leave the game.  Vince Evans replaced him but fared no better than Hostetler as both men completed just 18 of 38 passes. This is the game that gave birth to the \"Lambeau Leap\" when LeRoy Butler received a lateral from Reggie White, whom recovered a fumble.  Tim Brown did add 80 yards receiving but a 25-yard fumble return and a long touchdown run gave the Packers an important 28\u20130 victory.\n*Week 18  Jan 2 W 33\u201330 vs Denver Broncos (OT)\nNeeding a win to make the playoffs the Los Angeles Raiders came back from a 17-point deficit twice in the game.  Late in the fourth quarter the Raiders trailed Denver 30\u201323 but Jeff Hostetler and his offense drove Los Angeles down the field.  On the final play of regulation Hostetler completed a third down pass to Alexander Wright for a 4-yard touchdown to force overtime.  Denver won the overtime coin toss and John Elway drove Denver to a field goal opportunity.  Rookie kicker Jason Elam missed his kick and the Raiders were granted new life.  Hostetler drove Los Angeles down field again and Jeff Jaeger kicked a 47-yard field goal to send the Raiders to the 1993 playoffs.  One week later the Raiders would host Denver again in the 1993 WildCard Playoffs.<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\n==Classic comebacks==\n\nThe 1993 season saw an enormous amount of Raider comebacks.  These comebacks included:\n<br />\n<br />1) In week six versus the New York Jets.  The Raiders trailed 17\u20130 before coming back to win 24\u201320<ref>{{cite web|title=New York Jets  at  Los Angeles Raiders \u2013 October 10th, 1993 \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199310100rai.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5h6q6ihT1?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199310100rai.htm |archivedate=May 28, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<br />2) In week fifteen versus the Seattle Seahawks the Raiders trailed 9\u20133 before coming back to win 27\u201323.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199312120rai.htm</ref>\n<br />\n<br />3) In week seventeen the Raiders trailed Denver 17\u20130 and came back twice to tie and later win the game 33\u201330.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199401020rai.htm</ref>\n\n==Playoffs==\n\n===AFC Wild Card===\n{{Americanfootballbox | title=Los Angeles Raiders 42, Denver Broncos 24\n|Road=Broncos\n|R1=7\n|R2=14\n|R3=0\n|R4=3\n|RT=24\n|Home='''Raiders'''\n|H1=14\n|H2=7\n|H3=14\n|H4=7\n|HT=42\n|stadium= [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]], [[Los Angeles, California]]\n|time= 4:00 p.m. [[North American Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]/1:00 p.m. [[Pacific Standard Time Zone|PST]]\n|weather= {{convert|70|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}, clear\n|TV=[[NFL on NBC|NBC]]\n|TVAnnouncers= [[Charlie Jones (sportscaster)|Charlie Jones]] and [[Todd Christensen]]\n|referee= [[Bob McElwee]]\n|attendance= 65,314\n}}\nBoth teams entered the game with poor running games and backfield injuries.  This made the passing attacks of both squads very important.  During the first half both John Elway and Jeff Hostetler dominated with each man throwing three touchdown passes.  After a 21\u201321 tie at halftime, Raiders running back [[Napoleon McCallum]] scored three rushing touchdowns in the second half to lead his team to the victory.  Quarterback Jeff Hostetler completed 13 of 19 passes for 294 yards and 3 touchdowns.  James Jett caught 3 passes for 111 yards and a touchdown.  Tim Brown caught 3 passes for 86 yards and a touchdown.  The game was tied 21\u201321 at halftime but the Raiders pulled away with McCallum's three touchdowns in the second half.\n\n===AFC Divisional Playoff===\n{{Americanfootballbox | title=Buffalo Bills 29, Los Angeles Raiders 23\n|Road=Raiders\n|R1=0\n|R2=17\n|R3=6\n|R4=0\n|RT=23\n|Home='''Bills'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=13\n|H3=9\n|H4=7\n|HT=29\n|stadium= [[Rich Stadium]], [[Orchard Park (town), New York|Orchard Park, New York]]\n|time= 12:30 p.m. [[North American Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= {{convert|0|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}, cloudy\n|TV=[[NFL on NBC|NBC]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Marv Albert]] and [[Paul Maguire]]\n|referee= [[Red Cashion]]\n|attendance= 61,923\n}}\nIn one of the coldest games in NFL history, the Bills overcame a 17\u20136 Raiders lead by scoring three times in a span of 6:18 in the second half.  During the second half the Bills defense dominated the Raiders offense by allowing the Raiders to earn just one first down.  Tim Brown caught 5 passes for 127 yards which included an 86-yard pass for his lone touchdown of the game.  The play is the Raiders longest postseason play ever.  Running back Napoleon McCallum scored twice which brought his 1993 postseason touchdown total to five.\n\n==Awards, records, and milestones==\n\n* [[Jeff Hostetler]], Single Game Record, 424 passing yards, achieved on October 31 against the Chargers.  That record was broken when Derek Carr passed for 513 yards against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in 2016.\n* [[Jeff Jaeger]], Single Season Record, Most Field Goals in One Season, 35 and most field goals attempted in a season, 44.\n* [[Jeff Jaeger]], Single Season Record, Most Points in One Season, 132.  This record would remain a Raider record until the 2010 season.\n* [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] recorded his first 1,000 yard receiving season\n* [[Jeff Hostetler]] became the first Raider since 1979 to pass for over 3,000 yards.  He also became just the third Raider at that time to accomplish that feat.<ref>Los Angeles Raiders: Official 1993 Yearbook. Prod. Steve Sabol. VHS. NFL Films, 1994.</ref>\n*Defensive end [[Howie Long]] retired following the season.  In 2000, he entered the Pro Football Hall of Fame.\n*Pro Bowl: Cornerback [[Terry McDaniel]], Wide Receiver Tim Brown, Guard [[Steve Wisniewski]], Guard [[Max Montoya]] and Defensive End/Tackle [[Howie Long]].\n*This season was so memorable that Raiders.com has devoted three 3 of 27 of its \"Fantastic Finishes\" stories to the 1993 season.  The games that appear are the 12/5 game at Buffalo, the 10/10 game against the Jets and the 1/2/94 game against Denver.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakland Raiders \u2013 Greatest Moments |url=http://www.raiders.com/History/Default.aspx?id=874 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZZTdu?url=http://www.raiders.com/History/Default.aspx?id=874 |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n*Tim Browns 74-yard punt return for a touchdown was the second time that he returned a punt for a touchdown during his career.  He would only score one more time on a punt return and that would not occur again until 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Every Touchdown Scored by Tim Brown \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/score.cgi?id=BrowTi00 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdaPLAC?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/score.cgi?id=BrowTi00 |archivedate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 12, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> During the season, Brown became the Raiders all-time leader in punt return yardage by surpassing Neal Colize. Brown would eventually run his career punt return total to 3,272 yards and 3 touchdowns and a 10.2 average.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/career-returns.htm</ref>\n*[[Jeff Hostetler]] became just the third Raider ever to pass for 3,000 yards in one season.  At that time the others were [[Daryle Lamonica]] and [[Ken Stabler]].  Only five Raider quarterbacks have passed for 3,000 yards or more as a Raider since Hostetler.  This includes [[Rich Gannon]] (four times), [[Kerry Collins]] (twice), [[Carson Palmer]] (once), [[Derek Carr (American football)|Derek Carr]] (each of his four seasons thus far) and [[Jeff George]] (once).  The 1993 playoffs also marked Hostetler's first and only loss as a playoff starter.  Hostetler led the Giants to the Super Bowl championship in 1990 going 4\u20130 and the Raiders in 1993 with a 1\u20131 record.  In five playoff games, he completed 72 of 115 passes (62.6 percent) for 1,034 yards, seven touchdowns, no interceptions, and a 112.0 passer rating while going 4\u20131.\n\n==Team leaders==\n\n* Leading Passer [[Jeff Hostetler]], with 3,242 yards & 14 touchdowns\n* Leading rusher: [[Greg Robinson (running back)|Greg Robinson]] with 591 yards\n* Leading receiver: [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] with 80 receptions for 1,180 yards\n* Leading scorer: [[Jeff Jaeger]] with 132 points\n* Sack leader: [[Anthony Smith (defensive end)|Anthony Smith]] with 12.5 sacks\n* Leading Tackler: [[Winston Moss]] with 102 tackles\n* Interception leader: [[Terry McDaniel]] with 5 interceptions<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm Raiders on Pro Football Reference] ([https://www.webcitation.org/5ghdZAc9I?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rai/1993.htm Archived] 2009-05-11)\n* [http://www.jt-sw.com/football/pro/results.nsf/Teams/1993-lai Raiders on jt-sw.com]\n* [http://www.jt-sw.com/football/pro/stats.nsf/Annual/1993-lai Raiders stats on jt-sw.com]\n* Rinehart, Michael., [https://www.amazon.com/Complete-History-Angeles-Raiders-ebook/dp/B00E9DXEU2/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1381158899&sr=8-2&keywords=1993+los+angeles+raiders The Complete History of the 1993 Los Angeles Raiders. published on Amazon Kindle July 30, 2013]\n\n{{Las Vegas Raiders}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders seasons}}\n{{1993 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1993 Los Angeles Raiders season}}\n[[Category:1993 National Football League season by team|Los Angeles Raiders]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Raiders seasons]]\n[[Category:1993 in sports in California|Los]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams all-time \u2192 team's all-time", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1993_Los_Angeles_Raiders_season"}
{"title_page": "Geometrical properties of polynomial roots", "text_new": "{{short description|Geometry of the location of polynomial roots}}\n{{for|the computation of polynomial roots|Real-root isolation|Root-finding algorithm#Roots of polynomials}}\nIn [[mathematics]], a [[univariate polynomial]] of degree {{mvar|n}} with real or complex coefficients has {{mvar|n}} complex '''[[zero of a function|roots]]''', if counted with their [[multiplicities]]. They form a set of {{mvar|n}} points in the [[complex plane]]. This article concerns the '''geometry''' of these points, that is the information about their localization in the complex plane that can be deduced from the degree and the coefficients of the polynomial.\n\nSome of these geometrical properties are related to a single polynomial, such as upper bounds on the absolute values of the roots, which define a disk containing all roots, or lower bounds on the distance between two roots. Such bounds are widely used for [[root-finding algorithm]]s for polynomials, either for tuning them, or for computing their [[computational complexity]]\n\nSome other properties are probabilistic, such as the expected number of real roots of a random polynomial of degree {{mvar|n}} with real coefficients, which is less than  <math> 1+\\frac 2\\pi \\ln (n) </math> for {{mvar|n}} sufficiently large.\n\nIn this article, a polynomial that is considered is always denoted \n:<math>\n  p(x)=a_0 + a_1 x + \\cdots + a_n x^n,\n</math>\nwhere <math>a_0, \\dots, a_n</math> are real or complex numbers and <math>a_n \\neq 0</math>; thus {{mvar|n}} is the degree of the polynomial.\n\n==Continuous dependence on coefficients==\nThe {{math|''n''}} roots of a polynomial of degree {{math|''n''}} depend [[continuous function|continuously]] on the coefficients. For simple roots, this results immediately from the [[implicit function theorem]]. This is true also for multiple roots, but some care is needed for the proof.\n\nA small change of coefficients may induce a dramatic change of the roots, including the change of a real root into a complex root with a rather large imaginary part (see [[Wilkinson's polynomial]]). A consequence is that, for classical numeric [[root-finding algorithm]]s, the problem of approximating the roots given the coefficients is [[ill-conditioned]].\n\n==Conjugation==\n\nThe [[complex conjugate root theorem]] states that if the coefficients\nof a polynomial are real, then the non-real roots appear in pairs of the form  {{math|(''a'' + ''ib'', ''a'' \u2013 ''ib'')}}.\n\nIt follows that the roots of a polynomial with real coefficients are [[reflection symmetry|mirror-symmetric]] with respect to the real axis.\n\nThis can be extended to [[algebraic conjugate|algebraic conjugation]]: the roots of a polynomial with [[rational number|rational]] coefficients are ''conjugate'' (that is, invariant) under the action of the [[Galois group]] of the polynomial. However, this symmetry can rarely be interpreted geometrically.\n\n==Bounds on all roots==\nUpper bounds on the absolute values of polynomial roots are widely used for [[root-finding algorithm]]s, either for limiting the regions where roots should be searched, or for the computation of the [[computational complexity]] of these algorithms. \n\nMany such bounds have been given, and the sharper one depends generally of the specific sequence of coefficient that are considered. Most bounds are greater or equal to one, and are thus not sharp for a polynomial which have only roots of absolute values lower than one. However, such polynomials are very rare, as shown below.\n\nAny upper bound on the absolute values of roots provides a corresponding lower bound. In fact, if <math>a_n\\ne 0,</math> and {{mvar|U}} is an upper bound of the absolute values of the roots of \n:<math>\na_0 + a_1 x + \\cdots + a_n x^n,\n</math>\nthen {{math|1/''U''}} is a lower bound of the absolute values of \n:<math>\na_n + a_{n-1} x + \\cdots + a_0 x^n,\n</math>\nsince the roots of either polynomial are the multiplicative inverses of the roots of the other. ''Therefore, in the remainder of the article lower bounds will not be given explicitly''.\n\n===Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds===\n[[Lagrange]] and [[Cauchy]] were the firsts to provide upper bounds on all complex roots.<ref name=Hirst1997>{{cite journal |first=Holly P. |last=Hirst |first2=Wade T. |last2=Macey |title=Bounding the Roots of Polynomials |journal=[[The College Mathematics Journal]] |volume=28 |issue=4 |year=1997 |pages=292\u2013295 |jstor=2687152 }}</ref> Lagrange's bound is<ref>Lagrange J\u2013L (1798) Trait\u00e9 de la r\u00e9solution des \u00e9quations num\u00e9riques. Paris.</ref>\n <math>\\max\\left\\{1,\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|\\right\\},</math>\nand Cauchy's bound is<ref name=Cauchy1829>Cauchy Augustin-Louis (1829). ''Exercices de math\u00e9matique''. \u0152uvres 2 (9) p.122</ref>\n <math>1+\\max\\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_n}\\right|, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|\\right\\}</math>\n\nLagrange's bound is sharper (smaller) than Cauchy's bound only when 1 is larger than the sum of all <math>\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|</math> but the largest. This is relatively rare in practice, and explains why Cauchy's bound is more widely used than Lagrange's.\n\nBoth bounds result from the [[Gershgorin circle theorem]] applied to the [[companion matrix]] of the polynomial and its [[transpose]]. They can also be proved by elementary methods.\n\n{{cot|Proof of Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds}}\nIf {{mvar|z}} is a root of the polynomial, and {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2265 1}} one has \n:<math>|a_n||z^n| = \\left|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_iz^i\\right|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_iz^i|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_i||z|^{n-1}.\n</math>\n\nDividing by <math>|a_n||z|^{n-1},</math> one gets \n:<math>|z|\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\\frac{|a_i|}{|a_n|},</math>\nwhich is Lagrange's bound when there is at least one root of absolute value larger than 1. Otherwise, 1 is a bound on the roots, and is not larger than Lagrange's bound.\n\nSimilarly, for Cauchy's bound, one has, if {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2265 1}},\n:<math>|a_n||z^n| = \\left|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_iz^i\\right|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_iz^i|\n\\le \\max |a_i|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|z|^i\n= \\frac{|z|^n-1}{|z|-1}\\max |a_i|\n\\le  \\frac{|z|^n}{|z|-1}\\max |a_i|.\n</math>\nThus \n:<math>\n|a_n|(|z|-1) \\le \\max |a_i|.\n</math>\nSolving in {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}}}}, one gets Cauchy's bound if there is a root of absolute value larger than 1. Otherwise the bound is also correct, as Cauchy's bound is larger than 1.\n{{cob}}\n\nThese bounds are not invariant by scaling. That is, the roots of the polynomial {{math|''p''(''sx'')}} are the quotient by {{mvar|s}} of the root of {{mvar|p}}, and the bounds given for the roots of {{math|''p''(''sx'')}} are not the quotient by {{mvar|s}} of the bounds of {{mvar|p}}. Thus, one may get sharper bounds by minimizing over possible scalings. This gives \n <math>\\min_{s\\in \\mathbb R_+}\\left(\\max\\left\\{ s,\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|s^{i-n+1}\\right\\}\\right),</math>\nand\n <math>\\min_{s\\in \\mathbb R_+}\\left(s+\\max_{0\\le i\\le n-1}\\left(\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right| s^{i-n+1}\\right)\\right),</math>\nfor Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds respectively.\n\nAnother bound, originally given by Lagrange, but attributed to Zassenhaus by [[Donald Knuth]], is  <ref name =yap145>{{harvnb|Yap|2000|loc=\u00a7VI.2}}</ref>\n <math>2\\max\\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n}}\\right|^{1/2}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|^{1/n}\\right\\}.</math>\nThis bound is invariant by scaling.\n\n{{cot|Proof of the preceding bound}}\nLet {{mvar|A}} be the largest <math>\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|^\\frac 1{n-i}</math> for {{math|0 \u2264 ''i'' < ''n''}}. Thus one has\n:<math>\\frac {|a_{i}|}{|a_n|} \\le A^{n-i}</math>\nfor <math>0\\le i <n.</math>\nIf {{mvar|z}} is a root of {{mvar|p}}, one has \n:<math>-a_nz^n=\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_i z^i,</math>\nand thus, after dividing by <math>a_n,</math>\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n|z|^n&\\le\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}A^{n-i}|z|^i\\\\\n&=A\\frac{|z|^{n}-A^{n}}{|z|-A}.\n\\end{align}</math>\nAs we want to prove {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2264 2''A''}}, we may suppose that {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} > A}} (otherwise there is nothing to prove).\nThus \n:<math>|z|^n \\le A\\frac{|z|^n}{|z|-A},</math>\nwhich gives the result, since <math>|z|>A.</math>\n{{cob}}\n\nLagrange has improved this latter bound into the sum of the two largest values (possibly equal) in the sequence<ref name =yap145/>\n <math>\\left[ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n}}\\right|^{1/2}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|^{1/n}\\right].</math>\n\nLagrange provided also the bound {{cn|date=March 2019}}\n <math>\\sum_i \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_{i+1}}\\right|,</math>\nwhere <math>a_i</math> denotes the {{mvar|i}}th ''nonzero'' coefficient when the terms of the polynomials are sorted by increasing degrees.\n\n===Using H\u00f6lder's inequality===\n[[H\u00f6lder's inequality]] allows extends Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds to every [[p-norm|{{mvar|h}}-norm]]. The {{mvar|h}}-norm of a sequence\n:<math>s=(a_0, \\ldots, a_n)</math>\nis \n:<math>\\|s\\|_h = \\left(\\sum_{i=1}^n |a_i|^h\\right)^{1/h},</math>\nfor any real number {{math|''h'' \u2265 1}}, and \n:<math>\\|s\\|_\\infty = \\textstyle{\\max_{i=1}^n} |a_i|.</math>\n\nIf <math>\\frac 1h+ \\frac 1k=1,</math> with {{math|1 \u2264 ''h'', ''k'' \u2264 \u221e}}, and {{math|1=1 / \u221e = 0}}, an upper bound on the absolute values of the roots of {{mvar|p}} is \n <math>\\frac 1{|a_n|}\\left\\|(|a_n|, \\left\\|(|a_{n-1}|, \\ldots, |a_0| \\right)\\|_h\\right)\\|_k.</math>\n\nFor {{math|1=''k'' = 1}} and {{math|1=''k'' = \u221e}}, one gets respectively Cauchy's and Lagrange's bounds.\n\nFor {{math|1=''h'' = ''k'' = 1/2}}, one has the bound\n <math>\\frac 1{|a_n|}\\sqrt{|a_n|^2+|a_{n-1}|^2+ \\cdots +|a_0|^2 }.</math>\nThis is not only a bound of the absolute values of the roots, but also a bound of the product of their absolute values larger than 1; see {{slink||Landau's inequality}}, below.\n\n{{cot|Proof}}\nLet {{mvar|z}} be a root of the polynomial\n\n:<math>p(x)=a^n+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\\cdots+a_1x +a_0.</math>\n\nSetting \n:<math>A=\\left(\\frac{|a_{n-1}|}{|a_n|},\\ldots, \\frac{|a_1|}{|a_n|},\\frac{|a_0|}{|a_n|}\\right),</math>\nwe have to prove that every root {{mvar|z }} of {{mvar|p}} satisfies\n:<math>z\\le \\left\\|(1, \\left\\|A\\right\\|_h\\right)\\|_k.</math>\n\nIf <math>|z| \\le 1,</math> the inequality is true; so, one may suppose <math>|z| > 1</math> for the remainder of the proof.\n\nWriting the equation as\n:<math>-z^n=\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}z^{n-1}+\\cdots+\\frac{a_1}{a_n}z+a_0,</math>\nthe [[H\u00f6lder's inequality]] implies\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq \\|A\\|_h \\cdot\\left \\|(z^{n-1},\\ldots,z, 1) \\right \\|_k.</math>\n\nIf {{math|''k'' {{=}} 1}}, this is\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq\\|A\\|_1\\max \\left \\{|z|^{n-1},\\ldots,|z|,1 \\right \\} =\\|A\\|_1|z|^{n-1}.</math>\nThus\n:<math>|z|\\leq \\max\\{1,\\|A\\|_1\\}.</math>\n\nIn the case {{math|1 < ''k'' \u2264 \u221e}}, the summation formula for a [[geometric progression]], gives\n\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq \\|A\\|_h \\left(|z|^{k(n-1)}+\\cdots+|z|^k +1\\right)^{\\frac{1}{k}}=\\|A\\|_h \\left(\\frac{|z|^{kn}-1}{|z|^k-1}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{k}}\\leq\\|A\\|_h \\left(\\frac{|z|^{kn}}{|z|^k-1}\\right)^\\frac{1}{k}.</math>\nThus\n:<math>|z|^{kn}\\leq \\left(\\|A\\|_h\\right)^k \\frac{|z|^{kn}}{|z|^k-1},</math>\nwhich simplifies to\n:<math>|z|^k\\leq 1+\\left(\\|A\\|_h\\right)^k.</math>\n\nThus, in all cases\n:<math>|z|\\leq \\left \\| \\left (1,\\|A\\|_h \\right ) \\right \\|_k,</math>\nwhich finishes the proof.\n{{cob}}\n\n===Other bounds===\nMany other upper bounds for the magnitudes of all roots have been given.<ref>{{cite book |first=M. |last=Marden |title=Geometry of Polynomials |publisher=Amer. Math. Soc. |year=1966 |isbn=0-8218-1503-2 }}</ref>\n\nFujiwara's bound<ref name=Fujiwara1916>{{cite journal |last=Fujiwara |first=M. |year=1916 |title=\u00dcber die obere Schranke des absoluten Betrages der Wurzeln einer algebraischen Gleichung |journal=[[Tohoku Mathematical Journal]] |series=First series |volume=10 |issue= |pages=167\u2013171 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/tmj1911/10/0/10_0_167/_pdf }}</ref>\n <math>2\\, \\max \\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_n}\\right|^{\\frac{1}{2}}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_1}{a_n}\\right|^\\frac{1}{n-1}, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{2a_n}\\right|^\\frac 1 n\\right\\}, </math> \nimproves slightly an above given bound by dividing by two the last argument of the maximum.\n\nKojima's bound is<ref name=Kojima1917>{{cite journal |last=Kojima |first=T. |year=1917 |title=On the limits of the roots of an algebraic equation |journal=Tohoku Mathematical Journal |series=First series |volume=11 |issue= |pages=119\u2013127 |doi= |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/tmj1911/11/0/11_0_119/_pdf }}</ref>{{check|date=March 2019}}\n <math>2\\,\\max \\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|,\\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n-1}}\\right|, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{2a_1}\\right|\\right\\},</math>\nwhere <math>a_i</math> denotes the {{mvar|i}}th ''nonzero'' coefficient when the terms of the polynomials are sorted by increasing degrees. If all coefficients are nonzero, Fujiwara's bound is sharper, since\neach element in Fujiwara's bound is the [[geometric mean]] of first elements in Kojima's bound.\n\nSun and Hsieh obtained another improvement on Cauchy's bound.<ref name=Sun1996>{{cite journal |last=Sun |first=Y. J. |last2=Hsieh |first2=J. G. |year=1996 |title=A note on circular bound of polynomial zeros |journal=IEEE Trans Circuits Syst. I |volume=43 |issue=6 |pages=476\u2013478 |doi=10.1109/81.503258 }}</ref> Assume the polynomial is monic with general term {{mvar|a<sub>i</sub>x<sup>i</sup>}}. Sun and Hsieh showed that upper bounds {{math|1 + ''d''<sub>1</sub>}} and {{math|1 + ''d''<sub>2</sub>}} could be obtained from the following equations.\n\n:<math>d_1 = \\tfrac{1}{2} \\left((| a_{n-1}| - 1) + \\sqrt{(|a_{n-1}| - 1 )^2 + 4a } \\right), \\qquad a = \\max \\{ |a_i | \\}.</math>\n\n{{math|''d''<sub>2</sub>}} is the positive root of the cubic equation\n\n:<math>Q(x) = x^3 + (2 - |a_{n-1}|) x^2 + (1 - |a_{n-1}| - |a_{n-2}| ) x - a, \\qquad a = \\max \\{ |a_i | \\}</math>\n\nThey also noted that {{math|''d''<sub>2</sub> \u2264 ''d''<sub>1</sub>}}\n\n==Landau's inequality==\nThe previous bounds are upper bounds for each root separately. '''Landau's inequality''' provides an upper bound for the absolute values of the product of the roots that have an absolute value greater than one. This inequality, discovered in 1905 by [[Edmund Landau]]<ref>E. Landeau, Sur quelques th&or&mes de M. Petrovic relatifs aux z\u00e9ros des fonctions analytiques, ''Bull. Sot. Math. France'' 33 (1905), 251-261.</ref> has been forgotten and rediscovered at least three times during the 20th century.<ref>M. Mignotte. An inequality about factors of polynomials, ''Math. Comp.'' 28 (1974). 1153-1157.</ref><ref>W. Specht, Absch\u00e4tzungen der Wurzeln algebraischer Gleichungen, Math. Z. 52 (1949). 310-321.</ref><ref>J. Vincente Gon\u00e7alves, L\u2019in\u00e9galit\u00e9 de W. Specht. ''Univ. Lisboa Revista Fac. Ci A. Ci. Mat.'' 1 (195O), 167-171.</ref>\n\nThis bound of the product of roots is not much greater than the best preceding bounds of each root separately.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mignotte |first=Maurice |chapter=Some useful bounds |title=Computer Algebra : Symbolic and Algebraic Computation |pages=259\u2013263 |publisher=Springer |location=Vienna |year=1983 |isbn=0-387-81776-X |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCX4CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA259 }}</ref>\nLet <math>z_1, \\ldots, z_n</math> be the {{mvar|n}} roots of the polynomial {{mvar|p}}. If\n:<math>M(p)=|a_n|\\prod_{j=1}^n \\max(1,|z_j|)</math>\nis the [[Mahler measure]] of {{mvar|p}},\nthen \n:<math>M(p)\\le \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2}.</math>\n\nSurprisingly, this bound of the product of the absolute values larger than 1 of the roots is not much larger than the best bounds of ''one'' root that have been given above for a single root. This bound is even exactly equal to one of the bounds that are obtained [[#Using H\u00f6lder's inequality|using H\u00f6lder's inequality]].\n\nThis bound is also useful to bound the coefficients of a divisor of a polynomial with integer coefficients:<ref>Mignotte, M. (1988). An inequality about irreducible factors of integer polynomials. ''Journal of number theory'', 30(2), 156-166.</ref>\nif\n:<math>q= \\sum_{k=0}^m  b_k x^k</math>\nis a divisor of {{math|''p''}}, then\n:<math>|b_m|\\le|a_n|,</math>\nand, by [[Vieta's formulas]],\n:<math>\\frac{|b_i|}{|b_m|}\\le \\binom mi \\frac{M(p)}{|a_n|},</math>\nfor {{math|1=''i'' = 0, ..., ''m''}}, where <math>\\binom mi</math> is a [[binomial coefficient]]. Thus \n:<math>|b_i|\\le \\binom mi M(p)\\le \\binom mi \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2},</math>\nand \n:<math>\\sum_{i=0}^m |b_k| \\le 2^m M(p) \\le 2^m \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2}.</math>\n\n==Discs containing some roots==\n\n===From Rouch\u00e9 theorem===\n\n[[Rouch\u00e9's theorem]] allows defining discs centered at zero and containing a given number of roots. More precisely, if there is a positive real number {{mvar|''R''}} and an integer {{math|0 \u2264 ''k'' \u2264 ''n''}} such that\n:<math>|a_k| R^k > |a_0|+\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| R^{k-1}+|a_{k+1}| R^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| R^n,</math>\nthen there are exactly {{math|''k''}} roots, counted with multiplicity, of absolute value less than {{math|''R''}}. \n{{cot|Proof}}\nIf <math>|z|=R,</math> then\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n|a_0 &+\\cdots+a_{k-1}z^{k-1}+a_{k+1} z^{k+1}+\\cdots+a_n z^n|\\\\\n&\\le |a_0|+\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| R^{k-1}+|a_{k+1}| R^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| R^n\\\\\n&\\le |a_k| R^k \\le |a_k z^k|.\n\\end{align}</math>\nBy Rouch\u00e9's theorem, this implies directly that <math>p(z)</math> and <math>z^k</math> have the same number of roots of absolute values less than {{mvar|R}}, counted with multiplicities. As this number is {{mvar|k}}, the result is proved.\n{{cob}}\n\nThe above result may be applied if the polynomial\n:<math>h_k(x)=|a_0| +\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| x^{k-1}-|a_k|x^k+|a_{k+1}| x^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| x^n.</math>\ntakes a negative value for some positive real value of {{mvar|x}}.\n\nIn the remaining of the section, with suppose that {{math|''a''<sub>''0''</sub> \u2260 0}}. If it is not the case, zero is a root, and the localization of the other roots may be studied by dividing the polynomial by a power of the indeterminate, for getting a polynomial with a nonzero constant term.\n\nFor {{math|1=''k'' = 0}} and {{math|1=''k'' = ''n''}}, [[Descartes' rule of signs]] shows that the polynomial has exactly one positive real root. If <math>R_0</math> and <math>R_n</math> are these root, the above result shows that all the roots verifies \n:<math>R_0\\le |z| \\le R_1.</math>\nA these inequalities apply also to <math>h_0</math> and <math>h_n,</math> these bounds are optimal for polynomials with a given sequence of the absolute values of their coefficients. They are thus sharper than all bounds given in the preceding sections.\n\nFor {{math|0 < ''k'' < ''n''}}, Descartes' rule of signs implies that <math>h_k(x)</math> either has two positive real roots that are not multiple, or is nonnegative for every positive value of {{mvar|x}}. So, the above result may be applied only in the first case. If <math>R_{k,1}<R_{k,2}</math> are these two roots, the above result implies that\n:<math>|z| \\le R_{k,1}</math> \nfor {{mvar|k}} roots of {{mvar|p}}, and that \n:<math>|z| \\ge R_{k,2}</math> \nfor the {{math|''n'' \u2013 ''k''}} other roots.\n\nInstead of computing explicitly <math>R_{k,1}</math> and <math>R_{k,2},</math> it is generally sufficient to compute a value <math>R_k</math> such that <math>h_k(R_k)<0</math> (necessarily <math>R_{k,1}<R_k<R_{k,2}</math>). These  <math>R_k</math> have the property of separating roots in terms of their absolute values: if, for {{math|''h'' < ''k''}}, both <math>R_h</math> and <math>R_k</math> exist, there are exactly {{math|''k'' \u2013 ''h''}} roots {{mvar|z}} such that <math>R_h < |z| < R_k.</math>\n\nFor computing <math>R_k,</math> one can use that <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> is a [[convex function]] (its second derivative is positive). Thus <math>R_k</math> exists if and only if <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> is negative at its unique minimum. For computing this minimum, one can use any [[optimization]] method, or, alternatively, [[Newton's method]] for computing the unique positive zero of the derivative of <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> (it converges rapidly, as the derivative is a [[monotonic function]]).\n\nOne can increase the number of existing <math>R_k</math>'s by applying the root squaring operation of the [[Graeffe's method|Dandelin\u2013Graeffe iteration]]. If the roots have distinct absolute values, one can eventually separate completely the roots in terms of their absolute values, that is compute {{math|''n'' + 1}} positive numbers <math>R_0 < R_1 <\\dots <R_n</math> such there is exactly one root with an absolute value in the open interval <math>(R_{k-1},R_k),</math> for {{math|1=''k'' = 1, ..., ''n''}}.\n\n===From Gershgorin circle theorem ===\nThe [[Gershgorin circle theorem]] applied the [[companion matrix]] of the polynomial on a basis related to [[Lagrange interpolation]] provides discs centered at the interpolation points and each containing a root of the polynomial; see {{slink|Durand\u2013Kerner method|Root inclusion via Gerschgorin's circles}} for details.\n\nIf the interpolation points are close to the roots of the roots of the polynomial, the radiuses of the discs are small, and this is a key ingredient of Durand\u2013Kerner method for computing polynomial roots.\n\n==Bounds of real roots==\n\nFor polynomials with real coefficients, it is often useful to bound only the real roots. It suffices to bound the positive roots, as the negative roots of {{math|''p''(''x'')}} are the positive roots of {{math|''p''(\u2013''x'')}}.\n\nClearly, every bound of all roots applies also for real roots. But in some contexts, tighter bounds of real roots are useful. For example, the efficiency of the [[Real-root isolation#Method of continued fractions|method of continued fractions]] for [[real-root isolation]] strongly depends on tightness of a bound of positive roots. This has led to establish new bounds that are tighter than the general bounds of all roots. These bounds are generally expressed not only in terms of the absolute values of the coefficients, but also in terms of their signs.\n\nOther bounds apply only to polynomials whose all roots are reals (see below).\n\n===Bounds of positive real roots===\n\nFor giving a bound of the positive roots, one can suppose <math>a_n >0</math> without loss of generality, as changing the signs of all coefficients does not change the roots.\n\nEvery upper bound of the positive roots of \n:<math>q(x)=a_nx^n + \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\min(0,a_i)x^i</math>\nis also a bound  for the real zeros of \n:<math>p(x)=\\sum_{i=0}^n a_ix^i</math>. \nIn fact, if {{mvar|B}} is such a bound, for all {{math|''x'' > ''B''}}, one has\n{{math|''p''(''x'') \u2265 ''q''(''x'') > 0}}.\n\nApplied to Cauchy's bound, this gives the upper bound \n:<math>1+{\\textstyle\\max_{i=0}^{n-1}} \\frac{-a_i}{a_n}</math>\nfor the real roots of a polynomial with real coefficients. If this bound is not greater than {{val|1}}, this means that all nonzero coefficients have the same sign, and that there is no positive root.\n\nSimilarly, another upper bound of the positive roots is \n:<math>2\\,{\\max_{a_ia_n<0}}\\left(\\frac{-a_i}{a_n}\\right)^{\\frac 1{n-i}}.</math>\nIf all nonzero coefficients have the same sign, there is no positive root, and the maximum must be defined as being zero.\n\nOther bounds have been recently developed, mainly for the need of the [[Real-root isolation#Method of continued fractions|method of continued fractions]] for [[real-root isolation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Akritas |first=Alkiviadis G. |first2=A. W. |last2=Strzebo\u0144ski |first3=P. S. |last3=Vigklas |title=Improving the performance of the continued fractions method using new bounds of positive roots |journal=Nonlinear Analysis: Modelling and Control |year=2008 |volume=13 |pages=265\u2013279 |url=http://www.lana.lt/journal/30/Akritas.pdf |access-date=2019-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111718/http://www.lana.lt/journal/30/Akritas.pdf |archive-date=2013-12-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>\u015etef\u0103nescu, D. ''Bounds for Real Roots and Applications to Orthogonal Polynomials''. In: V. G. Ganzha, E. W. Mayr and E. V. Vorozhtsov (Editors): Proceedings of the 10th International Workshop on Computer Algebra in Scientific Computing, CASC 2007, pp. 377 \u2013 391, Bonn, Germany, September 16-20, 2007. LNCS 4770, Springer Verlag, Berlin, Heidelberg.</ref>\n\n===Polynomials whose roots are all real===\n\nIf all roots of a polynomial are real, [[Edmond Laguerre|Laguerre]] proved the following lower and upper bounds of the roots, by using what is now called [[Samuelson's inequality]].<ref name=Laguerre1880>{{cite journal | author = Laguerre E | title = Sur une m\u00e9thode pour obtenir par approximation les racines d'une \u00e9quation alg\u00e9brique qui a toutes ses racines r\u00e9elles | pages = 161\u2013172, 193\u2013202 | year = 1880 | journal = [[Nouvelles Annales de Math\u00e9matiques]] | series = 2 | volume = 19 | url = http://www.numdam.org/numdam-bin/browse?id=NAM_1880_2_19_ }}.</ref>\n\nLet <math>\\sum_{k=0}^n a_k x^k</math> be a polynomial with all real roots. Then its roots are located in the interval with endpoints\n:<math>-\\frac{a_{n-1}}{na_n} \\pm \\frac{n-1}{na_n}\\sqrt{a^2_{n-1} - \\frac{2n}{n-1}a_n a_{n-2}}.</math>\n\nFor example, the roots of the polynomial <math>x^4+5x^3+5x^2-5x-6=(x+3)(x+2)(x+1)(x-1)</math> satisfy\n:<math>-3.8118<-\\frac{5}{4} - \\frac{3}{4}\\sqrt{\\frac{35}{3}}\\le x\\le -\\frac{5}{4} + \\frac{3}{4}\\sqrt{\\frac{35}{3}}<1.3118.</math>\n\n==Root separation==\n\nThe '''root separation''' of a polynomial is the minimal distance between two roots, that is the minimum of the absolute values of the difference of two roots:\n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) = \\min\\{|\\alpha-\\beta|\\;;\\; \\alpha \\neq \\beta \\text{ and } p(\\alpha)=p(\\beta)=0\\}</math>\n\nThe root separation is a fundamental parameter of the [[computational complexity]] of [[root-finding algorithm]]s for polynomials. In fact, the root separation determines the precision of number representation that is needed for being sure of distinguishing different roots. Also, for [[real-root isolation]], it allows bounding the number of interval divisions that are needed for isolating all roots.\n\nFor polynomials with real or complex coefficients is not possible to express a lower bound of the root separation in terms of the degree and the absolute values of the coefficients only, because a small change on a single coefficient transforms a polynomial with multiple roots in a [[square-free polynomial]] with a small root separation, and essentially the same absolute values of the coefficient. However, involving the [[discriminant]] of the polynomial allows a lower bound.\n\nFor square-free polynomials with integer coefficients, the discriminant is an integer, and has thus an absolute value  that is not lower than {{val|1}}. This allows lower bounds for root separation that are independent from the discriminant.\n\nMignotte's separation bound is<ref>{{harvnb|Yap|2000|loc=\u00a7 VI.7, Proposition 29}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=George E.|last=Collins|authorlink=George E. Collins|title=Polynomial minimum root separation|journal=Journal of Symbolic Computation|year=2001|volume= 32|pages= 467\u2013473| doi=10.1006/jsco.2001.0481|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82808521.pdf }}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) >  \\frac {\\sqrt 3\\Delta(p)}{n^{n/2+1}(\\|p\\|_2)^{n-1}},</math>\nwhere <math>\\Delta(p)</math> is the discriminant, and <math>\\textstyle\\|p\\|_2=\\sqrt{a_0^2+a_1^2+\\dots+a_n^2}.</math> \n\nFor a square free polynomial with integer coefficients, this implies \n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) >  \\frac {\\sqrt 3}{n^{n/2+1}(\\|p\\|_2)^{n-1}}> \\frac 1{2^{2s^2}},</math>\nwhere {{mvar|s}} is the [[bit]] size of {{mvar|p}}, that is the sum of the bitsize of its coefficients.\n\n==Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem==\n{{main|Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem}}\nThe Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem states that the [[convex hull]] of the roots of a polynomial contains the roots of the [[derivative]] of the polynomial.\n\nA sometimes useful corollary is that, if all roots of a polynomial have positive real part, then so do the roots of all derivatives of the polynomial.\n\nA related result is [[Bernstein's inequality in mathematical analysis|Bernstein's inequality]]. It states that for a polynomial ''P'' of degree ''n'' with derivative ''P\u2032'' we have\n:<math>\\max_{|z| \\leq 1} \\big|P'(z)\\big| \\le n \\max_{|z| \\leq 1} \\big|P(z)\\big|.</math>\n\n==Statistical distribution of the roots==\n\nIf the coefficients {{math|''a''<sub>i</sub>}} of a random polynomial are independently and identically distributed with a [[mean]] of zero, most complex roots are on the unit circle or close to it. In particular, the real roots are mostly located near {{math|\u00b11}}, and, moreover, their expected number is, for a large degree, less than the [[natural logarithm]] of the degree.\n\nIf the coefficients are [[Gaussian distribution|Gaussian distributed]] with a mean of zero and [[variance]] of ''\u03c3'' then the mean density of real roots is given by the Kac formula<ref name=Kac1943>{{cite journal |last=Kac |first=M. |authorlink=Mark Kac |year=1943 |title=On the average number of real roots of a random algebraic equation |journal=[[Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society]] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=314\u2013320 |doi=10.1090/S0002-9904-1943-07912-8 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=Kac1948>{{cite journal |last=Kac |first=M. |year=1948 |title=On the Average Number of Real Roots of a Random Algebraic Equation (II) |journal=[[Proceedings of the London Mathematical Society]] |series=Second Series |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=390\u2013408 |doi=10.1112/plms/s2-50.5.390 }}</ref>\n\n: <math> m( x ) = \\frac { \\sqrt{ A( x ) C( x ) - B( x )^2 }} {\\pi A( x )} </math>\n\nwhere\n\n: <math> \\begin{align}\nA(x) &= \\sigma \\sum x^{2i} = \\sigma \\frac{x^{2n} - 1}{x-1}, \\\\\nB(x) &= \\frac 1 2 \\frac{ d } { dx } A( x ), \\\\\nC(x) &= \\frac 1 4 \\frac{d^2} {dx^2} A(x) + \\frac 1 { 4x } \\frac d {dx} A(x).\n\\end{align} </math>\n\nWhen the coefficients are Gaussian distributed with a non-zero mean and variance of ''\u03c3'', a similar but more complex formula is known.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\n===Real roots===\nFor large {{math|''n''}}, the mean density of real roots near {{mvar|x}} is asymptotically\n\n: <math> m( x ) = \\frac{ 1 } { \\pi | 1 - x^2 | } </math>\nif <math>x^2-1\\ne 0,</math>\nand\n: <math> m(\\pm 1) = \\frac 1 \\pi \\sqrt {\\frac{n^2 - 1}{12}} </math>\n\nIt follows that the expected number of real roots is, using [[big O notation|big {{mvar|O}} notation]]\n: <math> N_n = \\frac 2 \\pi \\ln n + C + \\frac 2 {\\pi n} +O( n^{ -2 } ) </math>\nwhere {{math|''C''}} is a constant approximately equal to {{val|0.6257358072}}.<ref name=ek>{{cite journal|last1=Edelman|first1=Alan|last2=Kostlan|first2=Eric|title=How many zeros of a random polynomial are real?| journal=Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society|year=1995|volume=32|pp=1-37|doi=10.1090/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9 |issue=1|url=https://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1995-32-01/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn other words, ''the expected number of real roots of a random polynomial of high degree is lower than the [[natural logarithm]] of the degree''.\n\nKac, Erd\u00f6s and others have shown that these results are insensitive to the distribution of the coefficients, if they are independent and have the same distribution with mean zero. However, if the  variance of the {{mvar|i}}th coefficient equal to <math>\\binom ni,</math> the expected number of real roots is <math>\\sqrt n.</math><ref name=ek/>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|Descartes' rule of signs}}\n* {{annotated link|Marden's theorem}}\n* {{annotated link|Newton's identities}}\n* [[Quadratic function#Upper bound on the magnitude of the roots]]\n* {{annotated link|Real-root isolation}}\n* {{annotated link|Root-finding algorithm#Roots of polynomials}}\n* {{annotated link|Square-free polynomial}}\n* {{annotated link|Vieta's formulas}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last1=Rahman | first1=Q. I. | last2=Schmeisser | first2=G. | title=Analytic theory of polynomials | series=London Mathematical Society Monographs. New Series | volume=26 | location=Oxford | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | year=2002 | isbn=0-19-853493-0 | zbl=1072.30006 }}\n* {{cite book | last=Yap | first= Chee-Keng| title=Fundamental problems of algorithmic algebra| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]| year = 2000|isbn=978-0195125160|ref=harv|\nurl=http://160592857366.free.fr/joe/ebooks/ShareData/Fundamental%20Problems%20in%20Algorithmic%20Algebra%201993%20Yap.pdf}}.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/roots/ The beauty of the roots], a visualization of the distribution of all roots of all polynomials with degree and integer coefficients in some range.\n\n[[Category:Polynomials]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Geometry of the location of polynomial roots}}\n{{for|the computation of polynomial roots|Real-root isolation|Root-finding algorithm#Roots of polynomials}}\nIn [[mathematics]], a [[univariate polynomial]] of degree {{mvar|n}} with real or complex coefficients has {{mvar|n}} complex '''[[zero of a function|roots]]''', if counted with their [[multiplicities]]. They form a set of {{mvar|n}} points in the [[complex plane]]. This article concerns the '''geometry''' of these points, that is the information about their localization in the complex plane that can be deduced from the degree and the coefficients of the polynomial.\n\nSome of these geometrical properties are related to a single polynomial, such as upper bounds on the absolute values of the roots, which define a disk containing all roots, or lower bounds on the distance between two roots. Such bounds are widely used for [[root-finding algorithm]]s for polynomials, either for tuning them, or for computing their [[computational complexity]]\n\nSome other properties are probabilistic, such as the expected number of real roots of a random polynomial of degree {{mvar|n}} with real coefficients, which is less than  <math> 1+\\frac 2\\pi \\ln (n) </math> for {{mvar|n}} sufficiently large.\n\nIn this article, a polynomial that is considered is always denoted \n:<math>\n  p(x)=a_0 + a_1 x + \\cdots + a_n x^n,\n</math>\nwhere <math>a_0, \\dots, a_n</math> are real or complex numbers and <math>a_n \\neq 0</math>; thus {{mvar|n}} is the degree of the polynomial.\n\n==Continuous dependence on coefficients==\nThe {{math|''n''}} roots of a polynomial of degree {{math|''n''}} depend [[continuous function|continuously]] on the coefficients. For simple roots, this results immediately from the [[implicit function theorem]]. This is true also for multiple roots, but some care is needed for the proof.\n\nA small change of coefficients may induce a dramatic change of the roots, including the change of a real root into a complex root with a rather large imaginary part (see [[Wilkinson's polynomial]]). A consequence is that, for classical numeric [[root-finding algorithm]]s, the problem of approximating the roots given the coefficients is [[ill-conditioned]].\n\n==Conjugation==\n\nThe [[complex conjugate root theorem]] states that if the coefficients\nof a polynomial are real, then the non-real roots appear in pairs of the form  {{math|(''a'' + ''ib'', ''a'' \u2013 ''ib'')}}.\n\nIt follows that the roots of a polynomial with real coefficients are [[reflection symmetry|mirror-symmetric]] with respect to the real axis.\n\nThis can be extended to [[algebraic conjugate|algebraic conjugation]]: the roots of a polynomial with [[rational number|rational]] coefficients are ''conjugate'' (that is, invariant) under the action of the [[Galois group]] of the polynomial. However, this symmetry can rarely be interpreted geometrically.\n\n==Bounds on all roots==\nUpper bounds on the absolute values of polynomial roots are widely used for [[root-finding algorithm]]s, either for limiting the regions where roots should be searched, or for the computation of the [[computational complexity]] of these algorithms. \n\nMany such bounds have been given, and the sharper one depends generally of the specific sequence of coefficient that are considered. Most bounds are greater or equal to one, and are thus not sharp for a polynomial which have only roots of absolute values lower than one. However, such polynomials are very rare, as shown below.\n\nAny upper bound on the absolute values of roots provides a corresponding lower bound. In fact, if <math>a_n\\ne 0,</math> and {{mvar|U}} is an upper bound of the absolute values of the roots of \n:<math>\na_0 + a_1 x + \\cdots + a_n x^n,\n</math>\nthen {{math|1/''U''}} is a lower bound of the absolute values of \n:<math>\na_n + a_{n-1} x + \\cdots + a_0 x^n,\n</math>\nsince the roots of either polynomial are the multiplicative inverses of the roots of the other. ''Therefore, in the remainder of the article lower bounds will not be given explicitly''.\n\n===Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds===\n[[Lagrange]] and [[Cauchy]] were the firsts to provide upper bounds on all complex roots.<ref name=Hirst1997>{{cite journal |first=Holly P. |last=Hirst |first2=Wade T. |last2=Macey |title=Bounding the Roots of Polynomials |journal=[[The College Mathematics Journal]] |volume=28 |issue=4 |year=1997 |pages=292\u2013295 |jstor=2687152 }}</ref> Lagrange's bound is<ref>Lagrange J\u2013L (1798) Trait\u00e9 de la r\u00e9solution des \u00e9quations num\u00e9riques. Paris.</ref>\n <math>\\max\\left\\{1,\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|\\right\\},</math>\nand Cauchy's bound is<ref name=Cauchy1829>Cauchy Augustin-Louis (1829). ''Exercices de math\u00e9matique''. \u0152uvres 2 (9) p.122</ref>\n <math>1+\\max\\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_n}\\right|, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|\\right\\}</math>\n\nLagrange's bound is sharper (smaller) than Cauchy's bound only when 1 is larger than the sum of all <math>\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|</math> but the largest. This is relatively rare in practice, and explains why Cauchy's bound is more widely used than Lagrange's.\n\nBoth bounds result from the [[Gershgorin circle theorem]] applied to the [[companion matrix]] of the polynomial and its [[transpose]]. They can also be proved by elementary methods.\n\n{{cot|Proof of Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds}}\nIf {{mvar|z}} is a root of the polynomial, and {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2265 1}} one has \n:<math>|a_n||z^n| = \\left|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_iz^i\\right|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_iz^i|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_i||z|^{n-1}.\n</math>\n\nDividing by <math>|a_n||z|^{n-1},</math> one gets \n:<math>|z|\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\\frac{|a_i|}{|a_n|},</math>\nwhich is Lagrange's bound when there is at least one root of absolute value larger than 1. Otherwise, 1 is a bound on the roots, and is not larger than Lagrange's bound.\n\nSimilarly, for Cauchy's bound, one has, if {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2265 1}},\n:<math>|a_n||z^n| = \\left|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_iz^i\\right|\n\\le \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|a_iz^i|\n\\le \\max |a_i|\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}|z|^i\n= \\frac{|z|^n-1}{|z|-1}\\max |a_i|\n\\le  \\frac{|z|^n}{|z|-1}\\max |a_i|.\n</math>\nThus \n:<math>\n|a_n|(|z|-1) \\le \\max |a_i|.\n</math>\nSolving in {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}}}}, one gets Cauchy's bound if there is a root of absolute value larger than 1. Otherwise the bound is also correct, as Cauchy's bound is larger than 1.\n{{cob}}\n\nThese bounds are not invariant by scaling. That is, the roots of the polynomial {{math|''p''(''sx'')}} are the quotient by {{mvar|s}} of the root of {{mvar|p}}, and the bounds given for the roots of {{math|''p''(''sx'')}} are not the quotient by {{mvar|s}} of the bounds of {{mvar|p}}. Thus, one may get sharper bounds by minimizing over possible scalings. This gives \n <math>\\min_{s\\in \\mathbb R_+}\\left(\\max\\left\\{ s,\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|s^{i-n+1}\\right\\}\\right),</math>\nand\n <math>\\min_{s\\in \\mathbb R_+}\\left(s+\\max_{0\\le i\\le n-1}\\left(\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right| s^{i-n+1}\\right)\\right),</math>\nfor Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds respectively.\n\nAnother bound, originally given by Lagrange, but attributed to Zassenhaus by [[Donald Knuth]], is  <ref name =yap145>{{harvnb|Yap|2000|loc=\u00a7VI.2}}</ref>\n <math>2\\max\\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n}}\\right|^{1/2}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|^{1/n}\\right\\}.</math>\nThis bound is invariant by scaling.\n\n{{cot|Proof of the preceding bound}}\nLet {{mvar|A}} be the largest <math>\\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_n}\\right|^\\frac 1{n-i}</math> for {{math|0 \u2264 ''i'' < ''n''}}. Thus one has\n:<math>\\frac {|a_{i}|}{|a_n|} \\le A^{n-i}</math>\nfor <math>0\\le i <n.</math>\nIf {{mvar|z}} is a root of {{mvar|p}}, one has \n:<math>-a_nz^n=\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_i z^i,</math>\nand thus, after dividing by <math>a_n,</math>\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n|z|^n&\\le\\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}A^{n-i}|z|^i\\\\\n&=A\\frac{|z|^{n}-A^{n}}{|z|-A}.\n\\end{align}</math>\nAs we want to prove {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} \u2264 2''A''}}, we may suppose that {{math|{{!}}''z''{{!}} > A}} (otherwise there is nothing to prove).\nThus \n:<math>|z|^n \\le A\\frac{|z|^n}{|z|-A},</math>\nwhich gives the result, since <math>|z|>A.</math>\n{{cob}}\n\nLagrange has improved this latter bound into the sum of the two largest values (possibly equal) in the sequence<ref name =yap145/>\n <math>\\left[ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n}}\\right|^{1/2}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{a_n}\\right|^{1/n}\\right].</math>\n\nLagrange provided also the bound {{cn|date=March 2019}}\n <math>\\sum_i \\left|\\frac{a_i}{a_{i+1}}\\right|,</math>\nwhere <math>a_i</math> denotes the {{mvar|i}}th ''nonzero'' coefficient when the terms of the polynomials are sorted by increasing degrees.\n\n===Using H\u00f6lder's inequality===\n[[H\u00f6lder's inequality]] allows extends Lagrange's and Cauchy's bounds to every [[p-norm|{{mvar|h}}-norm]]. The {{mvar|h}}-norm of a sequence\n:<math>s=(a_0, \\ldots, a_n)</math>\nis \n:<math>\\|s\\|_h = \\left(\\sum_{i=1}^n |a_i|^h\\right)^{1/h},</math>\nfor any real number {{math|''h'' \u2265 1}}, and \n:<math>\\|s\\|_\\infty = \\textstyle{\\max_{i=1}^n} |a_i|.</math>\n\nIf <math>\\frac 1h+ \\frac 1k=1,</math> with {{math|1 \u2264 ''h'', ''k'' \u2264 \u221e}}, and {{math|1=1 / \u221e = 0}}, an upper bound on the absolute values of the roots of {{mvar|p}} is \n <math>\\frac 1{|a_n|}\\left\\|(|a_n|, \\left\\|(|a_{n-1}|, \\ldots, |a_0| \\right)\\|_h\\right)\\|_k.</math>\n\nFor {{math|1=''k'' = 1}} and {{math|1=''k'' = \u221e}}, one gets respectively Cauchy's and Lagrange's bounds.\n\nFor {{math|1=''h'' = ''k'' = 1/2}}, one has the bound\n <math>\\frac 1{|a_n|}\\sqrt{|a_n|^2+|a_{n-1}|^2+ \\cdots +|a_0|^2 }.</math>\nThis is not only a bound of the absolute values of the roots, but also a bound of the product of their absolute values larger than 1; see {{slink||Landau's inequality}}, below.\n\n{{cot|Proof}}\nLet {{mvar|z}} be a root of the polynomial\n\n:<math>p(x)=a^n+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\\cdots+a_1x +a_0.</math>\n\nSetting \n:<math>A=\\left(\\frac{|a_{n-1}|}{|a_n|},\\ldots, \\frac{|a_1|}{|a_n|},\\frac{|a_0|}{|a_n|}\\right),</math>\nwe have to prove that every root {{mvar|z }} of {{mvar|p}} satisfies\n:<math>z\\le \\left\\|(1, \\left\\|A\\right\\|_h\\right)\\|_k.</math>\n\nIf <math>|z| \\le 1,</math> the inequality is true; so, one may suppose <math>|z| > 1</math> for the remainder of the proof.\n\nWriting the equation as\n:<math>-z^n=\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}z^{n-1}+\\cdots+\\frac{a_1}{a_n}z+a_0,</math>\nthe [[H\u00f6lder's inequality]] implies\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq \\|A\\|_h \\cdot\\left \\|(z^{n-1},\\ldots,z, 1) \\right \\|_k.</math>\n\nIf {{math|''k'' {{=}} 1}}, this is\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq\\|A\\|_1\\max \\left \\{|z|^{n-1},\\ldots,|z|,1 \\right \\} =\\|A\\|_1|z|^{n-1}.</math>\nThus\n:<math>|z|\\leq \\max\\{1,\\|A\\|_1\\}.</math>\n\nIn the case {{math|1 < ''k'' \u2264 \u221e}}, the summation formula for a [[geometric progression]], gives\n\n:<math>|z|^n\\leq \\|A\\|_h \\left(|z|^{k(n-1)}+\\cdots+|z|^k +1\\right)^{\\frac{1}{k}}=\\|A\\|_h \\left(\\frac{|z|^{kn}-1}{|z|^k-1}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{k}}\\leq\\|A\\|_h \\left(\\frac{|z|^{kn}}{|z|^k-1}\\right)^\\frac{1}{k}.</math>\nThus\n:<math>|z|^{kn}\\leq \\left(\\|A\\|_h\\right)^k \\frac{|z|^{kn}}{|z|^k-1},</math>\nwhich simplifies to\n:<math>|z|^k\\leq 1+\\left(\\|A\\|_h\\right)^k.</math>\n\nThus, in all cases\n:<math>|z|\\leq \\left \\| \\left (1,\\|A\\|_h \\right ) \\right \\|_k,</math>\nwhich finishes the proof.\n{{cob}}\n\n===Other bounds===\nMany other upper bounds for the magnitudes of all roots have been given.<ref>{{cite book |first=M. |last=Marden |title=Geometry of Polynomials |publisher=Amer. Math. Soc. |year=1966 |isbn=0-8218-1503-2 }}</ref>\n\nFujiwara's bound<ref name=Fujiwara1916>{{cite journal |last=Fujiwara |first=M. |year=1916 |title=\u00dcber die obere Schranke des absoluten Betrages der Wurzeln einer algebraischen Gleichung |journal=[[Tohoku Mathematical Journal]] |series=First series |volume=10 |issue= |pages=167\u2013171 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/tmj1911/10/0/10_0_167/_pdf }}</ref>\n <math>2\\, \\max \\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|, \\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_n}\\right|^{\\frac{1}{2}}, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_1}{a_n}\\right|^\\frac{1}{n-1}, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{2a_n}\\right|^\\frac 1 n\\right\\}, </math> \nimproves slightly an above given bound by dividing by two the last argument of the maximum.\n\nKojima's bound is<ref name=Kojima1917>{{cite journal |last=Kojima |first=T. |year=1917 |title=On the limits of the roots of an algebraic equation |journal=Tohoku Mathematical Journal |series=First series |volume=11 |issue= |pages=119\u2013127 |doi= |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/tmj1911/11/0/11_0_119/_pdf }}</ref>{{check|date=March 2019}}\n <math>2\\,\\max \\left\\{ \\left|\\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n}\\right|,\\left|\\frac{a_{n-2}}{a_{n-1}}\\right|, \\ldots, \\left|\\frac{a_0}{2a_1}\\right|\\right\\},</math>\nwhere <math>a_i</math> denotes the {{mvar|i}}th ''nonzero'' coefficient when the terms of the polynomials are sorted by increasing degrees. If all coefficients are nonzero, Fujiwara's bound is sharper, since\neach element in Fujiwara's bound is the [[geometric mean]] of first elements in Kojima's bound.\n\nSun and Hsieh obtained another improvement on Cauchy's bound.<ref name=Sun1996>{{cite journal |last=Sun |first=Y. J. |last2=Hsieh |first2=J. G. |year=1996 |title=A note on circular bound of polynomial zeros |journal=IEEE Trans Circuits Syst. I |volume=43 |issue=6 |pages=476\u2013478 |doi=10.1109/81.503258 }}</ref> Assume the polynomial is monic with general term {{mvar|a<sub>i</sub>x<sup>i</sup>}}. Sun and Hsieh showed that upper bounds {{math|1 + ''d''<sub>1</sub>}} and {{math|1 + ''d''<sub>2</sub>}} could be obtained from the following equations.\n\n:<math>d_1 = \\tfrac{1}{2} \\left((| a_{n-1}| - 1) + \\sqrt{(|a_{n-1}| - 1 )^2 + 4a } \\right), \\qquad a = \\max \\{ |a_i | \\}.</math>\n\n{{math|''d''<sub>2</sub>}} is the positive root of the cubic equation\n\n:<math>Q(x) = x^3 + (2 - |a_{n-1}|) x^2 + (1 - |a_{n-1}| - |a_{n-2}| ) x - a, \\qquad a = \\max \\{ |a_i | \\}</math>\n\nThey also noted that {{math|''d''<sub>2</sub> \u2264 ''d''<sub>1</sub>}}\n\n==Landau's inequality==\nThe previous bounds are upper bounds for each root separately. '''Landau's inequality''' provides an upper bound for the absolute values of the product of the roots that have an absolute value greater than one. This inequality, discovered in 1905 by [[Edmund Landau]]<ref>E. Landeau, Sur quelques th&or&mes de M. Petrovic relatifs aux z\u00e9ros des fonctions analytiques, ''Bull. Sot. Math. France'' 33 (1905), 251-261.</ref> has been forgotten and rediscovered at least three times during the 20th century.<ref>M. Mignotte. An inequality about factors of polynomials, ''Math. Comp.'' 28 (1974). 1153-1157.</ref><ref>W. Specht, Absch\u00e4tzungen der Wurzeln algebraischer Gleichungen, Math. Z. 52 (1949). 310-321.</ref><ref>J. Vincente Gon\u00e7alves, L\u2019in\u00e9galit\u00e9 de W. Specht. ''Univ. Lisboa Revista Fac. Ci A. Ci. Mat.'' 1 (195O), 167-171.</ref>\n\nThis bound of the product of roots is not much greater than the best preceding bounds of each root separately.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mignotte |first=Maurice |chapter=Some useful bounds |title=Computer Algebra : Symbolic and Algebraic Computation |pages=259\u2013263 |publisher=Springer |location=Vienna |year=1983 |isbn=0-387-81776-X |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCX4CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA259 }}</ref>\nLet <math>z_1, \\ldots, z_n</math> be the {{mvar|n}} roots of the polynomial {{mvar|p}}. If\n:<math>M(p)=|a_n|\\prod_{j=1}^n \\max(1,|z_j|)</math>\nis the [[Mahler measure]] of {{mvar|p}},\nthen \n:<math>M(p)\\le \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2}.</math>\n\nSurprisingly, this bound of the product of the absolute values larger than 1 of the roots is not much larger than the best bounds of ''one'' root that have been given above for a single root. This bound is even exactly equal to one of the bounds that are obtained [[#Using H\u00f6lder's inequality|using H\u00f6lder's inequality]].\n\nThis bound is also useful to bound the coefficients of a divisor of a polynomial with integer coefficients:<ref>Mignotte, M. (1988). An inequality about irreducible factors of integer polynomials. ''Journal of number theory'', 30(2), 156-166.</ref>\nif\n:<math>q= \\sum_{k=0}^m  b_k x^k</math>\nis a divisor of {{math|''p''}}, then\n:<math>|b_m|\\le|a_n|,</math>\nand, by [[Vieta's formulas]],\n:<math>\\frac{|b_i|}{|b_m|}\\le \\binom mi \\frac{M(p)}{|a_n|},</math>\nfor {{math|1=''i'' = 0, ..., ''m''}}, where <math>\\binom mi</math> is a [[binomial coefficient]]. Thus \n:<math>|b_i|\\le \\binom mi M(p)\\le \\binom mi \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2},</math>\nand \n:<math>\\sum_{i=0}^m |b_k| \\le 2^m M(p) \\le 2^m \\sqrt{\\sum_{k=0}^n |a_k|^2}.</math>\n\n==Discs containing some roots==\n\n===From Rouch\u00e9 theorem===\n\n[[Rouch\u00e9's theorem]] allows defining discs centered at zero and containing a given number of roots. More precisely, if there is a positive real number {{mvar|''R''}} and an integer {{math|0 \u2264 ''k'' \u2264 ''n''}} such that\n:<math>|a_k| R^k > |a_0|+\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| R^{k-1}+|a_{k+1}| R^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| R^n,</math>\nthen there are exactly {{math|''k''}} roots, counted with multiplicity, of absolute value less than {{math|''R''}}. \n{{cot|Proof}}\nIf <math>|z|=R,</math> then\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n|a_0 &+\\cdots+a_{k-1}z^{k-1}+a_{k+1} z^{k+1}+\\cdots+a_n z^n|\\\\\n&\\le |a_0|+\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| R^{k-1}+|a_{k+1}| R^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| R^n\\\\\n&\\le |a_k| R^k \\le |a_k z^k|.\n\\end{align}</math>\nBy Rouch\u00e9's theorem, this implies directly that <math>p(z)</math> and <math>z^k</math> have the same number of roots of absolute values less than {{mvar|R}}, counted with multiplicities. As this number is {{mvar|k}}, the result is proved.\n{{cob}}\n\nThe above result may be applied if the polynomial\n:<math>h_k(x)=|a_0| +\\cdots+|a_{k-1}| x^{k-1}-|a_k|x^k+|a_{k+1}| x^{k+1}+\\cdots+|a_n| x^n.</math>\ntakes a negative value for some positive real value of {{mvar|x}}.\n\nIn the remaining of the section, with suppose that {{math|''a''<sub>''0''</sub> \u2260 0}}. If it is not the case, zero is a root, and the localization of the other roots may be studied by dividing the polynomial by a power of the indeterminate, for getting a polynomial with a nonzero constant term.\n\nFor {{math|1=''k'' = 0}} and {{math|1=''k'' = ''n''}}, [[Descartes' rule of signs]] shows that the polynomial has exactly one positive real root. If <math>R_0</math> and <math>R_n</math> are these root, the above result shows that all the roots verifies \n:<math>R_0\\le |z| \\le R_1.</math>\nA these inequalities apply also to <math>h_0</math> and <math>h_n,</math> these bounds are optimal for polynomials with a given sequence of the absolute values of their coefficients. They are thus sharper than all bounds given in the preceding sections.\n\nFor {{math|0 < ''k'' < ''n''}}, Descartes' rule of signs implies that <math>h_k(x)</math> either has two positive real roots that are not multiple, or is nonnegative for every positive value of {{mvar|x}}. So, the above result may be applied only in the first case. If <math>R_{k,1}<R_{k,2}</math> are these two roots, the above result implies that\n:<math>|z| \\le R_{k,1}</math> \nfor {{mvar|k}} roots of {{mvar|p}}, and that \n:<math>|z| \\ge R_{k,2}</math> \nfor the {{math|''n'' \u2013 ''k''}} other roots.\n\nInstead of computing explicitly <math>R_{k,1}</math> and <math>R_{k,2},</math> it is generally sufficient to compute a value <math>R_k</math> such that <math>h_k(R_k)<0</math> (necessarily <math>R_{k,1}<R_k<R_{k,2}</math>). These  <math>R_k</math> have the property of separating roots in terms of their absolute values: if, for {{math|''h'' < ''k''}}, both <math>R_h</math> and <math>R_k</math> exist, there are exactly {{math|''k'' \u2013 ''h''}} roots {{mvar|z}} such that <math>R_h < |z| < R_k.</math>\n\nFor computing <math>R_k,</math> one can use that <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> is a [[convex function]] (its second derivative is positive). Thus <math>R_k</math> exists if and only if <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> is negative at its unique minimum. For computing this minimum, one can use any [[optimization]] method, or, alternatively, [[Newton's method]] for computing the unique positive zero of the derivative of <math>\\frac{h(x)}{x^k}</math> (it converges rapidly, as the derivative is a [[monotonic function]]).\n\nOne can increase the number of existing <math>R_k</math>'s by applying the root squaring operation of the [[Graeffe's method|Dandelin\u2013Graeffe iteration]]. If the roots have distinct absolute values, one can eventually separate completely the roots in terms of their absolute values, that is compute {{math|''n'' + 1}} positive numbers <math>R_0 < R_1 <\\dots <R_n</math> such there is exactly one root with an absolute value in the open interval <math>(R_{k-1},R_k),</math> for {{math|1=''k'' = 1, ..., ''n''}}.\n\n===From Gershgorin circle theorem ===\nThe [[Gershgorin circle theorem]] applied the [[companion matrix]] of the polynomial on a basis related to [[Lagrange interpolation]] provides discs centered at the interpolation points and each containing a root of the polynomial; see {{slink|Durand\u2013Kerner method|Root inclusion via Gerschgorin's circles}} for details.\n\nIf the interpolation points are close to the roots of the roots of the polynomial, the radiuses of the discs are small, and this is a key ingredient of Durand\u2013Kerner method for computing polynomial roots.\n\n==Bounds of real roots==\n\nFor polynomials with real coefficients, it is often useful to bound only the real roots. It suffices to bound the positive roots, as the negative roots of {{math|''p''(''x'')}} are the positive roots of {{math|''p''(\u2013''x'')}}.\n\nClearly, every bound of all roots applies also for real roots. But in some contexts, tighter bounds of real roots are useful. For example, the efficiency of the [[Real-root isolation#Method of continued fractions|method of continued fractions]] for [[real-root isolation]] strongly depends on tightness of a bound of positive roots. This has led to establish new bounds that are tighter than the general bounds of all roots. These bounds are generally expressed not only in terms of the absolute values of the coefficients, but also in terms of their signs.\n\nOther bounds apply only to polynomials whose all roots are reals (see below).\n\n===Bounds of positive real roots===\n\nFor giving a bound of the positive roots, one can suppose <math>a_n >0</math> without loss of generality, as changing the signs of all coefficients does not change the roots.\n\nEvery upper bound of the positive roots of \n:<math>q(x)=a_nx^n + \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \\min(0,a_i)x^i</math>\nis also a bound  for the real zeros of \n:<math>p(x)=\\sum_{i=0}^n a_ix^i</math>. \nIn fact, if {{mvar|B}} is such a bound, for all {{math|''x'' > ''B''}}, one has\n{{math|''p''(''x'') \u2265 ''q''(''x'') > 0}}.\n\nApplied to Cauchy's bound, this gives the upper bound \n:<math>1+{\\textstyle\\max_{i=0}^{n-1}} \\frac{-a_i}{a_n}</math>\nfor the real roots of a polynomial with real coefficients. If this bound is not greater than {{val|1}}, this means that all nonzero coefficients have the same sign, and that there is no positive root.\n\nSimilarly, another upper bound of the positive roots is \n:<math>2\\,{\\max_{a_ia_n<0}}\\left(\\frac{-a_i}{a_n}\\right)^{\\frac 1{n-i}}.</math>\nIf all nonzero coefficients have the same sign, there is no positive root, and the maximum must be defined as being zero.\n\nOther bounds have been recently developed, mainly for the need of the [[Real-root isolation#Method of continued fractions|method of continued fractions]] for [[real-root isolation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Akritas |first=Alkiviadis G. |first2=A. W. |last2=Strzebo\u0144ski |first3=P. S. |last3=Vigklas |title=Improving the performance of the continued fractions method using new bounds of positive roots |journal=Nonlinear Analysis: Modelling and Control |year=2008 |volume=13 |pages=265\u2013279 |url=http://www.lana.lt/journal/30/Akritas.pdf |access-date=2019-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111718/http://www.lana.lt/journal/30/Akritas.pdf |archive-date=2013-12-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>\u015etef\u0103nescu, D. ''Bounds for Real Roots and Applications to Orthogonal Polynomials''. In: V. G. Ganzha, E. W. Mayr and E. V. Vorozhtsov (Editors): Proceedings of the 10th International Workshop on Computer Algebra in Scientific Computing, CASC 2007, pp. 377 \u2013 391, Bonn, Germany, September 16-20, 2007. LNCS 4770, Springer Verlag, Berlin, Heidelberg.</ref>\n\n===Polynomials whose roots are all real===\n\nIf all roots of a polynomial are real, [[Edmond Laguerre|Laguerre]] proved the following lower and upper bounds of the roots, by using what is now called [[Samuelson's inequality]].<ref name=Laguerre1880>{{cite journal | author = Laguerre E | title = Sur une m\u00e9thode pour obtenir par approximation les racines d'une \u00e9quation alg\u00e9brique qui a toutes ses racines r\u00e9elles | pages = 161\u2013172, 193\u2013202 | year = 1880 | journal = [[Nouvelles Annales de Math\u00e9matiques]] | series = 2 | volume = 19 | url = http://www.numdam.org/numdam-bin/browse?id=NAM_1880_2_19_ }}.</ref>\n\nLet <math>\\sum_{k=0}^n a_k x^k</math> be a polynomial with all real roots. Then its roots are located in the interval with endpoints\n:<math>-\\frac{a_{n-1}}{na_n} \\pm \\frac{n-1}{na_n}\\sqrt{a^2_{n-1} - \\frac{2n}{n-1}a_n a_{n-2}}.</math>\n\nFor example, the roots of the polynomial <math>x^4+5x^3+5x^2-5x-6=(x+3)(x+2)(x+1)(x-1)</math> satisfy\n:<math>-3.8118<-\\frac{5}{4} - \\frac{3}{4}\\sqrt{\\frac{35}{3}}\\le x\\le -\\frac{5}{4} + \\frac{3}{4}\\sqrt{\\frac{35}{3}}<1.3118.</math>\n\n==Root separation==\n\nThe '''root separation''' of a polynomial is the minimal distance between two roots, that is the minimum of the absolute values of the difference of two roots:\n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) = \\min\\{|\\alpha-\\beta|\\;;\\; \\alpha \\neq \\beta \\text{ and } p(\\alpha)=p(\\beta)=0\\}</math>\n\nThe root separation is a fundamental parameter of the [[computational complexity]] of [[root-finding algorithm]]s for polynomials. In fact, the root separation determines the precision of number representation that is needed for being sure of distinguishing different roots. Also, for [[real-root isolation]], it allows bounding the number of interval divisions that are needed for isolating all roots.\n\nFor polynomials with real or complex coefficients is not possible to express a lower bound of the root separation in terms of the degree and the absolute values of the coefficients only, because a small change on a single coefficient transforms a polynomial with multiple roots in a [[square-free polynomial]] with a small root separation, and essentially the same absolute values of the coefficient. However, involving the [[discriminant]] of the polynomial allows a lower bound.\n\nFor square-free polynomials with integer coefficients, the discriminant is an integer, and has thus an absolute value  that is not lower than {{val|1}}. This allows lower bounds for root separation that are independent from the discriminant.\n\nMignotte's separation bound is<ref>{{harvnb|Yap|2000|loc=\u00a7 VI.7, Proposition 29}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=George E.|last=Collins|authorlink=George E. Collins|title=Polynomial minimum root separation|journal=Journal of Symbolic Computation|year=2001|volume= 32|pages= 467\u2013473| doi=10.1006/jsco.2001.0481|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82808521.pdf }}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) >  \\frac {\\sqrt 3\\Delta(p)}{n^{n/2+1}(\\|p\\|_2)^{n-1}},</math>\nwhere <math>\\Delta(p)</math> is the discriminant, and <math>\\textstyle\\|p\\|_2=\\sqrt{a_0^2+a_1^2+\\dots+a_n^2}.</math> \n\nFor a square free polynomial with integer coefficients, this implies \n:<math>\\operatorname{sep}(p) >  \\frac {\\sqrt 3}{n^{n/2+1}(\\|p\\|_2)^{n-1}}> \\frac 1{2^{2s^2}},</math>\nwhere {{mvar|s}} is the [[bit]] size of {{mvar|p}}, that is the sum of the bitsize of its coefficients.\n\n==Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem==\n{{main|Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem}}\nThe Gauss\u2013Lucas theorem states that the [[convex hull]] of the roots of a polynomial contains the roots of the [[derivative]] of the polynomial.\n\nA sometimes useful corollary is that, if all roots of a polynomial have positive real part, then so do the roots of all derivatives of the polynomial.\n\nA related result is [[Bernstein's inequality in mathematical analysis|Bernstein's inequality]]. It states that for a polynomial ''P'' of degree ''n'' with derivative ''P\u2032'' we have\n:<math>\\max_{|z| \\leq 1} \\big|P'(z)\\big| \\le n \\max_{|z| \\leq 1} \\big|P(z)\\big|.</math>\n\n==Statistical distribution of the roots==\n\nIf the coefficients {{math|''a''<sub>i</sub>}} of a random polynomial are independently and identically distributed with a [[mean]] of zero, most complex roots are on the unit circle or close to it. In particular, the real roots are mostly located near {{math|\u00b11}}, and, moreover, their expected number is, for a large degree, less than the [[natural logarithm]] of the degree.\n\nIf the coefficients are [[Gaussian distribution|Gaussian distributed]] with a mean of zero and [[variance]] of ''\u03c3'' then the mean density of real roots is given by the Kac formula<ref name=Kac1943>{{cite journal |last=Kac |first=M. |authorlink=Mark Kac |year=1943 |title=On the average number of real roots of a random algebraic equation |journal=[[Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society]] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=314\u2013320 |doi=10.1090/S0002-9904-1943-07912-8 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=Kac1948>{{cite journal |last=Kac |first=M. |year=1948 |title=On the Average Number of Real Roots of a Random Algebraic Equation (II) |journal=[[Proceedings of the London Mathematical Society]] |series=Second Series |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=390\u2013408 |doi=10.1112/plms/s2-50.5.390 }}</ref>\n\n: <math> m( x ) = \\frac { \\sqrt{ A( x ) C( x ) - B( x )^2 }} {\\pi A( x )} </math>\n\nwhere\n\n: <math> \\begin{align}\nA(x) &= \\sigma \\sum x^{2i} = \\sigma \\frac{x^{2n} - 1}{x-1}, \\\\\nB(x) &= \\frac 1 2 \\frac{ d } { dx } A( x ), \\\\\nC(x) &= \\frac 1 4 \\frac{d^2} {dx^2} A(x) + \\frac 1 { 4x } \\frac d {dx} A(x).\n\\end{align} </math>\n\nWhen the coefficients are Gaussian distributed with a non-zero mean and variance of ''\u03c3'', a similar but more complex formula is known.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\n===Real roots===\nFor large {{math|''n''}}, the mean density of real roots near {{mvar|x}} is asymptotically\n\n: <math> m( x ) = \\frac{ 1 } { \\pi | 1 - x^2 | } </math>\nif <math>x^2-1\\ne 0,</math>\nand\n: <math> m(\\pm 1) = \\frac 1 \\pi \\sqrt {\\frac{n^2 - 1}{12}} </math>\n\nIt follows that the expected number of real roots is, using [[big O notation|big {{mvar|O}} notation]]\n: <math> N_n = \\frac 2 \\pi \\ln n + C + \\frac 2 {\\pi n} +O( n^{ -2 } ) </math>\nwhere {{math|''C''}} is a constant approximately equal to {{val|0.6257358072}}.<ref name=ek>{{cite journal|last1=Edelman|first1=Alan|last2=Kostlan|first2=Eric|title=How many zeros of a random polynomial are real?| journal=Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society|year=1995|volume=32|pp=1-37|doi=10.1090/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9 |issue=1|url=https://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1995-32-01/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9/S0273-0979-1995-00571-9.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn other words, ''the expected number of real roots of a random polynomial of high degree is lower than the [[natural logarithm]] of the degree''.\n\nKac, Erd\u00f6s and others have shown that these results are insensitive to the distribution of the coefficients, if they are independent and have the same distribution with mean zero. However, if the  variance of the {{mvar|i}}th coefficient equal to <math>\\binom ni,</math> the expected number of real roots is <math>\\sqrt n.</math><ref name=ek/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Descartes' rule of signs]]\n* [[Marden's theorem]]\n* [[Newton's identities]]\n* [[Quadratic function#Upper bound on the magnitude of the roots]]\n* [[Real-root isolation]]\n* [[Root-finding algorithm#Roots of polynomials]]\n* [[Square-free polynomial]]\n* [[Vieta's formulas]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last1=Rahman | first1=Q. I. | last2=Schmeisser | first2=G. | title=Analytic theory of polynomials | series=London Mathematical Society Monographs. New Series | volume=26 | location=Oxford | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | year=2002 | isbn=0-19-853493-0 | zbl=1072.30006 }}\n* {{cite book | last=Yap | first= Chee-Keng| title=Fundamental problems of algorithmic algebra| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]| year = 2000|isbn=978-0195125160|ref=harv|\nurl=http://160592857366.free.fr/joe/ebooks/ShareData/Fundamental%20Problems%20in%20Algorithmic%20Algebra%201993%20Yap.pdf}}.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/roots/ The beauty of the roots], a visualization of the distribution of all roots of all polynomials with degree and integer coefficients in some range.\n\n[[Category:Polynomials]]\n", "name_user": "D.Lazard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:use of {{annotated link|}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometrical_properties_of_polynomial_roots"}
{"title_page": "Michelle Rhee", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American educational reformer}}\n{{lead too short|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Michelle Rhee\n| image = Michelle Rhee, 2012 (cropped).jpg\n| office = Chancellor of [[District of Columbia Public Schools]]\n| deputy = Kaya Henderson\n| term_start = June 12, 2007\n| term_end = October 29, 2010\n| predecessor = Clifford Janey\n| successor = [[Kaya Henderson]]\n| office1 = First Lady of [[Sacramento]]\n| 1blankname1 = Mayor\n| 1namedata1 = [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]]\n| term_label1 = In role\n| term_start1 = September 3, 2011\n| term_end1 = December 13, 2016\n| predecessor1 = Mary Yee\n| successor1 = Julie Steinberg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|12|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = [[Kevin S. Huffman|Kevin Huffman]] (divorced 2007)<br />{{marriage|[[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]]|2011}}\n| children = 2 daughters\n| education = [[Cornell University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Policy|MPP]])\n}}\n'''Michelle A. Rhee''' (born December 25, 1969) is an American educator and advocate for education reform.<ref name=SF>{{cite web|title=Michelle A. Rhee, Founder and CEO of StudentsFirst|url=http://www.studentsfirst.org/pages/about-michelle-rhee|website=www.studentsfirst.org|publisher=StudentsFirst|accessdate=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701200501/http://www.studentsfirst.org/pages/about-michelle-rhee|archivedate=July 1, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was Chancellor of [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] from 2007 to 2010. In late 2010, she founded [[StudentsFirst]], a non-profit organization that works on education reform.<ref>{{cite news |author=Valerie Strauss |title=Michelle Rhee to step down as StudentsFirst chief, take \u2018next step in life\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2014/08/13/michelle-rhee-reported-to-be-stepping-down-as-studentsfirst-chief/ |newspaper=Washington Post |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2015 }}<br />{{cite news |author=Tom Knox |title=Former D.C. schools chief Michelle Rhee joins Scotts board |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/news/2014/08/11/former-d-c-schools-chief-joins-scotts-board.html |newspaper=Columbus Business First |date=August 11, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2015 |quote=Michelle Rhee, who also goes by Michelle Johnson, will serve on two of the Scotts board\u2019s six committees \u2013 innovation and marketing, and compensation and organization, the Marysville lawn and garden company said Monday. }}</ref>\n\nShe began her career by teaching for three years in an inner city school, then founded and ran [[The New Teacher Project]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRhee was born in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], the second of three children of [[South Korea]]n immigrants Shang Rhee, a physician, and Inza Rhee, a clothing store owner.<ref name=\"DCExaminer2007\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Michelle A. Rhee |url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2009-06-14/news/36818883_1_rhee-research-firm-new-teacher-project |newspaper=Washington Post |date=June 14, 2009 |accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/><ref name=\"tackles\"/> She was raised in the [[Toledo, Ohio]] area and educated in [[state school|public schools]], through the sixth grade. Her parents then sent her to South Korea to attend school for one year. Upon her return, they enrolled her in a private school because they felt the public school was lacking.  She graduated from the private [[Maumee Valley Country Day School]] in 1988, and went on to [[Cornell University]] where she received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[government]] in 1992. She later earned a [[Master of Public Policy]] from [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]].\n\n==Teaching==\nInspired by a [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] special that she saw during her senior year in college, Rhee signed up with [[Teach For America]], went through their five-week summer training program, then worked for three years as a teacher in [[Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/><ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> She was assigned to Harlem Park Elementary School, one of the lowest-performing schools.<ref name=\"tackles\"/> Rhee told ''[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]'' magazine that she was demoralized by her first year of teaching, but said to herself, \"I\u2019m not going to let eight-year-old kids run me out of town.\" She said she took courses over the summer and received her [[Certified teacher|teacher's certification]], then returned to teach at Harlem Park.<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/>  Her \"Teach For America\" Training did not prepare her well to handle basic classroom management. She was so unprepared that in order to quiet down a class she taped children's mouths shut. One of the children's lips bled a little when the tape was removed.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/video/2010/08/13/VI2010081305444.html</ref>\n\nIn her second and third years of teaching, Rhee team taught a combined class of the same students with another teacher.<ref name=\"TeamTeaching\"/> She told ''The New York Times'' that those students had national [[standardized test]] scores that were initially at the 13th percentile but at the end of two years, the class was at grade level, with some students performing at the 90th percentile.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> Earlier she had said on her r\u00e9sum\u00e9 that 90 percent of her students had attained scores at the 90th percentile.<ref name=\"early test\"/> In math, her scores went from 22 percentile to 52 percentile, an average increase of 15 percentile annually.<ref name=\"HarlemPark\">{{cite news|url=http://gfbrandenburg.files.wordpress.com/2011/01/cohort-effects-at-harlem-park-jpg.jpg|title=Proficiency Scores at Harlem Park Elementary|accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> In reading, her scores went from 14 percentile to 48 percentile, an average increase of 17 percentile annually.<ref name=\"HarlemPark\"/> Rhee responded that the discrepancies between the official test scores and the ones listed on her r\u00e9sum\u00e9 could be explained by the fact that her principal at the time informed her of the gains but those results may not have been the official state tests that were preserved.<ref name=\"early test\"/>\n\n==The New Teacher Project==\nIn 1997, Rhee founded and began serving as the CEO of [[The New Teacher Project]], a nonprofit that within ten years of its founding, trained and supplied urban school districts with 23,000 mid-career professionals wanting to become classroom teachers.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> The project primarily serves New York, Chicago, Miami, and Philadelphia.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> Beginning in 2000, the project began redesigning the D.C. schools' recruitment and hiring processes.<ref name=\"DCExaminer2007\"/>\n\n==Chancellor of D.C. public schools==\nIn 2007 the D.C. Board of Education was stripped of its decision-making powers and turned into an advisory body, and the new office of chancellor was created\u2014so changes in the public school system could be made without waiting for the approval of the board.<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/><ref name=\"tackles\"/> Newly elected D.C. mayor [[Adrian Fenty]] quickly offered Rhee the job of chancellor;<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/> she accepted after being promised  mayoral backing for whatever changes she wanted to make.<ref name=\"fenty to oust\"/> Critics noted that Rhee had no experience running a school system,<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/> and had not even been a principal. She had been highly recommended to Fenty, however, by [[Joel Klein]], the [[New York City School Chancellor|chancellor]] of the [[New York City Department of Education|New York City public schools]].<ref name=\"was fired\"/>\n\nRhee inherited a troubled system; there had been six school chiefs in the previous 10 years,<ref name=\"Washingtonian 2007\"/> students historically had below-average scores on standardized tests,<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/r/michelle_rhee/index.html|title=Michelle A. Rhee News \u2013 The New York Times |date=December 7, 2012 |accessdate=April 17, 2012}}</ref> and according to Rhee, only 8 percent of eighth graders were performing at grade level in mathematics.<ref name=\"devastating\"/> The D.C. schools were performing poorly despite having the advantage of the third highest spending per student in the U.S.<ref name=\"spends\"/> Fenty and Rhee announced that they planned to make revolutionary changes in D.C. schools, and that part of the planned changes was a hoped-for \"grand bargain\" with teachers under which \"greater accountability, including an end to tenure,\" would be traded \"for a nearly 100-percent increase in salaries.\"<ref name=CITY>{{cite journal|last1=Sahm|first1=Charles|title=The Democrat's Education Divide|journal=City Journal|date=September 12, 2008|url=http://www.city-journal.org/2008/eon0912cs.html|accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 she also tried to renegotiate teacher compensation, offering teachers the choice of salaries of up to $140,000 based on what she termed \"student achievement\" with no [[tenure]] rights or earning much smaller pay raises with tenure rights retained. Teachers and the teachers union rejected the proposal, contesting that some form of tenure was necessary to protect against arbitrary, political, or wrongful termination of employment.<ref name=\"takes on tenure\"/>\n\nIn 2010 Rhee and the unions agreed on a new contract that offered 20 percent pay raises and bonuses of $20,000 to $30,000 for \"strong student achievement,\" in exchange for weakened teachers' seniority protections and the end of teacher tenure for one year. Under this new agreement, Rhee fired 241 teachers, the vast majority of whom received poor evaluations, and put 737 additional school employees on notice.<ref name=\"dismisses 241\"/>\n\n===Criticism===\nRhee's style of reform created a great deal of controversy. One common criticism disputes her assertion that, while a teacher, she dramatically increased students' average scores from the 13th percentile to the 90th. It was a statement that could not be verified during her confirmation process for D.C. Schools Chancellor.<ref name=\"challenge resume\"/>\n\nRhee contended that under her chancellorship, student achievement in the D.C. Public Schools greatly improved. Since 2007, secondary schools have improved their standardized test pass rates by 14 percent in reading and 17 percent in math, while elementary school pass rates have improved 6 percent in reading and 15 percent in math. Systemwide high school graduation rates also improved by 3 percent, up to 72 percent in 2009.<ref name=\"tied\"/> By 2010, D.C. Comprehensive Assessment System reading pass rates had increased by 14 percentage points, and math pass rates had increased by 17 percentage points. Enrollment decreased by 1 percent, a slower decline than prior years.<ref name=\"tied\"/> However, significant achievement gaps remained between students in high-performing and low-performing school districts, and between white and black students. Education historian [[Diane Ravitch]] questioned the legitimacy of Rhee's results, alleging that \"cheating, teaching to bad tests, institutionalized fraud, dumbing down of tests, and a narrowed curriculum\" were the true outcomes of Rhee's tenure in D.C. schools.<ref name=\"Ravitch\"/>\n\nSome D.C. parents and community leaders complained that despite these improvements, the speed with which Rhee enacted her reforms left them without input on the changes. The District Council also criticized Rhee for being unresponsive to council members' requests for information about school operations. From 2008 to 2010, Rhee's approval ratings decreased from 59 percent to 43 percent. In 2010, 28 percent of African Americans supported Rhee, down from 50 percent in 2008. Yet even \"as residents grow less supportive of Fenty's designated change agent for the schools,\" noted the Washington Post, \"they still approve of some of the changes. The proportion of parents in the city who see violence or crime as a 'big problem' has declined from 78 to 65 percent.... The quality and availability of books and other instructional materials is viewed as less of a major problem by all parents, dropping from 67 percent to 48 percent.\" Also, the Post indicated that \"Rhee's efforts to raise the quality of teaching through improved training, evaluation, and dismissals might be gaining traction as well.\"<ref name=\"slide\"/>\n\nRhee fired several administrators and school principals, including Marta Guzman, the principal of the high-performing Oyster\u2013Adams Bilingual Elementary School, which Rhee's own children attended.<ref name=\"tackles\"/><ref name=\"Turque2008\"/> Some parents alleged that the firing process was neither transparent nor fair. According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', \"the departure has stunned many Oyster\u2013Adams parents who wondered why, in a city filled with underperforming public schools, Rhee would sack a principal who has presided for the past five years over one of its few success stories. The move also heightened ethnic and class tensions within the school's diverse community. Eduardo Barada, co-chairman of the Oyster\u2013Adams Community Council, the school's PTA, said Guzman was toppled by a cadre of dissatisfied and largely affluent Anglo parents with the ear of a woman who was both a fellow parent and the chancellor.\"<ref name=\"Turque2008\"/> Rhee also fired a principal she had hired seven weeks before in Shepherd Elementary, another high-performing school in the upper [[Northwest, Washington, D.C.|Northwest neighborhood]].<ref name=\"fires shepherd\"/>\n\nRhee was criticized for closing several D.C. schools without holding public hearings,<ref name=\"News8_2008\"/> for not reporting complete budget figures at D.C. council hearings,<ref name=\"News8_2008\"/> for not involving parents to a sufficient degree,<ref name=\"urges more\"/> hiring former supporters to conduct an evaluation of her performance,<ref name=\"watchdog\"/> and for spending considerable time before the national media (''Time'', PBS, lecture circuit) instead of visiting schools.<ref name=\"News8_2008\"/> When Rhee outlined a proposed new security plan in a talk at [[Woodrow Wilson High School (Washington, DC)|Woodrow Wilson High School]], many students protested and proposed an alternative plan, Rhee responded indicating that she found the student plan well thought out and that she would consider incorporating aspects into the final plan.<ref name=\"walk out\"/>\n\n[[File:Michelle Rhee at NOAA.jpg|right|thumb|230px|Rhee at a [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] awards ceremony, June 2008]]\n\nReferring to the 266 teachers she laid off, Rhee told a national business magazine: \"I got rid of teachers who had hit children, who had had sex with children, who had missed 78 days of school. Why wouldn't we take those things into consideration?\" George Parker, president of the teachers union, called Rhee's statements \"reckless,\" said they had no factual basis, and demanded that Rhee apologize to the 266 teachers for making these remarks.<ref name=\"abused kids\" /> Rhee declined to apologize for her statement, claimed that one of the 266 dismissed employees had been accused of sexual misconduct, six had been suspended for using corporal punishment, and two had been absent without leave, while many others also had egregious time and attendance records.<ref name=\"Hedge\" />\n\n===2010 election and resignation===\n{{wikinews|District of Columbia Public Schools chancellor Michelle Rhee announces resignation}}\nThe [[2010 Washington, D.C. mayoral election|2010 mayoral election in Washington, D.C.,]]  was interpreted by some political observers as, in part, a referendum on Rhee's tenure as school chancellor.<ref name=\"Fenty's Loss\"/> Following the defeat of incumbent mayor Adrian Fenty in the 2010 Democratic primary election, Fenty announced on October 13, 2010, that Rhee had resigned. Rhee launched a personal website, a [[Twitter]] account, and a [[Facebook]] page soon thereafter.<ref name=\"resign\"/>\n\n===Test erasures===\n{{POV section|date=September 2012}}\nOpponents of Rhee, arguing that she had not genuinely improved education in D.C. schools, maintained that improvement in test scores must have been due to cheating, and attempted to show that changes made on some students\u2019 tests, in which wrong answers were erased and correct answers substituted, indicated a systematic pattern of answer-changing, presumably at Rhee\u2019s direction.<ref name=\"blames enemies\"/> These complaints led to studies of the alleged erasures.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillum |first=Jack |last2=Bello |first2=Marisol |date=March 30, 2011 |title=When standardized test scores soared in D.C., were the gains real? |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/education/2011-03-28-1Aschooltesting28_CV_N.htm |newspaper=USA Today |accessdate=October 18, 2014 }}</ref> In 2012, District of Columbia's inspector general conducted an investigation at Noyes Education Campus, and based on that investigation, it concluded \"investigators found no evidence to corroborate these allegations\", and that there was \"no evidence of criminal activity or widespread cheating on the DC CAS exams\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/r/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2012/08/08/Local/Graphics/OIG%20Report%20-%20Testing.pdf |title=Report of Investigation into Cheating on the DC Comprehensive Assessment System Standardized Exams Administered by the District of Columbia Public Schools OIG NO. 2011-0318 |last1=Pittell |first1=Stacie |last2=Willoughby |first2=Charles J. |date=August 8, 2012 |website=Washington Post |accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the U.S. Department of Education released the results of their investigation finding that there was no evidence of widespread cheating in the D.C. public schools.  The investigation focused on a single school out of the dozens of schools where high rates of test erasures were reported.  The investigation also excluded Rhee's first year.  Only one incident of cheating that may have affected funding was found.<ref name=\"Frontline2013\">{{cite news | url= https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/education/education-of-michelle-rhee/education-department-finds-no-evidence-of-widespread-cheating-on-d-c-exams/ | title = Education Department Finds No Evidence Of Widespread Cheating On D.C. Exams | date = January 8, 2013 | first = Jason M. | last = Breslow | work = [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] | accessdate = March 21, 2013}}</ref>{{Disputed inline|Test erasures|date=October 2014}}\n\n==School choice and school vouchers==\nRhee was originally neutral on school vouchers, issuing a 2008 statement that she had not \"taken a formal position on vouchers\" and that she disagreed \"with the notion that vouchers are the remedy for repairing the city\u2019s school system.\"<ref name=\"position on vouchers\"/> In an op-ed published in the ''Wall Street Journal'' on January 11, 2011, Rhee endorsed vouchers, saying that she supported \"giving poor families access to publicly funded scholarships to attend private schools.\" She added that \"All children deserve the chance to get a great education; no family should be forced to send kids to a school they know is failing.\"<ref name=\"an opening\"/> In a February 2011 speech before Georgia's legislature, she indicated she had supported the D.C. voucher program as a supplement to the charter school alternative. She said that if a parent did not win the [[lottery]] to get a child into a charter school, then \"who am I to deny them a $7,500 voucher to send their child to a great Catholic school.\"<ref name=\"on vouchers\">{{cite news|title=Michelle Rhee on vouchers, social promotion and putting kids first|date=February 10, 2011|author=Maureen Downey|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/get-schooled-blog/2011/02/10/michelle-rhee-on-vouchers-social-promotion-and-putting-kids-first/|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|accessdate=July 17, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221104559/http://blogs.ajc.com/get-schooled-blog/2011/02/10/michelle-rhee-on-vouchers-social-promotion-and-putting-kids-first/|archivedate=February 21, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==After D.C. schools==\n[[File:StudentsFirst founder Michelle Rhee delivering her speech at Policy Exchange.jpg|thumb|left|Rhee speaking to [[Policy Exchange]] in 2012]]\nOn December 6, 2010, Rhee went on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]] to announce that she had declined all job offers resulting from her high-profile work as D.C. Chancellor and would be focusing on a new advocacy organization she had formed called [[StudentsFirst]].<ref name=\"big announcement\"/> She told Winfrey's audience she wanted to have one million members and raise $1 billion in order to catalyze education reform in the United States.<ref name=\"big announcement\"/> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'' abolishing teacher [[tenure]] is a main objective of Rhee and the group.<ref name=\"take aim\"/> Within weeks of its founding, Rhee and StudentsFirst had advised the governors of Florida, Nevada and New Jersey on abolishing teacher tenure and other issues related to public education reform.<ref name=\"take aim\"/>  In 2010\u20132011, Rhee served on the transition team of Florida Republican governor [[Rick Scott]].<ref name=\"not heading\"/>\n\nShe has also been a visible figure in the national media, appearing on television shows, radio programs, and the documentary film ''[[Waiting for \"Superman\"|Waiting for Superman]]''. In May 2011, Rhee spoke in favor of school choice alongside the Wisconsin Republican governor, [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], at an event hosted by the American Federation for Children, a pro-[[school choice]] education organization founded and funded by [[Betsy DeVos]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post_now/post/michelle-rhee-to-speak-in-dc/2011/05/09/AFPQkzWG_blog.html|title=Rhee to speak in D.C|agency=Associated Press|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2011|access-date=July 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Rhee wrote ''Radical: Fighting to Put Students First''.\n\nIn August 2014, Rhee became a board member of the [[Scotts Miracle-Gro Company]].<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2014/08/13/michelle-rhee-reported-to-be-stepping-down-as-studentsfirst-chief/</ref> She also replaced Jim Scheible as chairman of St. Hope Public Schools, a [[charter school]] chain run by her husband, Sacramento mayor [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]],<ref name=leave14>{{cite web|last1=Resmovits|first1=Joy|title=Michelle Rhee Will Leave CEO Job At StudentsFirst, Group She Founded |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/12/michelle-rhee-studentsfirst_n_5672586.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|access-date=August 24, 2014|date=August 13, 2014}}<br />{{cite news|last1=Strauss|first1=Valerie|title=Michelle Rhee has a new position|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2014/08/05/michelle-rhee-has-a-new-position/|access-date=April 30, 2015|agency=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|date=August 5, 2014}}</ref> and subsequently announced that she would be stepping down as CEO of StudentsFirst.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelle Rhee former DC schools chief leaving StudentsFirst post|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/michelle-rhee-former-d-c-schools-chief-leaving-studentsfirst-post-1407979573|website=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|access-date=August 24, 2014|date=August 12, 2014}}</ref> On March 29, 2016, StudentsFirst announced some of its state chapters would merge with [[50CAN]], a nonprofit education advocacy group based in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.the74million.org/article/the-74-exclusive-ed-reform-groups-studentsfirst-and-50can-to-merge|title=The 74 Exclusive: Ed Reform Groups StudentsFirst and 50CAN to Merge|last=Keierleber|first=Mark|date=March 29, 2016|work=|access-date=April 4, 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2016, Rhee met with President-elect [[Donald Trump]] and Vice President\u2013elect [[Mike Pence]], sparking speculation that she was in consideration for [[United States Secretary of Education|Secretary of Education]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/11/19/trump-meets-with-school-reformer-democrat-michelle-rhee-with-education-secretary-post-still-open.html|title=Trump meets with school reformer, Democrat Michelle Rhee with education secretary post still open|publisher=FoxNews.com|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gma.yahoo.com/trump-set-meet-today-mitt-romney-michelle-rhee-175904622--abc-news-topstories.html|title=Trump Met With Mitt Romney, Set to Also Meet Michelle Rhee and Others|publisher=ABC News|website=yahoo.com|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> Rhee later [[Twitter|tweeted]] that she was not interested in pursuing the position.<ref name=\"WaPo_Brown\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Emma|title=Michelle Rhee takes herself out of the running for Trump\u2019s education secretary|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/education/wp/2016/11/22/michelle-rhee-takes-herself-out-of-the-running-for-trumps-education-secretary/|accessdate=23 November 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nRhee has served on the advisory boards for the [[National Council on Teacher Quality]],<ref name=\"nctq\"/> and the National Center for Alternative Certification.<ref name=\"alt cert\"/> She was a special guest of [[First Lady]] [[Laura Bush]] at [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]]'s 2008 [[State of the Union]] address.<ref name=\"among first\"/>\n \n==Family and personal life==\nWhile Rhee was teaching, she met [[Kevin S. Huffman|Kevin Huffman]], who was also a member of Teach for America and later became head of public affairs of the organization.<ref name=\"tackles\"/> The couple married two years after meeting; while married they had two daughters. They divorced in 2007.<ref name=\"unlikely\"/> Both daughters attend private schools, the [[Harpeth Hall School]] in [[Nashville]], Tennessee,<ref name=\"psparent\">{{cite web|last=Mishak|first=Michael J.|title=Michelle Rhee, 'a public school parent'?|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/political/la-me-pc-michelle-rhee-a-public-school-parent-20130328,0,6195587.story|publisher=L. A. Times|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}<br />{{cite news |author=Valerie Strauss |title=Michelle Rhee, a private school parent? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2013/03/29/michelle-rhee-a-private-school-parent/ |newspaper=Washington Post |date=March 29, 2013 |access-date=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> and the [[Chattanooga Christian School]] in [[Chattanooga]], Tennessee.\nIn March 2010, Rhee became engaged to [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]], 55th mayor of [[Sacramento, California]], and former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player.<ref name=\"SacOb24JAN2013\">{{cite news|url=http://sacobserver.com/2013/01/education-reformer-michelle-rhee-speaks-locally/|title=Education reformer Michelle Rhee Speaks Locally|date=January 24, 2013|newspaper=Sacramento Observer|accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Lessons\"/><ref name=\"engaged\"/> The two married in September 2011 in a small ceremony at [[Blackberry Farm (Tennessee)|Blackberry Farm]] near [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref>Reliable Source blog: [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/post/michelle-rhee-and-kevin-johnson-kept-their-wedding-under-the-radar/2011/09/07/gIQAZIXIAK_blog.html Michelle Rhee and Kevin Johnson kept their wedding under the radar], ''Washington Post'' (September 7, 2011). Retrieved on November 20, 2011.</ref><ref>Reliable Source blog: [http://voices.washingtonpost.com/reliable-source/2010/08/michelle_rhee_and_kevin_johnso.html Michelle Rhee and Kevin Johnson downsize their wedding], ''Washington Post'' (August 25, 2010). Retrieved on November 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Education|Biography}}\n* [[Lobbying in the United States#The focus of lobbying efforts|Lobbying in the United States]]\n* [[No Child Left Behind Act]]\n* [[Privatization]]\n* [[Teaching to the test]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"abused kids\">{{cite news |author= Bill Turque |title=Rhee says laid-off teachers in D.C. abused kids |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/22/AR2010012204543.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |page= |date=January 23, 2010 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"alt cert\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teach-now.org/aboutboard.cfm|title=Advisory Board|publisher=National Center for Alternative Certification|accessdate=May 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720125627/http://www.teach-now.org/aboutboard.cfm|archivedate=July 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"among first\">{{cite news |title=Michelle Rhee Among First Lady's Guests|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2008/01/28/ST2008012801147.html|author=Howard Schneider |work=The Washington Post |date=January 28, 2008 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"an opening\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704739504576068142896954626|title= In Budget Crises, an Opening for School Reform: School systems