      = <!-- Note: Use and cite reliable sources to identify genre/s, not personal interpretation. Please don't include more than three genres (per [[MOS:A&M]]). --> Action\n| creator         = MTJJ\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = ONA\n| title           = \n| director        = \n| producer        = \n| writer          = \n| music           = Mint Image, Wang Wei, Xiao Chen Ge\n| studio          = [[Beijing Hanmu Chunhua Animation Technology|Beijing Hanmu Chunhua Animation Technology Co., Ltd.]]\n| licensee        = \n| first           = March 18, 2011\n| last            = ongoing\n| episodes        = <!-- This parameter should only be incremented when new episodes air or when a [[Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources|reliable source]] can confirm a specific number of episodes. --> 27 + 3 specials\n| episode_list    = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n'''The Legend of Luo Xiaohei''' (\u7f57\u5c0f\u9ed1\u6218\u8bb0) is a [[flash animation]] and web cartoon by Chinese artist MTJJ (real name Zhang Ping).<ref>{{citation|url= http://www.iqiyi.com/dongman/2012dmjnh.html/ |title=2012\u7231\u5947\u827a\u52a8\u6f2b\u5609\u5e74\u534e |accessdate=2013-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130731233834/http://www.iqiyi.com/dongman/2012dmjnh.html |archivedate=2013-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url= http://tdvf2013.tudou.com/ |title=2013\u571f\u8c46\u6620\u50cf\u8282 |accessdate=2013-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130514005135/http://tdvf2013.tudou.com/ |archivedate=2013-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url= http://www.comicfans.net/special/cicf6/news/2013/09/10/09255529419.html |title=2013\u4e2d\u56fd\u52a8\u6f2b\u91d1\u9f99\u5956 |accessdate=2013-05-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913015408/http://www.comicfans.net/special/cicf6/news/2013/09/10/09255529419.html|archivedate=2019-09-13}}</ref> The franchise has also extended to become a [[Sticker (messaging)|social media sticker]] series on [[Wechat]]. As of March 19, 2018, 27 episodes of \"The Legend of Luo Xiaohei\" are available alongside 3 extra videos, \"Exam Day\", \"Sh\u2026\", and \"Goodnight Meow\". A feature-length prequel film named \"The Legend of Hei\" was released on September 12, 2019.<ref>{{citation|url= https://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/the-chinese-web-series-the-legend-of-luo-xiaohei-is-getting-a-feature-spinoff-177712.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190802190354/https://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/the-chinese-web-series-the-legend-of-luo-xiaohei-is-getting-a-feature-spinoff-177712.html |archivedate=August 4, 2019 |title=The Chinese Web Series 'The Legend of Luo Xiaohei' Is Getting A Feature Spinoff}}</ref>\n\nThe series was adapted to graphic novel in 2015, published by [[Beijing United Publishing]]. It has also been turned into a mobile game titled \"Luo Xiaohei's Battle Demon Book\" (\u7f57\u5c0f\u9ed1\u6218\u8bb0\u5996\u7075\u7c3f) by [[Beijing Manya Entertainment Culture Media|Beijing Manya Entertainment Culture Media Co.]],<ref>{{citation|url= https://www.tap.io/app/39207 |archiveurl= https://www.tap.io/app/39207 |title=Luo Xiaohei's Battle Demon Book app |accessdate=2019-08-04 |archivedate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> and an event for the Chinese/Taiwanese edition of the mobile game [[Ensemble Stars!]] includes [[gijinka]] of the series' characters.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe story focuses on the titular Luo Xiaohei, a spirit that stole a certain artifact which resulted in him getting injured and weakened in the process, preventing him from using most of his abilities as well as making him unable to transform into his humanoid form making him stuck in a form of a small, black kitten with a blue tongue.\n\nAfter escaping those who wounded him, he sought shelter from the rain. The spirit hid inside a cardboard box in an alleyway within a city and took his rest there. Next day, however he woke up in a home of a young girl named Xiaobai who mistook him for a homeless cat, taking him in and giving him a name Xiaohei.\n\n== Characters ==\n* '''Luo Xiaohei''': A cat monster was severely injured when he stole Laojun's celestial pearl and was returned to its original form. He was picked up and adopted by Xiaobai when he was living on the street. When angry, the eyes will turn green, and the pupils will turn into thin yellow pupils like cats.\n* '''Luo Xiaobai''': Luo Xiaohei's owner, Agen's sister.\n* Mom: Luo Xiaobai's mother, who wears a mask all the year round, has appeared in the TV version.\n* Dad: Luo Xiaobai's dad, who covers his face with a newspaper in every episode. The true image is unknown, and his lines are in the newspaper.\n* Grandpa: Tucao Emperor, met Xuan Lizhen when he was young.\n* '''Agen''': Xuan Li (not claiming / defaulting to Xuan Li), Luo Xiaobai's brother, wearing glasses, is also a mythical beast like Xuan Ting, and can control the three states of water (even absorb fire) and release a clone. Has dual spirit space.\n* Shan Xin: Luo Xiaobai's good friend, Shushuang Ponytail, the owner of Huang Shou. (Note: Shanxin is also the name of a voice actor in reality )\n* Emperor Suspension: An ordinary gray tabby cat has been sticking to Xiao Hei madly since being rescued by Xiao Hei from SATAN's dog. [Note 1]\n* Heixiu: Luo Xiaohei's tail is split into a separate conscious body, which has telepathy with Luo Xiaohei, and can be divided infinitely. In general, it is divided into four.\n* Bidiu: A chamecavy, or a rabbit-like creature, captured by Agen to prevent Bidiu from eating his house. Chamecavies have a large appetite, and they turn into the color of the food that they have just eaten. It can be restored in about 5 minutes. If you eat animals or metal, the mutation will be huge and aggressive, and you can stop the bruising pattern between the eyebrows, but the mutation is very burdensome.\n* Laojun: The prototype of Taishang Laojun , who lives in Lanxi Town. He has made a number of vows and wrote them as \"Oath Records\". Those who complete the vows can get prizes. For example, there is a prize for those who do something to force Laojun. One of the vows is that he must not leave Laojun Pavilion or interfere in external affairs within a hundred years, but there is a bottom line (it is said that this vow was made by Laojun's apprentice Li Qingning).\n* Musi, Axian: Break into Laojun's enchantment because of Laojun's Oath Record (Note: they are based on the members of the Muting Club)\n* Infinite: Master Luo Xiaohei instructed Luo Xiaohei to steal the Pearl of Heaven. The ability is Royal Gold, and the space system can devour it.\n* Powder: Flower elf, asking Luo Xiaohei and Agen to rescue their companions.\n* Diting: the main antagonist of the series, who seeks revenge against Luo Xiaohei for stealing an artifact from him.\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! #\n! Title\n! Release Date\n|-\n| CAT.0\n| Trail Notice (\u9884\u544a)\n|2011-3-13\n|-\n| CAT.1\n| Cat (\u55b5)\n| 2011-3-17<br />2014-4-25(remastered)\n|-\n| CAT.2\n| Escape (\u9003)\n| 2011-6-1<br />2014-4-25(remastered)\n|-\n| Special\n| Final Exam\n| 2011-7-10\n|-\n| CAT.3\n| Hey! (\u563f)\n| 2012-1-16\n|-\n| CAT.4\n| The Wind (\u98d8)\n| 2012-6-11\n|-\n| CAT.5\n| Yo! (\u5537)\n| 2012-12-21\n|-\n| CAT.6\n| Root (\u963f\u6839)\n| 2013-3-21\n|-\n| CAT.7\n| Bidiu (\u6bd4\u4e22)\n| 2013-6-13\n|-\n| CAT.8\n| Deep Mountain (\u6df1\u5c71)\n| 2013-9-11\n|-\n| CAT.8.5 (Spoof)\n| Goodbye, Bidiu (\u518d\u898b\u4e86\uff0c\u6bd4\u4e1f)\n| 2013-9-12\n|-\n| CAT.9\n| Listen (\u8c1b\u542c)\n| 2013-12-30\n|-\n| CAT.10\n| Laojun (\u8001\u541b)\n| 2014-4-28\n|-\n| MV\n| Goodnight Meow (\u665a\u5b89\u55b5)\n| 2014-5-27\n|-\n| CAT.11\n| Lanxi Town (\u84dd\u6eaa\u9547)\n| 2014-7-23\n|-\n| CAT.12\n| Pickup (\u62fe\u8d30\u96c6)\n| 2014-9-17\n|-\n| CAT.13\n| Spiritual Power (\u7075\u8d28\u529b)\n| 2014-9-28\n|-\n| CAT.14\n| Flower Elf (\u82b1\u7cbe\u7075)\n| 2014-12-29\n|-\n| CAT.15\n| Lingfeng Mountain (\u7075\u98ce\u5c71)\n| 2015-2-5\n|-\n| CAT.16\n| Fairy and Elf (\u4ed9\u4e0e\u7cbe\u7075)\n| 2015-5-13\n|-\n| CAT.17\n| Calm (\u98ce\u5e73\u6d6a\u9759)\n| 2015-8-19\n|-\n| CAT.18\n| Top War (\u9876\u4e0a\u6218\u4e89)\n| 2015-10-28\n|-\n| CAT.19\n| City Center (\u57ce\u4e2d\u522b\u82d1)\n| 2015-11-25\n|-\n| CAT.20\n| Demon Hall (\u5996\u7075\u4f1a\u9986)\n| 2015-12-30\n|-\n| CAT.21\n| Target Day Pearl (\u76ee\u6807\u5929\u660e\u73e0)\n| 2016-4-28\n|-\n| CAT.22\n| Meet Auntie (\u76f8\u9047\u963f\u5472\u9601)\n| 2016-6-23\n|-\n| CAT.23\n| Inside and outside and winning and losing (\u5185\u5916\u4e0e\u80dc\u8d1f)\n|2016-8-23\n|-\n| CAT.24\n| Tacit Rules (\u9ed8\u5951\u7684\u89c4\u5219)\n|2016-11-30\n|-\n| MV\n| Sh... (\u5618)\n| 2017-1-11\n|-\n| CAT.25\n| Morning Sprout (\u6e05\u6668\u7684\u840c\u82bd)\n| 2017-3-30\n|-\n| CAT.26\n| Illegal Legal Person (\u975e\u6cd5\u8005\u5408\u6cd5\u8005)\n|2017-7-31\n|-\n| CAT.27\n| What's this Taste? (\u8fd9\u662f\u4ec0\u4e48\u6ecb\u5473)\n|2017-11-29\n|-\n| CAT.28\n| Not a \"Goodbye\", but a \"See you soon\" (\u79bb\u522b\u7ec8\u4f1a\u76f8\u89c1)\n|2019-8-27\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legend of Luo Xiaohei, The}}\n[[Category:Chinese animation]]\n[[Category:Fictional cats]]\n[[Category:Web animation]]\n[[Category:Flash cartoons]]\n\n\n{{animation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "TheBestVillager", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Legend_of_Luo_Xiaohei"}
{"title_page": "Sarah Clarke (Black Rod)", "text_new": "{{short description|British administrator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Sarah Clarke\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        =\n|imagesize    =\n|alt          =\n|caption      =\n|office       = [[Black Rod|Lady Usher of the Black Rod]]\n|term_start   = 13 February 2018\n|term_end     =\n|monarch      = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|predecessor  = [[David Leakey]]\n|successor    =\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=y|12 October 1965}}\n|birth_place  = [[Wolverhampton]], [[Staffordshire]], England\n|birthname    =\n|nationality  = British\n|spouse       =\n|children     =\n|residence    =\n|alma_mater   = [[Roehampton Institute of Higher Education]] <br /> [[University of Leicester]]\n|occupation   =\n|profession   =\n|portfolio    =\n|religion     =\n|website      =\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Sarah Clarke''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|OBE}} (born 12 October 1965) is a British administrator. Since 13 February 2018, she has served as [[Black Rod]], the first female Black Rod in the 650-year history of the role.  The role is formally \"The Lady Usher of the Black Rod\" (for previous incumbents \"Gentleman Usher of the Black Rod\").<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42025131|title=First female Black Rod in 650 years|date=17 November 2017|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 November 2017|via=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117142439/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42025131|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wimbledon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/articles/2017-11-17/2017-11-17_sarah_clarke_appointed_to_the_role_of_black_road.html|title=Sarah Clarke appointed to the role of Black Rod|website=www.wimbledon.com|accessdate=17 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040159/http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/articles/2017-11-17/2017-11-17_sarah_clarke_appointed_to_the_role_of_black_road.html|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>  Before taking this role, she was in charge of the administration of [[The Championships, Wimbledon]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nClarke was born on 12 October 1965 in [[Wolverhampton]], [[Staffordshire]], England. She was educated at [[Wolverhampton Girls' High School]], a [[grammar school]] in the town. She studied at the [[Roehampton Institute of Higher Education]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Science]] (BSc) degree in 1988: as the institute could not award its own degree, her BSc was validated by the [[University of Surrey]]. She obtained a certificate from the [[The Chartered Institute of Marketing|Institute of Marketing]] in 1993 and a [[Master of Science]] (MSc) degree from the [[University of Leicester]] in 2005.<ref name=\"WW 2019\">{{cite web |title=Clarke, Sarah |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-290330 |website=[[Who's Who 2019]] |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=10 September 2019 |date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Sport===\nPrior to working for Wimbledon, Clarkes first job was working as a tennis tournament organiser for Brian Hewitt Associates in Durham after which she worked on four Olympic Games, including the [[2012 Olympic Games]] in London, the [[London Marathon]], and [[UK Sport]].<ref name=\"wimbledon.com\"/>\n\nClarke was employed by [[The Championships, Wimbledon]], as Championships director, and first worked at Wimbledon as a school-leaver in 1986.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Martin|title=Inside Wimbledon: What really goes on behind the scenes|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2017/07/02/inside-wimbledon-really-goes-behind-scenes/|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=3 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705171215/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2017/07/02/inside-wimbledon-really-goes-behind-scenes/|archivedate=5 July 2017}}</ref>  Interviewed by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' in 2017, she commented on their quest for perfection, \"We live for details.  We love details\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Black Rod===\nClarke succeeded Lieutenant General [[David Leakey]], who retired in February 2018, as [[Black Rod]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Speaking to ''[[The Guardian]]'', Clarke said:\n{{quote|\"Over many years I have been fortunate to work at the heart of some of the world's most complex events and institutions.  To be given the opportunity to join such an experienced and dedicated team is a great privilege.  The House of Lords is a place where the smallest detail is as important as the big picture and the depth of heritage and tradition is second to none.  I am truly looking forward to starting work.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/17/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-role-of-black-rod-parliament|title=Sarah Clarke becomes first female Black Rod after 669 years|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=17 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 November 2017|via=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117145639/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/17/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-role-of-black-rod-parliament|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nClarke heads a department that manages the day-to-day business of the House of Lords, and is \"also responsible for business resilience and continuity planning\", and will have about 30 staff, including the [[Yeoman Usher]] and the [[Doorkeeper (Houses of Parliament)|House of Lords doorkeeper]]s.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2017/november/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-the-role-of-black-rod/|title=Sarah Clarke appointed to the role of Black Rod \u2013 News from Parliament|author=|date=|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=17 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117174836/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2017/november/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-the-role-of-black-rod/|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref> She is paid up to \u00a393,000 a year.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Leakey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Black Rod]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Officers of the Lords and Commons}}\n{{Members of the Order of the Garter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen Ushers of the Black Rod]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wolverhampton Girls' High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Roehampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British administrator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Sarah Clarke\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        =\n|imagesize    =\n|alt          =\n|caption      =\n|office       = [[Black Rod|Lady Usher of the Black Rod]]\n|term_start   = 13 February 2018\n|term_end     =\n|monarch      = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|predecessor  = [[David Leakey]]\n|successor    =\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=y|12 October 1965}}\n|birth_place  = [[Wolverhampton]], [[Staffordshire]], England\n|birthname    =\n|nationality  = British\n|spouse       =\n|children     =\n|residence    =\n|alma_mater   = [[Roehampton Institute of Higher Education]] <br /> [[University of Leicester]]\n|occupation   =\n|profession   =\n|portfolio    =\n|religion     =\n|website      =\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Sarah Clarke''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|OBE}} (born 12 October 1965) is a British administrator. Since 13 February 2018, she has served as [[Black Rod]], the first female Black Rod in the 650-year history of the role.  The role is formally \"The Lady Usher of the Black Rod\" (for previous incumbents \"Gentleman Usher of the Black Rod\").<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42025131|title=First female Black Rod in 650 years|date=17 November 2017|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 November 2017|via=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117142439/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42025131|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wimbledon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/articles/2017-11-17/2017-11-17_sarah_clarke_appointed_to_the_role_of_black_road.html|title=Sarah Clarke appointed to the role of Black Rod|website=www.wimbledon.com|accessdate=17 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040159/http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/articles/2017-11-17/2017-11-17_sarah_clarke_appointed_to_the_role_of_black_road.html|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>  Before taking this role, she was in charge of the administration of [[The Championships, Wimbledon]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nClarke was born on 12 October 1965 in [[Wolverhampton]], [[Staffordshire]], England. She was educated at [[Wolverhampton Girls' High School]], a [[grammar school]] in the town. She studied at the [[Roehampton Institute of Higher Education]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Science]] (BSc) degree in 1988: as the institute could not award its own degree, her BSc was validated by the [[University of Surrey]]. She obtained a certificate from the [[The Chartered Institute of Marketing|Institute of Marketing]] in 1993 and a [[Master of Science]] (MSc) degree from the [[University of Leicester]] in 2005.<ref name=\"WW 2019\">{{cite web |title=Clarke, Sarah |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-290330 |website=[[Who's Who 2019]] |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=10 September 2019 |date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Sport===\nPrior to working for Wimbledon, Clarkes first job was working as a tennis tournament organiser for Brian Hewitt Associates in Durham after which she worked on four Olympic Games, including the [[2012 Olympic Games]] in London, the [[London Marathon]], and [[UK Sport]].<ref name=\"wimbledon.com\"/>\n\nClarke was employed by [[The Championships, Wimbledon]] as Championships director, and first worked at Wimbledon as a school-leaver in 1986.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Martin|title=Inside Wimbledon: What really goes on behind the scenes|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2017/07/02/inside-wimbledon-really-goes-behind-scenes/|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=3 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705171215/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2017/07/02/inside-wimbledon-really-goes-behind-scenes/|archivedate=5 July 2017}}</ref>  Interviewed by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' in 2017, she commented on their quest for perfection, \"We live for details.  We love details\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Black Rod===\nClarke succeeded Lieutenant General [[David Leakey]], who retired in February 2018, as [[Black Rod]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Speaking to ''[[The Guardian]]'', Clarke said:\n{{quote|\"Over many years I have been fortunate to work at the heart of some of the world's most complex events and institutions.  To be given the opportunity to join such an experienced and dedicated team is a great privilege.  The House of Lords is a place where the smallest detail is as important as the big picture and the depth of heritage and tradition is second to none.  I am truly looking forward to starting work.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/17/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-role-of-black-rod-parliament|title=Sarah Clarke becomes first female Black Rod after 669 years|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=17 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 November 2017|via=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117145639/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/17/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-role-of-black-rod-parliament|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nClarke heads a department that manages the day-to-day business of the House of Lords, and is \"also responsible for business resilience and continuity planning\", and will have about 30 staff, including the [[Yeoman Usher]] and the [[Doorkeeper (Houses of Parliament)|House of Lords doorkeeper]]s.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2017/november/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-the-role-of-black-rod/|title=Sarah Clarke appointed to the role of Black Rod \u2013 News from Parliament|author=|date=|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=17 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117174836/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2017/november/sarah-clarke-appointed-to-the-role-of-black-rod/|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref> She is paid up to \u00a393,000 a year.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Leakey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Black Rod]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Officers of the Lords and Commons}}\n{{Members of the Order of the Garter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen Ushers of the Black Rod]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wolverhampton Girls' High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Roehampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n", "name_user": "HandsomeFella", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSport", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_Clarke_(Black_Rod)"}
